e=\"background:{{Lutte Ouvri\u00e8re/meta/color}};\"|\n| data-sort-value=\"Arthaud, Nathalie\"| [[Nathalie Arthaud]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 0.64%\n| \u20ac958,237\n| \u20ac4.12\n| \u20ac800,423<ref>{{cite web|title=D\u00e9cision du 21 d\u00e9cembre 2017 relative au compte de campagne de Mme Nathalie ARTHAUD, candidate \u00e0 l'\u00e9lection du Pr\u00e9sident de la R\u00e9publique des 23 avril et 7 mai 2017|url=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000036593733|publisher=L\u00e9gifrance|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=13 February 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Solidarity and Progress/meta/color}};\"|\n| data-sort-value=\"Cheminade, Jacques\"| [[Jacques Cheminade]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 0.18%\n| \u20ac412,983\n| \u20ac6.30\n| \u20ac337,606<ref>{{cite web|title=D\u00e9cision du 21 d\u00e9cembre 2017 relative au compte de campagne de M. Jacques CHEMINADE, candidat \u00e0 l'\u00e9lection du Pr\u00e9sident de la R\u00e9publique des 23 avril et 7 mai 2017|url=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000036593761|publisher=L\u00e9gifrance|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=13 February 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*Elgie, Robert. \"The election of Emmanuel Macron and the new French party system: a return to the \u00e9ternel marais?.\" ''Modern & Contemporary France'' 26.1 (2018): 15\u201329.\n*Gil, Cameron Michael. \"Spatial analysis of La R\u00e9publique En Marche and French Parties, 2002\u20132017.\" ''French Politics'' (2018): 1\u201327.\n*Gougou, Florent, and Simon Persico. \"A new party system in the making? The 2017 French presidential election.\" ''French Politics'' 15.3 (2017): 303\u2013321.\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikinews|Emmanuel Macron wins French presidential election race}}\n{{Commons category|French presidential election (2017)}}\n*[http://presidentielle2017.conseil-constitutionnel.fr/ Constitutional Council] {{in lang|fr}}\n*[http://elections.interieur.gouv.fr/presidentielle-2017/ Ministry of the Interior] {{in lang|fr}}\n*[https://presidentielle2017.conseil-constitutionnel.fr/les-parrainages/tous-les-parrainages/ List of all sponsorships by elected officials] {{in lang|fr}}\n*[https://presidentielle2017.conseil-constitutionnel.fr/les-parrainages/donnees-et-graphiques/ Data and graphics for sponsorships] {{in lang|fr}}\n*[https://www.data.gouv.fr/s/resources/election-presidentielle-des-23-avril-et-7-mai-2017-resultats-definitifs-du-1er-tour-1/20170427-100131/Presidentielle_2017_Resultats_Tour_1_c.xls Results of the first round of the presidential election by constituency] {{in lang|fr}}\n\n{{French elections}}\n{{Candidates in the French presidential election, 2017}}\n\n[[Category:2017 French presidential election| ]]\n[[Category:2017 elections in France]]\n[[Category:April 2017 events in France]]\n[[Category:May 2017 events in France]]\n[[Category:Presidential elections in France|2017]]\n[[Category:2017 establishments in France]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2017 presidential election in France}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name     = 2017 French presidential election\n| country           = France\n| type              = presidential\n| ongoing           = no\n| previous_election = 2012 French presidential election\n| previous_year     = 2012\n| election_date     = 23 April 2017 (first round)<br />7 May 2017 (second round)\n| next_election     = 2022 French presidential election\n| next_year         = 2022\n| image1            = Emmanuel Macron (cropped).jpg\n| colour1           = FFE25A\n| nominee1          = '''[[Emmanuel Macron]]'''\n| party1            = [[En Marche!|EM]]\n| popular_vote1     = '''20,743,128'''\n| percentage1       = '''66.1%'''\n| map_image         = \u00c9lection pr\u00e9sidentielle de 2017 par d\u00e9partement T2.svg\n| map_size          = 250px\n| map_caption       = Results of the second round by department<br />{{color box|#f1c136|border=darkgray}} [[Emmanuel Macron]] {{colorbox|#0d378a|border=darkgray}} [[Marine Le Pen]]\n| title             = President\n| before_election   = [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]]\n| before_party      = Socialist Party (France)\n| after_election    = [[Emmanuel Macron]] \n| after_party       = [[En Marche!|EM]]\n| image1_size       = 190x190px\n| image2            = Le Pen, Marine-9586 (cropped).jpg\n| image2_size       = 190x190px\n| nominee2          = [[Marine Le Pen]]\n| party2            = National Front (France)\n| popular_vote2     = 10,638,475\n| percentage2       = 33.9%\n}}\n\nThe '''2017 French presidential election''' was held on 23 April and 7 May 2017. As no candidate won a majority in the first round on 23 April, a [[two-round system|run-off]] was held between the top two candidates, [[Emmanuel Macron]] of [[En Marche!]] and [[Marine Le Pen]] of the [[National Front (France)|National Front]] (FN), which Macron won by a decisive margin on 7 May. The [[Presidential elections in France|presidential election]] was followed by [[2017 French legislative election|legislative elections]] to elect members of the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]] on 11 and 18 June. Incumbent president [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]] of the [[Socialist Party (France)|Socialist Party]] (PS) was eligible to run for a second term, but declared on 1 December 2016 that he would not seek reelection in light of low approval ratings, making him the first incumbent president of the [[French Fifth Republic|Fifth Republic]] not to seek re-election.\n\n[[Fran\u00e7ois Fillon]] of [[The Republicans (France)|The Republicans]] (LR), after winning [[The Republicans (France) presidential primary, 2016|the party's first open primary]], and Marine Le Pen of the National Front led first-round [[Opinion polling for the French presidential election, 2017|opinion polls]] in November 2016 and mid-January 2017. Polls tightened considerably by late January, and after the publication of revelations that Fillon employed family members in possibly fictitious jobs in a series of politico-financial affairs that came to be colloquially known as \"[[Fillon affair|Penelopegate]]\", Macron overtook Fillon to place consistently second in first-round polling. At the same time, [[Beno\u00eet Hamon]] won the [[French Socialist Party presidential primary, 2017|Socialist primary]], entering fourth place in the polls. After strong debate performances, [[Jean-Luc M\u00e9lenchon]] of [[la France Insoumise]] rose significantly in polls in late March, overtaking Hamon to place just below Fillon.\n\nThe first round was held under a state of emergency that was declared following the [[November 2015 Paris attacks]].<ref>{{cite news|title=La France aux urnes pour le premier tour de la pr\u00e9sidentielle 2017|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2017/04/23/la-france-aux-urnes-pour-le-premier-tour-de-la-presidentielle-2017_5115733_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=23 April 2017|accessdate=28 April 2017}}</ref> Following the result of the first round, Macron and Le Pen continued to the 7 May runoff.<ref name=\"live-20170423\"/> It was the first time since [[2002 French presidential election|2002]] that a National Front candidate continued to the second round and the first time in the history of the Fifth Republic that the runoff did not include a nominee of the traditional left or right parties;<ref>{{cite news|title=Macron et Le Pen au second tour d'une pr\u00e9sidentielle hors norme|url=http://www.sudouest.fr/2017/04/23/macron-et-le-pen-au-second-tour-d-une-presidentielle-hors-norme-3389901-6121.php|agency=Agence France-Presse|newspaper=Sud-Ouest|date=23 April 2017|accessdate=23 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424090214/http://www.sudouest.fr/2017/04/23/macron-et-le-pen-au-second-tour-d-une-presidentielle-hors-norme-3389901-6121.php|archivedate=24 April 2017}}</ref> their combined share of the vote from eligible voters, at approximately 26%, was also a historic low.<ref>{{cite news|author=Maxime Vaudano|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle 2017 : un revers in\u00e9dit dans la Ve R\u00e9publique pour les deux grands partis fran\u00e7ais|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/les-decodeurs/article/2017/04/23/presidentielle-2017-un-revers-inedit-dans-la-ve-republique-pour-les-deux-grands-partis-francais_5115977_4355770.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=23 April 2017|accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nEstimations of the result of the second round on 7 May indicated that Macron had been elected by a decisive margin, and Le Pen immediately conceded defeat.<ref name=\"live-20170507\"/> After the [[Minister of the Interior (France)|Interior Ministry]] published preliminary results, the official result of the second round was proclaimed by the [[Constitutional Council (France)|Constitutional Council]] on 10 May. Overall, 43.6% of the registered electorate voted for Macron; in 2002, by contrast, two-thirds of eligible voters voted against then-FN candidate [[Jean-Marie Le Pen]].<ref>{{cite news|author1=Maxime Vaudano|author2= Adrien S\u00e9n\u00e9cat|author3=El\u00e9a Pommiers|title=Le second tour de la pr\u00e9sidentielle 2017 en 8 chiffres|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/les-decodeurs/article/2017/05/07/le-second-tour-de-la-presidentielle-2017-en-8-chiffres_5123931_4355770.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=7 May 2017|accessdate=18 December 2018}}</ref> When Macron took office on 14 May, he became the youngest president in French history and the youngest French head of state since [[Napoleon]]. He named [[\u00c9douard Philippe]] as [[Prime Minister of France|Prime Minister]] the next day. The [[First Philippe government|initial government]] was assembled on 17 May, and [[2017 French legislative election|legislative elections]] on 11 and 18 June gave Macron a substantial majority.\n\n== Background ==\nThe [[President of France|President of the French Republic]] is elected to a five-year term in a two-round election under Article 7 of the [[Constitution of France|Constitution]]: if no candidate secures an absolute majority of votes in the first round, a second round is held two weeks later between the two candidates who received the most votes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Constitution du 4 octobre 1958  - Article 7|url=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexteArticle.do?idArticle=LEGIARTI000006527463&cidTexte=LEGITEXT000006071194&dateTexte=19621108|publisher=L\u00e9gifrance|accessdate=22 February 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170223125733/https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexteArticle.do?idArticle=LEGIARTI000006527463&cidTexte=LEGITEXT000006071194&dateTexte=19621108|archivedate=23 February 2017}}</ref> In 2017, the first and second rounds were held 23 April and 7 May.<ref name=\"rules\">{{cite news|author=Patrick Roger|title=Parrainages, temps de parole, d\u00e9bats\u2026 Les dates cl\u00e9 de l\u2019\u00e9lection pr\u00e9sidentielle|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2017/02/15/parrainages-temps-de-parole-debats-les-dates-cle-de-l-election-presidentielle_5079909_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=15 February 2017|accessdate=22 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nEach presidential candidate must meet a specific set of [[List of presidential qualifications by country|requirements]] in order to run. They must be a French citizen of at least 18 years old. It is also necessary for candidates to be on an [[electoral roll]], proving their eligibility to vote. \n\nTo be listed on the first-round ballot, candidates must secure 500 signatures<ref>{{Citation|title=D\u00e9cision n\u00b0 81-30 ORGA du Conseil constitutionnel du 24 f\u00e9vrier 1981|url=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000000879634|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref> (often referred to as ''parrainages'') from national or local elected officials from at least 30 different [[departments of France|departments]] or [[overseas collectivity|overseas collectivities]], with no more than a tenth of these signatories from any single department.<ref name=\"parrainages\">{{cite web|title=Concernant les parrainages, qu'est-ce qui a chang\u00e9 depuis 2012 ?|url=http://presidentielle2017.conseil-constitutionnel.fr/tout-savoir/parrainages/concernant-parrainages-quest-a-change-2012/|publisher=Conseil constitutionnel pr\u00e9sidentielle 2017|accessdate=12 February 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203064440/http://presidentielle2017.conseil-constitutionnel.fr/tout-savoir/parrainages/concernant-parrainages-quest-a-change-2012/|archivedate= 3 February 2017}}</ref> The official signature collection period followed the publication of the [[Journal officiel de la R\u00e9publique fran\u00e7aise|''Journal officiel'']] on 25 February to 17 March.<ref name=\"dates\">{{cite news|author=Patrick Roger|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle : que pr\u00e9voit la Constitution en cas de retrait de la candidature de Fillon ?|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2017/02/10/les-dates-cles-d-ici-a-l-election-presidentielle_5077684_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=10 February 2017|accessdate=22 February 2017}}</ref> The collection period had initially been scheduled to begin on 23 February, but a visit by Prime Minister [[Bernard Cazeneuve]] to China on that date forced a delay.<ref>{{cite news|author=S\u00e9bastien Tronche|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle : pourquoi la p\u00e9riode d\u2019ouverture des parrainages est report\u00e9e ? (spoiler : c'est la faute de Cazeneuve)|url=http://lelab.europe1.fr/presidentielle-pourquoi-la-periode-douverture-des-parrainages-est-reportee-spoiler-cest-la-faute-de-cazeneuve-2983682|work=Le Lab|publisher=Europe 1|date=21 February 2017|accessdate=22 February 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170223130408/http://lelab.europe1.fr/presidentielle-pourquoi-la-periode-douverture-des-parrainages-est-reportee-spoiler-cest-la-faute-de-cazeneuve-2983682|archivedate=23 February 2017}}</ref> French prefectures mailed sponsorship forms to the 42,000 elected officials eligible to give their signature to a candidate, which must then be delivered to the [[Constitutional Council (France)|Constitutional Council]] for validation. Unlike in previous years, a list of validated signatures was posted on Tuesday and Thursday of every week on the Council's website; in the past, signatories were published only after the official candidate list had been verified after the end of the collection period. The end of the signature collection period also marked the deadline for the declaration of personal assets required of prospective candidates. The final list of candidates was declared on 21 March.<ref name=\"dates\" />{{bar box\n|float=right\n|title=Speaking time of candidates and supporters from 1&nbsp;February to 10&nbsp;April recorded by the [[Conseil sup\u00e9rieur de l'audiovisuel|CSA]]<ref>{{cite news|author1=Gary Dagorn|author2=Agathe Dahyot|author3=Maxime Vaudano|title=Sondages, temps de parole... suivez la campagne pr\u00e9sidentielle avec quatre indicateurs|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/les-decodeurs/visuel/2017/03/07/sondages-parrainages-meetings-temps-de-parole-quatre-indicateurs-pour-suivre-la-campagne-presidentielle_5090550_4355770.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=7 March 2017|accessdate=14 April 2017}}</ref>\n|width=350px\n|bars=\n{{bar pixel|[[Fran\u00e7ois Fillon|Fillon]]|{{The Republicans (France)/meta/color}}|201||300h58}}\n{{bar pixel|[[Beno\u00eet Hamon|Hamon]]|{{Socialist Party (France)/meta/color}}|171||255h51}}\n{{bar pixel|[[Emmanuel Macron|Macron]]|{{En Marche!/meta/color}}|156||234h03}}\n{{bar pixel|[[Marine Le Pen|Le Pen]]|{{National Front (France)/meta/color}}|153||229h02}}\n{{bar pixel|[[Jean-Luc M\u00e9lenchon|M\u00e9lenchon]]|{{La France Insoumise/meta/color}}|107||160h36}}\n{{bar pixel|[[Nicolas Dupont-Aignan|Dupont-Aignan]]|{{Debout la France/meta/color}}|29||44h00}}\n{{bar pixel|Others|{{Independent/meta/color}}|55||82h33}}\n}}The [[Conseil sup\u00e9rieur de l'audiovisuel]] (CSA) ensured that all candidates receive equal time in broadcast media \"under comparable programming conditions\" from 19 March onward.<ref name=\"rules\" /> The CSA warned on 8 March that the amount of speaking time broadcasters had given Fillon and his supporters was \"unusually high\", even given the unusual circumstances surrounding his candidacy.<ref>{{cite news|title=Temps de parole: le CSA pointe un d\u00e9s\u00e9quilibre en faveur de Fran\u00e7ois Fillon|url=http://www.lcp.fr/afp/le-temps-de-parole-de-fillon-anormalement-eleve-selon-le-csa|agency=Agence France-Presse|publisher=LCP|date=8 March 2017|accessdate=10 March 2017}}</ref> After the official start of the campaign on 10 April, the CSA strictly enforced equal time in broadcast media. Campaigning for the first round of the election ended at midnight on 21 April, two days before the vote. The Constitutional Council verified the results of the first round between the 24\u201326 April and officially certified the vote tallies on 26 April, with the same procedure being used for the second round. The new President of the French Republic was set to be proclaimed on 11 May and undergo their [[French presidential inauguration|investiture ceremony]] on 14 May at the latest.<ref name=\"rules\" />\n{{clear}}\n\n== Candidates ==\nOn 18 March 2017, the [[Constitutional Council (France)|Constitutional Council]] published the names of the 11 candidates who received 500 valid sponsorships, with the order of the list determined by drawing lots.<ref>{{cite web|title=Liste officielle des candidats \u00e0 l'\u00e9lection pr\u00e9sidentielle|url=https://presidentielle2017.conseil-constitutionnel.fr/liste-officielle-des-candidats-a-lelection-presidentielle/|publisher=Conseil constitutionnel pr\u00e9sidentielle 2017|date=18 March 2017|accessdate=18 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170414063724/https://presidentielle2017.conseil-constitutionnel.fr/liste-officielle-des-candidats-a-lelection-presidentielle/|archivedate=14 April 2017}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"width:20%;\"| Candidate name and age,<ref>Per convention, candidates' ages are calculated based on the date of publication of the official list of candidates by the Constitutional Council on 21 March 2017.</ref><br />political party\n! Political office(s)\n! Campaign logo\n! style=\"width:48%;\"| Details\n|-\n| style=\"background:lavender;\"| '''[[Nicolas Dupont-Aignan]]''' ({{Age|1961|3|7|2017|3|21}})<br />[[Debout la France]] (DLF)\n| [[File:Portrait 3 - Flickr - dupontaignan (cropped).jpg|80px|Nicolas Dupont-Aignan]]\n| style=\"background-color:{{Debout la France/meta/color}};\" |\n| '''President of [[Debout la France]]'''<br /><small>(since 2008)</small><br />'''[[Deputies of the 14th National Assembly of France by constituency|Deputy]] for [[Essonne]]'''<br /><small>(since 1997)</small><br />'''[[Mayor (France)|Mayor]] of [[Yerres]]'''<br /><small>(1995-2017)</small>\n| [[File:Nicolas Dupont-Aignan 2017 logo.png|100px|Logo of Nicolas Dupont-Aignan]]\n| A former member of the [[Rally for the Republic|RPR]], [[Rally for France|RPF]], and [[Union for a Popular Movement|UMP]], Dupont-Aignan left the latter party on the eve of the [[2007 French presidential election|2007 presidential election]] due to disagreements with [[Nicolas Sarkozy]]. He subsequently founded the [[souverainism|sovereignist]] political party [[Debout la R\u00e9publique]] (DLR), which was later renamed [[Debout la France]] (DLF) in 2014. He previously stood as a candidate in the [[2012 French presidential election|2012 presidential election]], in which he garnered 1.79% of the vote in the first round. Claiming the mantle of [[Gaullism]], he sought to position himself between [[Marine Le Pen|Le Pen]] and [[Fran\u00e7ois Fillon|Fillon]].<ref name=\"candidates\">{{cite news|title=Qui sont les candidats pour la pr\u00e9sidentielle 2017 ?|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2017/03/18/deux-femmes-neuf-hommes-qui-sont-les-candidats-qualifies-pour-l-election-presidentielle_5096791_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=18 March 2017|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref> Five days after his elimination in the first round, he announced his support for Le Pen in the second round.<ref name=\"NDA-MLP\">{{cite news|title=Nicolas Dupont-Aignan soutient Marine Le Pen pour le second tour|url=http://www.bfmtv.com/politique/nicolas-dupont-aignan-a-annonce-son-soutien-a-marine-le-pen-1153182.html|publisher=BFM TV|date=28 April 2017|accessdate=28 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428224852/http://www.bfmtv.com/politique/nicolas-dupont-aignan-a-annonce-son-soutien-a-marine-le-pen-1153182.html|archivedate=28 April 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:lavender;\"| '''[[Marine Le Pen]]''' ({{Age|1968|8|5|2017|3|21}})<br />[[National Front (France)|National Front]] (FN)\n| [[File:Marine Le Pen (2017-03-24) 01 cropped.jpg|80px|Marine Le Pen]]\n| style=\"background-color:{{National Front (France)/meta/color}};\" |\n| '''President of the [[National Front (France)|National Front]]'''<br /><small>(2011\u201317)</small><br />'''[[Member of European Parliament|MEP]] for [[North-West France (European Parliament constituency)|North-West France]]'''<br /><small>(since 2004)</small>\n| [[File:Marine Le Pen 2017 logo.png|140px|Logo of Marine Le Pen]]\n| When Le Pen, a former lawyer, stood in the [[2012 French presidential election|2012 presidential election]], she came in third with 17.90% of first-round votes. She rose within the ranks of the [[National Front (France)|National Front]] (FN), founded and previously led by her father [[Jean-Marie Le Pen]], culminating in a bitter leadership struggle which she won in 2011. Her campaign program prioritized the national interests of France and an exit from the [[eurozone]],<ref name=\"candidates\"/> and emphasized her party's traditional concern about security and immigration, as well as socioeconomic issues and the sovereignty of the French state, on matters of currency, borders, the economy, and the rule of law.<ref name=\"candidates-figaro\">{{cite news|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle : qui sont les 11 candidats sur la ligne de d\u00e9part|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/elections/presidentielles/2017/03/18/35003-20170318ARTFIG00052-presidentielle-qui-sont-les-11-candidats-sur-la-ligne-de-depart.php|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=18 March 2017|accessdate=19 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170318141422/http://www.lefigaro.fr/elections/presidentielles/2017/03/18/35003-20170318ARTFIG00052-presidentielle-qui-sont-les-11-candidats-sur-la-ligne-de-depart.php|archivedate=18 March 2017}}</ref> Her campaign was punctuated by [[#FN use of European Parliament assistants|judicial inquiries into her party]] and personal associates.<ref name=\"candidates\"/>\n|-\n| style=\"background:lavender;\"| '''[[Emmanuel Macron]]''' ({{Age|1977|12|21|2017|3|21}})<br />[[En Marche!]] (EM)\n|[[File:Emmanuel Macron in Tallinn Digital Summit. Welcome dinner hosted by HE Donald Tusk. Handshake (36669381364) (cropped).jpg|109x109px]]\n| style=\"background-color:{{En Marche!/meta/color}};\" |\n| '''President of [[En Marche!]]'''<br /><small>(2016\u201317)</small><br />'''[[French Ministry for the Economy and Finance|Minister of the Economy, Industry, and Digital Affairs]]'''<br /><small>(2014\u201316)</small>\n| [[File:Logo En Marche !.svg|140px|Logo of En Marche!]]\n| The youngest candidate in the race and a former [[French Ministry for the Economy and Finance|economy minister]] who had never run for elected office, Macron described himself as \"neither of the right nor the left\". He was appointed deputy secretary-general of the [[\u00c9lys\u00e9e]] in 2012 and became economy minister in 2014, lending his name to the \"Macron law\" to promote economic growth and opportunities. He founded the [[En Marche!]] movement in April 2016 before resigning from the cabinet on 30 August.<ref name=\"candidates\"/> The most explicitly pro-European of the candidates, Macron intends to implement reforms to modernize the French economy.<ref name=\"candidates-figaro\"/> Macron secured support across the political spectrum, but primarily among liberal-leaning figures;<ref>{{cite news|author1=Anne-A\u00ebl Durand|author2=Pierre Breteau|title=Gauche, centre, droite, milieux \u00e9conomiques ou soci\u00e9t\u00e9 civile : qui sont les soutiens d\u2019Emmanuel Macron ?|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/les-decodeurs/article/2017/03/09/gauche-centre-droite-milieux-economiques-ou-societe-civile-qui-sont-les-soutiens-d-emmanuel-macron_5092220_4355770.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=9 March 2017|accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref> notable supporters include perennial centrist candidate [[Fran\u00e7ois Bayrou]], president of the [[Democratic Movement (France)|Democratic Movement]] (MoDem),<ref name=\"Bayrou\"/> and [[Minister of Defence (France)|Minister of Defence]] [[Jean-Yves Le Drian]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Exclusif. Le Drian annonce son soutien \u00e0 Macron ce jeudi|url=http://www.ouest-france.fr/elections/presidentielle/exclusif-jean-yves-le-drian-annonce-son-soutien-emmanuel-macron-4878523|newspaper=Ouest-France|date=23 March 2017|accessdate=3 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170329114947/http://www.ouest-france.fr/elections/presidentielle/exclusif-jean-yves-le-drian-annonce-son-soutien-emmanuel-macron-4878523|archivedate=29 March 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:lavender;\"| '''[[Beno\u00eet Hamon]]''' ({{Age|1967|6|26|2017|3|21}})<br />[[Socialist Party (France)|Socialist Party]] (PS)\n|[[File:2015-03-18 20-21-20 meeting-soc-belfort (cropped).jpg|80px|Beno\u00eet Hamon]]\n| style=\"background-color:{{Socialist Party (France)/meta/color}};\" |\n| '''[[Deputies of the 14th National Assembly of France by constituency|Deputy]] for [[Yvelines]]'''<br /><small>(2012 and since 2014)</small>\n{{Hidden|Other offices|\n* [[Ministry of National Education (France)|Minister of National Education, Higher Education and Research]] in 2014\n* [[French Ministry for the Economy and Finance|Deputy Minister of the Economy and Finance]] responsible for Consumer Affairs and the Social and Solidarity Economy from 2012 to 2014\n* Deputy Minister of the Economy, Finance, and Foreign Trade responsible for the Social and Solidarity Economy in 2012\n* [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]] for [[East France (European Parliament constituency)|East France]] from 2004 to 2009}}\n| [[File:Logo candidature Hamon 2017.svg|160px|Logo of Beno\u00eet Hamon]]\n| Hamon, a left-wing critic of [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande|Hollande]]'s government, was the surprise winner of the [[French Socialist Party presidential primary, 2017|Socialist primary]] in January 2017, defeating former [[Prime Minister of France|Prime Minister]] [[Manuel Valls]]. Hamon's primary victory was driven in part by his support for a [[basic income|universal basic income]], which remained integral to his program. He negotiated the withdrawal and support of [[Yannick Jadot]] of [[Europe Ecology \u2013 The Greens]] (EELV) in February, becoming the joint candidate of both parties.<ref name=\"candidates\"/> He also advocated for the legalization of cannabis and reforming the structure of government to a \"Sixth Republic\".<ref name=\"candidates-figaro\"/> He endorsed [[Emmanuel Macron]] in the second round.<ref name=\"live-20170423\"/>\n|-\n| style=\"background:lavender;\"| '''[[Nathalie Arthaud]]''' ({{Age|1970|2|23|2017|3|21}})<br />[[Lutte Ouvri\u00e8re]] (LO)\n| [[File:2017-02-11 16-10-22 meeting-lo-belfort (cropped).jpg|80px|Nathalie Arthaud]]\n| style=\"background-color:{{Lutte Ouvri\u00e8re/meta/color}};\" |\n| '''Spokesperson of [[Lutte Ouvri\u00e8re]]'''<br /><small>(since 2008)</small>\n|\n| Arthaud first ran for the presidency in the [[2012 French presidential election|2012 election]] under the LO banner, receiving 0.56% of votes in the first round. A professor of economics, she described the objective of her candidacy as being to, \"make the workers' voice heard\", hoping to \"allow workers, the unemployed, and exploited to defend their interests, as opposed to [those who pocketed] millions and millions\".<ref name=\"candidates\"/> She claims that she is the only communist candidate, and wants to see borders disappear and overthrow capitalism.<ref name=\"candidates-figaro\"/> She intended to cast a [[protest vote|blank vote]] in the second round.<ref name=\"live-20170423\"/>\n|-\n| style=\"background:lavender;\"| '''[[Philippe Poutou]]''' ({{Age|1967|3|14|2017|3|21}})<br />[[New Anticapitalist Party]] (NPA)\n| [[File:Philippe Poutou 2011 (cropped).jpg|80px|Philippe Poutou]]\n| style=\"background-color:{{New Anticapitalist Party/meta/color}};\" |\n| '''Spokesperson of the [[New Anticapitalist Party]]'''<br /><small>(since 2009)</small>\n|\n| A long-time radical left-wing activist,  as well as a trade unionist and Ford mechanic in [[Blanquefort, Gironde|Blanquefort]], Poutou led opposition to the shutdown of the local factory. He also ran in the [[2012 French presidential election|2012 presidential election]], obtaining 1.15% of votes. He launched his political activities at [[Lutte Ouvri\u00e8re]] before joining the [[Revolutionary Communist League (France)|Revolutionary Communist League]] (LCR) which became the NPA in 2009.<ref name=\"candidates\"/> With Marxist and anarchist roots, he crusades against capitalism and espouses radical-left ideas.<ref name=\"candidates-figaro\"/> He offered no voting instructions to his supporters for the second round.<ref name=\"live-20170423\"/>\n|-\n| style=\"background:lavender;\"| '''[[Jacques Cheminade]]''' ({{Age|1941|8|20|2017|3|21}})<br />[[Solidarity and Progress]] (S&P)\n| [[File:Jacques-Cheminade 2.jpg|80px|Jacques Cheminade]]\n| style=\"background-color:{{Solidarity and Progress/meta/color}};\" |\n| '''President of [[Solidarity and Progress]]'''<br /><small>(since 1996)</small>\n| [[File:Logo candidature Cheminade 2017.svg|140px|Logo of Jacques Cheminade]]\n| Cheminade founded [[Solidarity and Progress]] in 1996 and is the figurehead of the [[LaRouche movement]] in France. He proposes leaving [[NATO]], the [[European Union|EU]], the [[eurozone]], and returning to the [[French franc|franc]]. He supports [[colonization of the Moon]] to facilitate [[exploration of Mars]]. He was a candidate twice before, in [[1995 French presidential election|1995]] and [[2012 French presidential election|2012]], collecting 0.28% and 0.25% of the vote, respectively, but failed to appear on the ballot in 1981, 1988, 2002, and 2007.<ref name=\"candidates\"/> His position on the second round is unclear,<ref name=\"live-20170423\"/> only specifying that he, personally, would not cast a vote for Le Pen while also denouncing the forces of \"financial occupation\".<ref name=\"Cheminade\">{{cite news|title=Fillon, M\u00e9lenchon, Hamon, Poutou... Quelle est la consigne de vote des neuf \u00e9limin\u00e9s en vue du second tour ?|url=http://www.francetvinfo.fr/elections/presidentielle/fillon-melenchon-hamon-poutou-quelle-est-la-consigne-de-vote-des-neuf-elimines-en-vue-du-second-tour_2158950.html|publisher=franceinfo|date=24 April 2017|accessdate=7 May 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428211325/http://www.francetvinfo.fr/elections/presidentielle/fillon-melenchon-hamon-poutou-quelle-est-la-consigne-de-vote-des-neuf-elimines-en-vue-du-second-tour_2158950.html|archivedate=28 April 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:lavender;\"| '''[[Jean Lassalle]]''' ({{Age|1955|5|3|2017|3|21}})<br />[[R\u00e9sistons!]]\n| [[File:MoDem regional elections 2010-01-24 n06.jpg|80px|Jean Lassalle]]\n| style=\"background:{{Miscellaneous right/meta/color}};\"|\n| '''[[Deputies of the 14th National Assembly of France by constituency|Deputy]] for the [[Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques]]'''<br /><small>(since 2002)</small><br />'''[[Mayor (France)|Mayor]] of [[Lourdios-Ich\u00e8re]]'''<br /><small>(since 1977)</small>\n| [[File:Jean Lassalle 2017 logo.png|140px|Logo of Jean Lassalle]]\n| Lassalle, a former member of the [[Democratic Movement (France)|Democratic Movement]] (MoDem) and associate of [[Fran\u00e7ois Bayrou]] running under the banner of ''Resistons !'', considered himself the \"defender of rural territories and a humanist ecology\". He became famous for a successful 39-day [[hunger strike]] protesting the movement of the [[Total S.A.|Total]] factory from [[Accous]] to the [[Lacq gas field|Lacq basin]] {{convert|65|km|mi|abbr=on}} away. In 2013, he walked {{convert|6000|km|mi|abbr=on}} on foot to \"meet the French\".<ref name=\"candidates\"/> He opted to cast a [[protest vote|blank vote]] in the second round.<ref name=\"Lassalle-blanc\"/>\n|-\n| style=\"background:lavender;\"| '''[[Jean-Luc M\u00e9lenchon]]''' ({{Age|1951|8|19|2017|3|21}})<br />[[La France Insoumise]] (FI)\n| [[File:Meeting M\u00e9lenchon Toulouse - 2017-04-16 - Jean-Luc M\u00e9lenchon - 41 (cropped 2).jpg|80px|Jean-Luc M\u00e9lenchon]]\n| style=\"background-color:{{La France Insoumise/meta/color}};\" |\n| '''[[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]] for [[South-West France (European Parliament constituency)|South-West France]]'''<br /><small>(since 2009)</small>\n{{Hidden|Other offices|\n* President, then co-president of the [[Left Party (France)|Left Party]] from 2009 to 2014\n* [[Senate (France)|Senator]] for [[Essonne]] from 1986 to 2000 and from 2004 to 2010\n* [[Ministry of National Education (France)|Deputy Minister of Vocational Education]] from 2000 to 2002}}\n| [[File:Jean-Luc M\u00e9lenchon 2017 logo.png|140px|Logo of Jean-Luc M\u00e9lenchon]]\n| Denouncing the \"liberal drift\" of the party, M\u00e9lenchon left the [[Socialist Party (France)|PS]] in 2008 to found the [[Left Party (France)|Left Party]]. He made a previous presidential run in [[2012 French presidential election|2012]], coming in fourth with 11.10% of votes,<ref name=\"candidates\"/> with the backing of the [[French Communist Party]] (PCF). A perennial critic of the [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande|Hollande]] government, he launched his 2017 bid without consulting the PCF, instead choosing to start his own movement, [[la France Insoumise]] (FI).<ref name=\"candidates-figaro\"/> He later won the PCF's support by a narrow margin.<ref>{{cite news|title=Les militants communistes votent \u00e0 53,6% en faveur d'un soutien \u00e0 Jean-Luc M\u00e9lenchon pour l'\u00e9lection pr\u00e9sidentielle|url=http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/melenchon/les-militants-communistes-votent-a-53-6-en-faveur-d-un-soutien-a-jean-luc-melenchon-pour-l-election-presidentielle_1940593.html|agency=Agence France-Presse; Reuters|publisher=franceinfo|date=26 November 2016|accessdate=17 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161219004435/http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/melenchon/les-militants-communistes-votent-a-53-6-en-faveur-d-un-soutien-a-jean-luc-melenchon-pour-l-election-presidentielle_1940593.html|archivedate=19 December 2016}}</ref> His program underlined left-wing and environmental principles,<ref name=\"candidates\"/> including the establishment of a Sixth Republic, redistribution of wealth, renegotiating [[European Union|EU]] treaties, environmental planning, and protecting the independence of France, namely from the [[United States]].<ref name=\"candidates-figaro\"/> He ran an innovative campaign, gathering a large following on social media,<ref>{{cite news|author=Marc de Boni|title=M\u00e9lenchon poursuit sa strat\u00e9gie gagnante sur YouTube|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/elections/presidentielles/2017/01/09/35003-20170109ARTFIG00246-melenchon-poursuit-sa-strategie-gagnante-sur-youtube.php|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=9 January 2017|accessdate=17 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170409073634/http://www.lefigaro.fr/elections/presidentielles/2017/01/09/35003-20170109ARTFIG00246-melenchon-poursuit-sa-strategie-gagnante-sur-youtube.php|archivedate= 9 April 2017}}</ref> and holding simultaneous meetings in multiple cities via hologram.<ref>{{cite news|author=Florian Maussion|title=VIDEO. Hologramme : et soudain Jean-Luc M\u00e9lenchon se d\u00e9doubla...|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/elections/presidentielle/l-hologramme-de-jean-luc-melenchon-en-meeting-comment-ca-marche-05-02-2017-6656853.php|newspaper=Le Parisien|date=5 February 2017|accessdate=17 April 2017}}</ref> He intended to consult with his movement before making any pronouncement on the second round.<ref name=\"live-20170423\"/> After a few days, he stated that he would not vote for the FN, but never explicitly provided any further voting instructions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jean-Luc M\u00e9lenchon \" ne votera pas FN \" mais ne donne pas de consigne de vote|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2017/04/28/jean-luc-melenchon-ne-votera-pas-front-national-mais-ne-donne-pas-de-consigne-de-vote_5119675_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=28 April 2017|accessdate=15 May 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:lavender;\"| '''[[Fran\u00e7ois Asselineau]]''' ({{Age|1957|9|14|2017|3|21}})<br />[[Popular Republican Union (2007)|Popular Republican Union]] (UPR)\n| [[File:Fran\u00e7ois ASSELINEAU.jpg|80px|Fran\u00e7ois Asselineau]]\n| style=\"background-color:{{Popular Republican Union/meta/color}};\" |\n| '''President of the [[Popular Republican Union (2007)|UPR]]'''<br /><small>(since 2007)</small>\n| [[File:Fran\u00e7ois Asselineau 2017 logo.png|140px|Logo of Fran\u00e7ois Asselineau]]\n| A [[souverainism|sovereignist]], Asselineau surprised political observers with his ability to secure the 500 sponsorships required to stand as a candidate. Formerly of the [[Rally for France|RPF]] and [[Union for a Popular Movement|UMP]], he founded the [[Popular Republican Union (2007)|Popular Republican Union]] (UPR) in 2007 and has agitated for the French to exit from the [[European Union|EU]].<ref name=\"candidates\"/> Sometimes classified as a far-right Eurosceptic, he has denounced \"American imperialism\" and proposed leaving [[NATO]].<ref name=\"candidates-figaro\"/> He offered no endorsement in the second round.<ref name=\"live-20170423\"/>\n|-\n| style=\"background:lavender;\"| '''[[Fran\u00e7ois Fillon]]''' ({{Age|1954|3|4|2017|3|21}})<br />[[The Republicans (France)|The Republicans]] (LR)\n| [[File:Fran\u00e7ois Fillon 2010 (cropped).jpg|80px|Fran\u00e7ois Fillon]]\n| style=\"background-color:{{The Republicans (France)/meta/color}};\" |\n| '''[[Deputies of the 14th National Assembly of France by constituency|Deputy]] for [[Paris]]'''<br /><small>(since 2012)</small><br />'''[[Prime Minister of France|Prime Minister]]'''<br /><small>(2007\u201312)</small>\n{{Hidden|Other offices|\n* Co-president of the [[Union for a Popular Movement]] ''(interim)'' in 2014\n* President of the [[Rassemblement-UMP|Rassemblement-UMP group]] in the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]] from 2012 to 2013\n* [[Ministry of Ecology, Sustainable Development and Energy|Minister of Ecology, Sustainable Development, Transport]] and [[Minister of Housing and Territorial Equality (France)|Housing]] in 2012\n* [[National Assembly (France)|Deputy]] for the [[Sarthe]] from 1981 to 1993, from 1997 to 2002 and in 2007\n* [[Senate (France)|Senator]] for the [[Sarthe]] in 2004 and from 2005 to 2007\n* [[Ministry of National Education (France)|Minister of National Education, Higher Education and Research]] from 2004 to 2005\n* [[Minister of Social Affairs (France)|Minister of Social Affairs, Labour and Solidarity]] from 2002 to 2004\n* [[President of the Regional Council (France)|President]] of the [[Regional council (France)|regional council]] of [[Pays de la Loire]] from 1998 to 2002\n* [[Mayor (France)|Mayor]] of [[Sabl\u00e9-sur-Sarthe]] from 1983 to 2001\n* [[President of the General Council|President]] of the [[Departmental councils (France)|general council]] of the [[Sarthe]] from 1992 to 1998\n* Deputy Minister responsible for [[Minister of Posts, Telegraphs, and Telephones|Post, Telecommunications and Space]] from 1995 to 1997\n* [[Minister of Posts, Telegraphs, and Telephones|Minister of Information Technology and Post]] in 1995\n* [[Ministry of National Education (France)|Minister of Higher Education and Research]] from 1993 to 1995}}\n| [[File:Fran\u00e7ois Fillon 2017 logo.png|80px|Logo of Fran\u00e7ois Fillon]]\n| Fillon led a prolific political career starting from the early 1970s. The surprise winner of the [[The Republicans (France) presidential primary, 2016|primary of the right]] offered a liberal economic program ending the [[35-hour workweek]], dismissing 500,000 civil servants, abolishing the [[solidarity tax on wealth|wealth tax]] (ISF), streamlining the labour code, and reforming the [[Health care in France#Health insurance|health insurance system]]. However, his campaign was hobbled in January 2017 following the publication of allegations of fictitious employment of family members, including his wife, collectively known as \"[[Fillon affair|Penelopegate]]\". He initially said he would drop his bid if placed under formal investigation, but continued his candidacy after such investigations began on 15 March.<ref name=\"candidates\"/> He endorsed [[Emmanuel Macron]] in the second round.<ref name=\"live-20170423\"/>\n|}\n\n=== Sponsorships ===\nA candidate must secure 500 signatures from elected officials in order to appear on the first-round ballot,<ref name=\"parrainages\"/> with the signature collection period ending on 17 March.<ref name=\"dates\"/> The table below lists sponsorships received by the Constitutional Council by candidate.<ref name=\"parrainages-par-candidat\">{{cite web|title=Les parrainages par candidat|url=https://presidentielle2017.conseil-constitutionnel.fr/les-parrainages/parrainages-par-candidat/|publisher=Conseil constitutionnel pr\u00e9sidentielle 2017|date=18 March 2017|accessdate=18 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n;Colour legend\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:650px;table-layout:fixed;overflow:visible;text-align:center;font-size:85%;\"\n|- style=\"height:15px;\"\n| style=\"border:1px solid black; background:#EAAAAA;\" | \n| style=\"border:1px solid black; background:#EEBAAB;\" | \n| style=\"border:1px solid black; background:#F2CBAC;\" | \n| style=\"border:1px solid black; background:#F6DBAD;\" | \n| style=\"border:1px solid black; background:#FAECAE;\" | \n| style=\"border:1px solid black; background:#FFFDB0;\" | \n| style=\"border:1px solid black; background:#EAF5AB;\" | \n| style=\"border:1px solid black; background:#D5EDA7;\" | \n| style=\"border:1px solid black; background:#C0E5A3;\" | \n| style=\"border:1px solid black; background:#ABDD9F;\" | \n| style=\"border:1px solid black; background:#97D59B;\" | \n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| 1\u201350 || 51\u2013100 || 101\u2013150 || 151\u2013200 || 201\u2013250 || 251\u2013300 || 301\u2013350 || 351\u2013400 || 401\u2013450 || 451\u2013500 || 500+\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:95%;text-align:right;\"\n|+ Signatures received by the Constitutional Council as of 18 March<ref name=\"parrainages-par-candidat\"/>\n|-\n!colspan=2|Candidate\n!Party\n!1 Mar\n!3 Mar\n!7 Mar\n!10 Mar\n!14 Mar\n!18 Mar\n!Total\n!Notes\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:{{Miscellaneous right/meta/color}};\"|\n|data-sort-value=\"Alliot-Marie, Mich\u00e8le\" style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie]]\n|[[Miscellaneous right|DVD]]\n|4\n|4\n|18\n|12\n|15\n|21\n|style=\"background:#EEBAAB;\"|74\n|\n|- style=\"background-color:#C5F199\"\n|style=\"background-color:{{Workers' Struggle/meta/color}};\"|\n|data-sort-value=\"Arthaud, Nathalie\" style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Nathalie Arthaud]]\n|[[Lutte Ouvri\u00e8re|LO]]\n|201\n|113\n|243\n|36\n|30\n|14\n|style=\"ba