=6 March 2017|accessdate=7 March 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:{{Independent/meta/color}};\"|\n|data-sort-value=\"Vergne, Michel\" style=\"text-align:left;\"|Michel Vergne\n|[[Sans \u00e9tiquette|SE]]\n|0\n|1\n|0\n|1\n|0\n|1\n|style=\"background:#EAAAAA;\"|3\n|Non-candidate; sponsored by friend as a joke<ref>{{cite news|author=J\u00e9r\u00f4me Schrepf|title=Un maire parraine un ami \u00e0 la pr\u00e9sidentielle, pour lui faire \"une blague\"|url=http://www.ladepeche.fr/article/2017/03/06/2530248-maire-pinel-hauterive-parraine-ami-presidentielle-faire-blague.html|date=6 March 2017|accessdate=9 March 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:{{Independent Ecological Movement/meta/color}};\"|\n|data-sort-value=\"Waechter, Antoine\" style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Antoine Waechter]]\n|[[Independent Ecological Movement|MEI]]\n|1\n|0\n|1\n|2\n|2\n|5\n|style=\"background:#EAAAAA;\"|11\n|\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:{{The Republicans (France)/meta/color}};\"|\n|data-sort-value=\"Wauquiez, Laurent\" style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Laurent Wauquiez]]\n|[[The Republicans (France)|LR]]\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|1\n|style=\"background:#EAAAAA;\"|1\n|Not a candidate\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:{{Miscellaneous right/meta/color}};\"|\n|data-sort-value=\"Yade, Rama\" style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Rama Yade]]\n|[[Miscellaneous right|DVD]]\n|8\n|21\n|84\n|38\n|66\n|136\n|style=\"background:#D5EDA7;\"|353\n|\n|-\n!colspan=3|Total\n!1,717\n!1,438\n!4,626\n!1,442\n!2,589\n!2,484\n!11,812\n!\n|}\n\n== Non-candidates ==\n=== Socialist Party (PS) ===\nThe 2017 presidential election was the first in the history of the [[French Fifth Republic|Fifth Republic]] in which a sitting president did not seek a second term. On 1 December 2016, incumbent president [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]], acknowledging his low approval ratings, announced he would not seek a second term. His then-[[Prime Minister of France|Prime Minister]] [[Manuel Valls]] declared on 5 December 2016 that he would run in the [[French Socialist Party presidential primary, 2017|Socialist primary]] on 22 January 2017,<ref name=\"Valls\">{{cite news|author1=Kocila Makdeche|author2=Yann Thompson|author3=Camille Caldini|title=DIRECT. \"Je quitterai mes fonctions d\u00e8s demain\", d\u00e9clare Manuel Valls \u00e0 Evry|url=http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/ps/primaire-a-gauche/presidentielle-manuel-valls-annoncera-sa-candidature-a-la-primaire-de-la-gauche-cet-apres-midi-a-evry-suivez-notre-direct_1953857.html|publisher=franceinfo|date=5 December 2016|accessdate=22 February 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170210153431/http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/ps/primaire-a-gauche/presidentielle-manuel-valls-annoncera-sa-candidature-a-la-primaire-de-la-gauche-cet-apres-midi-a-evry-suivez-notre-direct_1953857.html|archivedate=10 February 2017}}</ref> but he was defeated by Beno\u00eet Hamon in its second round on 29 January.<ref>{{cite news|title=R\u00e9sultats de la primaire \u00e0 gauche : Beno\u00eet Hamon l\u2019emporte largement face \u00e0 Manuel Valls|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/primaire-de-la-gauche/article/2017/01/29/primaire-a-gauche-benoit-hamon-l-emporte-largement-face-a-manuel-valls_5071066_5008374.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=29 January 2017|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Democratic Movement (MoDem) ===\n[[File:BayrouEM.jpg|thumb|right|180px|Fran\u00e7ois Bayrou in 2006]]\n[[Fran\u00e7ois Bayrou]], the three-time centrist presidential candidate and leader of the [[Democratic Movement (France)|Democratic Movement]] (MoDem) \u2013 who came fourth in [[2002 French presidential election|2002]], third in [[2007 French presidential election|2007]], and fifth in [[2012 French presidential election|2012]] \u2013 initially supported the candidacy of [[Alain Jupp\u00e9]] in [[The Republicans (France) presidential primary, 2016|the primary of the right]] against his long-time adversary [[Nicolas Sarkozy]], whom he vowed to run against if he won the primary.<ref>{{cite news|author=Enora Ollivier|title=Les trois pr\u00e9sidentielles de Fran\u00e7ois Bayrou|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2017/02/22/les-trois-presidentielles-de-francois-bayrou_5083376_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=22 February 2017|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref> However, Fillon's victory in the primary \u2013 which saw the elimination of Sarkozy in the first round and the defeat of Jupp\u00e9 in the runoff \u2013 led Bayrou to reconsider lodging a bid for the presidency, despite his [[2014 French municipal elections#Pau|2014 election]] promise during his successful mayoral campaign in [[Pau, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques|Pau]] that he would not seek the presidency if he won. After an extended period of suspense, he finally announced on 22 February that he would not run for a fourth time, instead proposing a conditional alliance with [[Emmanuel Macron]], who accepted his offer.<ref name=\"Bayrou\">{{cite news|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle : Bayrou et Macron, une alliance sous conditions|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2017/02/22/presidentielle-fin-du-suspense-autour-de-la-candidature-de-francois-bayrou_5083592_4854003.html|agency=Agence France-Presse|newspaper=Le Monde|date=22 February 2017|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Europe Ecology \u2013 The Greens (EELV)===\nOn 9 July 2016, [[Europe Ecology \u2013 The Greens]] (EELV) announced that it would hold a primary election before the 2017 presidential election. Those wishing to be nominated required the support of 36 of its \"federal councilors\" out of 240; nominations were open to individuals in civic society as well. The vote was open to both party members as well as sympathizers who could register to vote in the primary. The announcement came just days after prominent environmentalist [[Nicolas Hulot]]'s surprise declaration that he would not offer himself as a presidential candidate on 5 July.<ref>{{cite news|title=EELV annonce une primaire \u00e0 la fin octobre en vue de la pr\u00e9sidentielle|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2016/07/09/eelv-annonce-une-primaire-fin-octobre-en-vue-de-la-presidentielle_4966987_4854003.html|agency=Agence France-Presse|newspaper=Le Monde|date=9 July 2016|accessdate=24 February 2017}}</ref> EELV were the first party to hold a presidential primary for the 2017 election, with two rounds held on 19 October and 7 November 2016. It was contested by [[National Assembly (France)|deputy]], former [[Minister of Housing and Territorial Equality (France)|Minister of Territorial Equality and Housing]], and ex-party leader [[C\u00e9cile Duflot]], as well as three [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]]s \u2013 [[Karima Delli]], [[Yannick Jadot]], and [[Mich\u00e8le Rivasi]].<ref name=\"primaire-\u00e9colo\">{{cite news|author=Rapha\u00eblle Besse Desmouli\u00e8res|title=Primaire \u00e9colo : quatre candidats pour une investiture|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2016/08/31/primaire-ecolo-quatre-candidats-pour-une-investiture_4990637_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=31 August 2016|accessdate=24 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:EELV 2016 vote primaire.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Voting materials for the first round of the ecologist primary]]\n\nDuflot was considered the early favorite, though she initially opposed holding a primary, aware of the risk that she might lose it; and highlighted her experience in government. Her main proposal was to incorporate the fight against climate change into the [[Constitution of France|Constitution]]. Jadot was perceived as her main challenger; elected as an MEP in 2009, he worked with [[Greenpeace|Greenpeace France]] from 2002 to 2008, specializing in transatlantic trade and climate issues. With [[Thomas Piketty]] and [[Daniel Cohn-Bendit]], he sought a \"primary of all the left\", which failed to materialize. He rejected the \"candidacy awaited by the political-media world\" \u2013 that of Duflot, among others \u2013 and represented an anti-Duflot force from the party's right wing. Rivasi only barely managed to qualify for the primary, earlier lacking the necessary sponsorships. Like Jadot, she represented the radical wing of the party \u2013 albeit on its left flank \u2013 and served as deputy for [[Dr\u00f4me]] from 1997 to 2002 and led Greenpeace France from 2003 to 2004. Delli, the daughter of Algerian immigrants, first became involved in politics as part of collective movements, and sought to become an MEP in 2009 after a stint as parliamentary assistant to [[Marie-Christine Blandin]]. Also of the party's left-wing, she declared that she would defend a \"popular ecology\".<ref name=\"primaire-\u00e9colo\"/>\n\nJadot and Rivasi advanced to the runoff after scoring 35.61% and 30.16%, respectively, in the first round; the other two candidates were eliminated, with Duflot garnering 24.41% and Delli 9.82%. Jadot won the second round of the primary on 7 November, obtaining 54.25% of the vote against Rivasi's 40.75%, becoming the nominee of the EELV in the presidential election.<ref>{{cite news|author=S\u00e9bastien Tronche|title=Yannick Jadot \u00e9lu candidat d\u2019EELV face \u00e0 Mich\u00e8le Rivasi pour la pr\u00e9sidentielle de 2017|url=http://lelab.europe1.fr/yannick-jadot-elu-candidat-deelv-face-a-michele-rivasi-pour-la-presidentielle-de-2017-2893619|work=Le Lab|publisher=Europe 1|date=7 November 2016|accessdate=24 February 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170225130301/http://lelab.europe1.fr/yannick-jadot-elu-candidat-deelv-face-a-michele-rivasi-pour-la-presidentielle-de-2017-2893619|archivedate=25 February 2017}}</ref> Jadot, who claimed 496 sponsorships just before the opening of the collection period,<ref>{{cite news|author1=Bastien Bonnefous|author2=Rapha\u00eblle Besse Desmouli\u00e8res|title=Beno\u00eet Hamon et Yannick Jadot tardent \u00e0 c\u00e9l\u00e9brer leur mariage|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2017/02/21/benoit-hamon-et-yannick-jadot-tardent-a-celebrer-leur-mariage_5082933_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=21 February 2017|accessdate=22 February 2017}}</ref> withdrew his candidacy on 23 February and endorsed Hamon, the pair having agreed on a common platform.<ref name=\"Jadot-withdraw\">{{cite news|title=Yannick Jadot se retire de la course \u00e0 la pr\u00e9sidentielle et rallie Beno\u00eet Hamon|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2017/02/23/yannick-jadot-se-retire-de-la-course-a-la-presidentielle-et-rallie-benoit-hamon_5084560_4854003.html|agency=Agence France-Presse|newspaper=Le Monde|date=23 February 2017|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref> An online vote among EELV primary voters from 24 and 26 February was required to confirm the agreement; an earlier vote to open talks with Hamon and M\u00e9lenchon was approved by 89.7% of those electors.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle : le candidat \u00e9cologiste Yannick Jadot retire sa candidature en faveur de Beno\u00eet Hamon|url=http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/benoit-hamon/presidentielle-le-candidat-ecologiste-yannick-jadot-retire-sa-candidature-en-faveur-de-benoit-hamon_2070551.html|agency=Agence France-Presse|publisher=franceinfo|date=23 February 2017|accessdate=24 February 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170225023600/http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/benoit-hamon/presidentielle-le-candidat-ecologiste-yannick-jadot-retire-sa-candidature-en-faveur-de-benoit-hamon_2070551.html|archivedate=25 February 2017}}</ref> The Hamon\u2013Jadot alliance was consummated on 26 February; among those who cast a vote, 79.53% voted to support it, with 15.39% opposed and 5.08% submitting blank ballots, and an overall voter turnout of 55.25% (9,433 votes).<ref>{{cite news|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle : les \u00e9lecteurs \u00e9cologistes approuvent l\u2019accord entre Hamon et Jadot|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/politique/article/2017/02/26/presidentielle-les-electeurs-ecologistes-approuvent-a-pres-de-80-l-accord-entre-hamon-et-jadot_5085810_823448.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=26 February 2017|accessdate=26 February 2017}}</ref> This marks the first election since [[1969 French presidential election|1969]] without a green candidate.<ref>{{cite news|title=Appel \u00e0 t\u00e9moignages : \" On ne brade pas l\u2019\u00e9cologie pour quelques si\u00e8ges \u00e0 l\u2019Assembl\u00e9e \"|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2017/03/02/appel-a-temoignages-on-ne-brade-pas-l-ecologie-pour-quelques-sieges-a-l-assemblee_5088369_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=2 March 2017|accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Primaries ==\n=== The Republicans (LR) ===\n{{Main|The Republicans (France) presidential primary, 2016}}\n[[File:Primaire pr\u00e9sidentielle des R\u00e9publicains de 2016 T1.svg|thumb|right|200px|First-round results by department {{legend|#d95f02|Fran\u00e7ois Fillon}}{{legend|#1b9e77|Alain Jupp\u00e9}}{{legend|#7570b3|Nicolas Sarkozy}}]]\nAfter his loss as the nominee of the [[Union for a Popular Movement]] (UMP) in the [[2012 French presidential election|2012 presidential election]], ex-president [[Nicolas Sarkozy]] pledged to return to being a \"Frenchman among the French\". However, he announced on 19 September 2014 that he would seek the presidency of the party,<ref>{{cite news|title=Nicolas Sarkozy annonce sa candidature \u00e0 la pr\u00e9sidence de l'UMP|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/politique/article/2014/09/19/nicolas-sarkozy-annonce-sa-candidature-a-la-presidence-de-l-ump_4490958_823448.html|agency=Reuters|newspaper=Le Monde|date=19 September 2014|accessdate=9 March 2017}}</ref> a position he secured in an online vote on 29 November online vote with the backing of 64.50% of party members, against his main opponent [[Bruno Le Maire]]'s 29.18%. He succeeded the triumvirate of [[Alain Jupp\u00e9]], [[Fran\u00e7ois Fillon]], and [[Jean-Pierre Raffarin]], which assumed the party's leadership after the resignation of [[Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Cop\u00e9]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Pr\u00e9sidence de l'UMP : Nicolas Sarkozy \u00e9lu, bon score de Bruno Le Maire|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/politique/en-direct-suivez-l-election-du-president-de-l-ump-29-11-2014-4332621.php|newspaper=Le Parisien|date=29 November 2014|accessdate=9 March 2017}}</ref> Sarkozy was initially reluctant to accept the idea of holding a right-wing primary for the 2017 presidential election, but on 25 September 2014 he declared his support for a primary of the right after a warning from Jupp\u00e9,<ref>{{cite news|author=Charles Jaigu|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle 2017 : Sarkozy accepte le principe des primaires \u00e0 droite|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/2014/09/25/01002-20140925ARTFIG00396-nicolas-sarkozy-accepte-le-principe-des-primaires.php|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=25 September 2014|accessdate=9 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312033331/http://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/2014/09/25/01002-20140925ARTFIG00396-nicolas-sarkozy-accepte-le-principe-des-primaires.php|archivedate=12 March 2017}}</ref> who on 20 August made public his intention to run for the nomination.<ref>{{cite news|title=Alain Jupp\u00e9 officialise sa candidature \u00e0 la primaire de l'UMP pour 2017|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/2014/08/20/97001-20140820FILWWW00042-alain-juppe-officialise-sa-candidature-a-la-primaire-de-l-ump.php|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=20 August 2014|accessdate=9 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312032325/http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/2014/08/20/97001-20140820FILWWW00042-alain-juppe-officialise-sa-candidature-a-la-primaire-de-l-ump.php|archivedate=12 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe rules of the primary were confirmed in April 2015, scheduling the first round of an open primary for 20 November 2016, with a runoff on 27 November if no candidate received more than 50% of the vote. Those wishing to vote were required to pay \u20ac2 per ballot and sign a charter indicating their adherence to \"Republican values of the right and centre\".<ref name=\"Monde-primaire-droite\">{{cite news|author1=Matthieu Goar|author2=Alexandre Lemari\u00e9|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle de 2017 : l\u2019UMP fixe les r\u00e8gles du jeu de la primaire \u00e0 droite|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/politique/article/2015/04/02/presidentielle-de-2017-l-ump-fixe-les-regles-du-jeu-de-sa-primaire_4607796_823448.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=2 April 2015|accessdate=9 March 2017}}</ref> In order to appear on the ballot, prospective candidates needed to present sponsorships from 250 elected officials, including at least 20 [[French Parliament|parliamentarians]] from at least 30 [[departments of France|departments]], with no more than a tenth from the same department, in addition to the signatures of at least 2,500 party members across at least 15 departments, with no more than a tenth from the same department.<ref>{{cite web|title=Charte de la Primaire|url=http://www.primaire2016.org/charte|publisher=Primaire ouverte de la droite et du centre|accessdate=9 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170205195730/http://www.primaire2016.org/charte|archivedate= 5 February 2017}}</ref> The charter permitted other parties wishing to participate to set their own sponsorship requirements.<ref name=\"Monde-primaire-droite\"/> The High Authority ultimately determined that seven candidates qualified to compete in the open primary of the right and centre: Fillon, Jupp\u00e9, Le Maire, Cop\u00e9, Sarkozy, and [[Nathalie Kosciusko-Morizet]] of [[the Republicans (France)|the Republicans]],<ref name=\"HAP\">{{cite web|title=Haute Autorit\u00e9 de la Primaire, D\u00e9cision \u2013 21 septembre 2016 [HAP 2016-12 D], Liste des candidats \u00e0 la primaire|url=http://www.primaire2016.org/upload/default/57e26463a3481_HAP%20-%202016-12%20D%20-%20Liste%20des%20candidats.pdf|publisher=Primaire ouverte de la droite et du centre|date=21 September 2016|accessdate=9 March 2017|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161117213910/http://www.primaire2016.org/upload/default/57e26463a3481_HAP%20-%202016-12%20D%20-%20Liste%20des%20candidats.pdf|archivedate=17 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> the party's name after May 2015,<ref>{{cite news|title=Les militants UMP approuvent le nouveau nom du parti, \" Les R\u00e9publicains \"|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/politique/article/2015/05/29/a-la-veille-du-congres-sarkozy-enterre-l-ump-et-lance-un-appel-aux-republicains_4643815_823448.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=29 May 2015|accessdate=9 March 2017}}</ref> as well as [[Jean-Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Poisson]] of the [[Christian Democratic Party (France)|Christian Democratic Party]] (PCD), who was not required to present signatures as the leader of another party.<ref name=\"HAP\"/><ref>{{cite news|author=Tristan Quinault Maupoil|title=Jean-Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Poisson officialise sa candidature \u00e0 la primaire de la droite|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/le-scan/coulisses/2015/09/14/25006-20150914ARTFIG00361-jean-frederic-poisson-officialise-sa-candidature-a-la-primaire-de-la-droite.php|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=14 September 2015|accessdate=9 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312032240/http://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/le-scan/coulisses/2015/09/14/25006-20150914ARTFIG00361-jean-frederic-poisson-officialise-sa-candidature-a-la-primaire-de-la-droite.php|archivedate=12 March 2017}}</ref> The [[National Centre of Independents and Peasants]] (CNIP) were also allowed to participate, but not to present a candidate.<ref>{{cite news|author=Etienne Baldit|title=Les R\u00e9publicains autorisent le CNIP \u00e0 participer \u00e0 la primaire|url=http://lelab.europe1.fr/les-republicains-autorisent-le-cnip-a-participer-a-la-primaire-2735947|work=Le Lab|publisher=Europe 1|date=3 May 2016|accessdate=9 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011074433/http://lelab.europe1.fr/les-republicains-autorisent-le-cnip-a-participer-a-la-primaire-2735947|archivedate=11 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Primaire pr\u00e9sidentielle des R\u00e9publicains de 2016 T2.svg|thumb|right|200px|Second-round results by department {{legend|#d95f02|Fran\u00e7ois Fillon}}{{legend|#1b9e77|Alain Jupp\u00e9}}]]\n\nThe primary was initially fought primarily between Jupp\u00e9 and Sarkozy, the top two candidates in primary polls.<ref>{{cite news|title=Primaire de la droite : Jupp\u00e9 en t\u00eate (sondage BVA)|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/2016/09/25/97001-20160925FILWWW00012-primaire-de-la-droite-juppe-en-tete-sondage-bva.php|agency=Agence France-Presse|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=25 September 2016|accessdate=13 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161013161708/http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/2016/09/25/97001-20160925FILWWW00012-primaire-de-la-droite-juppe-en-tete-sondage-bva.php|archivedate=13 October 2016}}</ref> Sarkozy's program emphasized the themes of Islam, immigration, security, and defense. He proposed to end family reunifications and reform the right to [[jus soli|birthright citizenship]], halt the flow of economic migrants, and increase residence requirements to secure French nationality. He reaffirmed his interest in the \"assimilation\" of immigrants, and intended to ban other menus for school canteens (i.e., options for Muslim students) as well as Muslim headscarves at universities. Sarkozy also suggested that radical imams be expelled and suspected terrorists be detained by authorities and tried by a special anti-terrorist court, in addition a reduction in the age of criminal responsibility from 18 to 16. He proposed to postpone the increase the retirement age to 64 until 2024, permit exemptions to the [[35-hour workweek]], cut 300,000 civil service jobs by increasing working hours to 37 per week, and abolish the [[solidarity tax on wealth|wealth tax]] (ISF). Like Le Maire, he did not rule out the possibility of a referendum on the [[European Union]] (EU).<ref>{{cite news|author=Matthieu Goar|author2=Alexandre Lemari\u00e9|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle : ce que propose Sarkozy dans son livre|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2016/08/23/presidentielle-ce-que-propose-sarkozy-dans-son-livre_4986695_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=23 August 2016|accessdate=9 March 2017}}</ref> He also sought a European treaty \"refounding\", the creation of a European monetary fund, to commit 2% to defense spending by 2025,<ref>{{cite news|author=Mathilde Cousin|title=Quel est le programme de Nicolas Sarkozy ?|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/elections/presidentielles/primaires-droite/2016/10/20/35004-20161020ARTFIG00239-quel-est-le-programme-de-nicolas-sarkozy.php|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=20 October 2016|accessdate=9 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312033015/http://www.lefigaro.fr/elections/presidentielles/primaires-droite/2016/10/20/35004-20161020ARTFIG00239-quel-est-le-programme-de-nicolas-sarkozy.php|archivedate=12 March 2017}}</ref> and to reduce public spending by \u20ac100 billion and taxes by \u20ac40 billion while reducing the budget deficit to under 3% of GDP.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sarkozy promet un budget sous les 3% de d\u00e9ficit en 2019, \u00e0 l'\u00e9quilibre en 2022|url=http://www.europe1.fr/politique/sarkozy-promet-un-budget-sous-les-3-de-deficit-en-2019-a-lequilibre-en-2022-2862478|publisher=Europe 1|date=2 October 2016|accessdate=9 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312034750/http://www.europe1.fr/politique/sarkozy-promet-un-budget-sous-les-3-de-deficit-en-2019-a-lequilibre-en-2022-2862478|archivedate=12 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn contrast to Sarkozy, Jupp\u00e9 spoke of a \"happy identity\" and emphasized the importance of integration as opposed to assimilation.<ref>{{cite news|author=Alexandre Lemari\u00e9|title=A Strasbourg, Alain Jupp\u00e9 assume l\u2019\" identit\u00e9 heureuse \"|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/politique/article/2016/09/13/a-strasbourg-alain-juppe-assume-l-identite-heureuse_4997186_823448.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=13 September 2016|accessdate=9 March 2017}}</ref> He supported drawing up a common list of \"safe countries\" to differentiate refugees from economic migrants, setting a \"quota\" on immigrants as necessary, and to stop providing foreign aid to countries refusing to comply with their obligation to accept deported citizens. He questioned Sarkozy's proposals on [[Schengen Area|Schengen]] and instead merely acknowledged that it was not functioning correctly, but concurred with him in exempting the acquisition of French nationality by foreigners at the age of 18 if previously convicted.<ref>{{cite news|author=Judith Waintraub|title=Immigration : Jupp\u00e9 se d\u00e9marque des propositions de Sarkozy|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/2015/09/17/01002-20150917ARTFIG00239-immigration-juppe-se-demarque-des-propositions-de-sarkozy.php|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=17 September 2015|accessdate=9 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170309014959/http://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/2015/09/17/01002-20150917ARTFIG00239-immigration-juppe-se-demarque-des-propositions-de-sarkozy.php|archivedate= 9 March 2017}}</ref> Jupp\u00e9 also demanded transparency on the funding of places of worship, civic training for imams, and, unlike Sarkozy, favored allowing women to wear the Muslim headscarf at universities. On economic issues, he proposed to end the 35-hour workweek, abolish the wealth tax, reduce corporate taxation, and set the retirement age at 65. He also pledged to slash in half the number of parliamentarians, renegotiate Schengen, and increase defense spending in absolute terms by at least \u20ac7 billion by 2022.<ref>{{cite news|author=Jean-Baptiste Semerdjian|title=Quel est le programme d'Alain Jupp\u00e9 ?|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/elections/presidentielles/primaires-droite/2016/10/20/35004-20161020ARTFIG00234-quel-est-le-programme-d-alain-juppe.php|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=20 October 2016|accessdate=9 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312031933/http://www.lefigaro.fr/elections/presidentielles/primaires-droite/2016/10/20/35004-20161020ARTFIG00234-quel-est-le-programme-d-alain-juppe.php|archivedate=12 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter several strong debate performances by Fillon, however, a second-round Jupp\u00e9\u2013Sarkozy duel no longer appeared inevitable.<ref>{{cite news|title=Primaire \u00e0 droite : Fran\u00e7ois Fillon grand vainqueur du dernier d\u00e9bat t\u00e9l\u00e9vis\u00e9, selon deux sondages|url=http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/les-republicains/primaire-de-la-droite/primaire-a-droite-francois-fillon-grand-vainqueur-du-dernier-debat-televise-selon-deux-sondages_1926671.html|publisher=franceinfo|date=18 November 2016|accessdate=9 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129124933/http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/les-republicains/primaire-de-la-droite/primaire-a-droite-francois-fillon-grand-vainqueur-du-dernier-debat-televise-selon-deux-sondages_1926671.html|archivedate=29 November 2016}}</ref> Fillon's rise was propelled by his proposals for a rigorous economic program. Seeking \u20ac100 billion in cuts, he proposed eliminating 500,000 civil service jobs by 2022 and a return to the 39-hour workweek for civil servants. Like the other primary candidates, he planned to eliminate the wealth tax; in addition, Fillon suggested abolishing the 35-hour workweek \u2013 capping it at the 48-hour maximum allowed within the EU \u2013 and the implementation of other liberal economic measures. He also adopted a staunchly conservative social program, opposing adoption by same-sex couples and arguing France had no religious problem apart from Islam itself. Like Sarkozy, he sought to expand the capacity of French prisons, but unlike his former superior, he opposed banning religious symbols in public places. He also professed a more pro-Russian stance than other candidates, urging cooperation in Syria against the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] and supporting the \"pragmatism\" of [[Vladimir Putin]]'s intervention in the [[Syrian civil war]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Primaire \u00e0 droite: cinq choses \u00e0 savoir sur le programme de Fran\u00e7ois Fillon|url=http://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/politique/primaire-a-droite-cinq-choses-a-savoir-sur-le-programme-de-francois-fillon_1852316.html|newspaper=L'Express|date=21 November 2016|accessdate=9 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312032712/http://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/politique/primaire-a-droite-cinq-choses-a-savoir-sur-le-programme-de-francois-fillon_1852316.html|archivedate=12 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe first round of the primary on 20 November saw the unexpected elimination of Sarkozy, with Fillon coming in first with 44.1%, Jupp\u00e9 at 28.6%, and Sarkozy at 20.7% of the vote, and all other candidates far behind. A second round between Fillon and Jupp\u00e9 was confirmed, and Sarkozy announced that he would vote for his former Prime Minister soon after the results became clear.<ref>{{cite news|title=R\u00e9sultats de la primaire de la droite : Fillon largement en t\u00eate du premier tour|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2016/11/20/primaire-de-la-droite-fillon-largement-en-tete-sarkozy-en-mauvaise-posture_5034730_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=20 November 2016|accessdate=9 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Haute Autorit\u00e9 de la Primaire, D\u00e9cision \u2013 23 novembre 2016 [HAP 2016-19 D], Proclamation des r\u00e9sultats du 1<sup>er</sup> tour, arr\u00eatant la liste des deux candidats habilit\u00e9s \u00e0 se pr\u00e9senter pour le 2nd tour|url=http://www.primaire2016.org/upload/default/5835c95b6fb1a_HAP%20-%202016-19%20D%20-%20Proclamation%20des%20re%CC%81sultats%20et%20candidats%20au%20second%20tour.pdf|publisher=Primaire ouverte de la droite et du centre|date=23 November 2016|accessdate=9 March 2017|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161124162501/http://www.primaire2016.org/upload/default/5835c95b6fb1a_HAP%20-%202016-19%20D%20-%20Proclamation%20des%20re%CC%81sultats%20et%20candidats%20au%20second%20tour.pdf|archivedate=24 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Fillon scored a landslide victory in the 27 November runoff with 66.5% of the vote to Jupp\u00e9's 33.5% and became the Republicans' nominee; voter turnout \u2013 at 4.4 million \u2013 was even higher than in the first round.<ref>{{cite news|title=R\u00e9sultats de la primaire \u00e0 droite : Fillon plebiscit\u00e9 avec 66,5% des voix|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/elections/presidentielle/primaires/primaire-a-droite-les-resultats-partiels-du-second-tour-27-11-2016-6382575.php|newspaper=Le Parisien|date=27 November 2016|accessdate=9 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Haute Autorit\u00e9 de la Primaire, D\u00e9cision \u2013 30 novembre 2016 [HAP 2016-20 D], Proclamation des r\u00e9sultats du 2nd tour de la Primaire de la droite et du centre|url=http://www.primaire2016.org/upload/default/583edfa37eca6_HAP%20-%202016-20%20D%20-%20Proclamation%20second%20tour%20Primaire.pdf|publisher=Primaire ouverte de la droite et du centre|date=30 November 2016|accessdate=9 March 2017|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220093016/http://www.primaire2016.org/upload/default/583edfa37eca6_HAP%20-%202016-20%20D%20-%20Proclamation%20second%20tour%20Primaire.pdf|archivedate=20 December 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Socialist Party (PS) ===\n{{Main|French Socialist Party presidential primary, 2017}}\n[[File:Primaire pr\u00e9sidentielle du PS de 2017 T1.svg|thumb|right|200px|First-round results by department {{legend|#d36027|Beno\u00eet Hamon}}{{legend|#0773b3|Manuel Valls}}{{legend|#f1e545|Arnaud Montebourg}}{{legend|#069f73|Sylvia Pinel}}]]\nAt the 2012 [[Toulouse Congress, 2012|Toulouse Congress]], the [[Socialist Party (France)|Socialist Party]] (PS) modified its statutes to guarantee the selection of a candidate of the left through open primaries, with the National Council of the Socialist Party announcing the timetable and organization of the primaries at least one year beforehand.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle 2017 : Hollande veut clore le d\u00e9bat sur la primaire \u00e0 gauche|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/politique/presidentielle-2017-hollande-espere-clore-le-debat-sur-la-primaire-a-gauche-20-11-2014-4308475.php|newspaper=Le Parisien|date=20 November 2014|accessdate=9 April 2017}}</ref> On 11 January, ''[[Lib\u00e9ration]]'' published an editorial in favor of a \"primary of the left and ecologists\",<ref name=\"20160411-Monde\">{{cite news|author=Charlotte Belaich|title=Primaire de la gauche : o\u00f9 en est-on ?|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/politique/article/2016/04/11/primaire-de-la-gauche-ou-en-est-on_4900163_823448.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=11 April 2016|accessdate=9 April 2017}}</ref> and on 9 April the National Council of the Socialist Party unanimously approved the idea of holding such a primary in early December.<ref>{{cite news|author=Claire Gaveau|title=Primaire \u00e0 gauche : le conseil national du Parti socialiste valide le principe d'un tel scrutin|url=http://www.rtl.fr/actu/politique/primaire-a-gauche-le-conseil-national-du-parti-socialiste-valide-le-principe-d-un-tel-scrutin-7782755870|agency=Agence France-Presse|publisher=RTL|date=9 April 2016|accessdate=9 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170409113121/http://www.rtl.fr/actu/politique/primaire-a-gauche-le-conseil-national-du-parti-socialiste-valide-le-principe-d-un-tel-scrutin-7782755870|archivedate= 9 April 2017}}</ref> On 18 June, the National Council finally confirmed that it would organize a primary to select a candidate for the 2017 presidential election. Applications could be submitted from 1 to 15 December, with two rounds of voting planned for 22 and 29 January 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=Le PS d\u00e9cide \u00e0 l'unanimit\u00e9 d'organiser une primaire pour la pr\u00e9sidentielle de 2017|url=http://www.francetvinfo.fr/elections/presidentielle/le-conseil-national-du-ps-decide-a-l-unanimite-d-organiser-une-primaire-pour-la-presidentielle-de-2017_1506125.html|publisher=franceinfo|date=18 June 2016|accessdate=9 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161217113053/http://www.francetvinfo.fr/elections/presidentielle/le-conseil-national-du-ps-decide-a-l-unanimite-d-organiser-une-primaire-pour-la-presidentielle-de-2017_1506125.html|archivedate=17 December 2016}}</ref> Prospective PS candidates were required to sign the primary's charter of ethics requiring candidates to rally behind its winner and to secure the support of 5% of one of the following groups: members of the National Council; Socialist parliamentarians, regional and departmental Socialist councilors in at least 4 regions and 10 departments; or Socialist mayors representing more than 10,000 people in at least 4 regions and 10 departments.<ref>{{cite web|title=R\u00e9solution sur les Primaires citoyennes Conseil national du Parti socialiste \u2013 2 octobre 2016|url=http://www.parti-socialiste.fr/resolution-primaires-citoyennes-conseil-national-parti-socialiste-2-octobre-2016/|publisher=Parti socialiste|date=2 October 2016|accessdate=9 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427024022/http://www.parti-socialiste.fr/resolution-primaires-citoyennes-conseil-national-parti-socialiste-2-octobre-2016/|archivedate=27 April 2017}}</ref> The conditions for becoming a candidate of other member parties of the BAP \u2013 the PRG, UDE, PE, and [[Democratic Front (France)|Democratic Front]] (FD) \u2013 were determined by the respective parties' leadership.<ref>{{cite web|title=Code \u00e9lectoral des Primaires citoyennes|url=http://www.lesprimairescitoyennes.fr/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/CODE_ELECTORAL.pdf|publisher=Comit\u00e9 national d\u2019organisation des Primaires|date=14 November 2016|accessdate=9 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161216130003/https://www.lesprimairescitoyennes.fr/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/CODE_ELECTORAL.pdf|archivedate=16 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe EELV declared on 20 June that it would not participate in the primary,<ref>{{cite news|author=Arthur Berdah|title=EELV refuse de participer \u00e0 la primaire \u00e0 gauche|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/le-scan/citations/2016/06/20/25002-20160620ARTFIG00057-eelv-refuse-de-participer-a-la-primaire-a-gauche.php|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=20 June 2016|accessdate=9 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170410050939/http://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/le-scan/citations/2016/06/20/25002-20160620ARTFIG00057-eelv-refuse-de-participer-a-la-primaire-a-gauche.php|archivedate=10 April 2017}}</ref> and the [[French Communist Party]] (PCF) did likewise the following day.<ref>{{cite news|author=Arthur Berdah|title=Le PCF exclut \u00e0 son tour de participer \u00e0 la primaire \u00e0 gauche|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/le-scan/citations/2016/06/21/25002-20160621ARTFIG00067-le-pcf-exclut-a-son-tour-de-participer-a-la-primaire-a-gauche.php|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=21 June 2016|accessdate=9 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317005513/http://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/le-scan/citations/2016/06/21/25002-20160621ARTFIG00067-le-pcf-exclut-a-son-tour-de-participer-a-la-primaire-a-gauche.php|archivedate=17 March 2017}}</ref> After declaring his candidacy for the presidential election, [[Emmanuel Macron]] of [[En Marche!]] also declined to participate,<ref>{{cite news|title=Macron fera cavalier seul pour la pr\u00e9sidentielle, Valls pr\u00eat \u00e0 se d\u00e9clarer candidat|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2016/12/04/pour-macron-la-primaire-va-scenariser-le-dechirement-autour-du-bilan-du-quinquennat_5042987_4854003.html|agency=Agence France-Presse; Reuters|newspaper=Le Monde|date=4 December 2016|accessdate=9 April 2017}}</ref> as did [[Jean-Luc M\u00e9lenchon]] under the banner of [[la France Insoumise]], saying that he did not want to run in a primary with [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]] since he would not be able to support Hollande if he won.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Olivier Mazerolle|author2=Claire Gaveau|title=Primaire \u00e0 gauche : \"Si Fran\u00e7ois Hollande gagne, je n'appelerai pas \u00e0 voter pour lui\", se d\u00e9fend Jean-Luc M\u00e9lenchon|url=http://www.rtl.fr/actu/politique/primaire-a-gauche-si-francois-hollande-gagne-je-n-appelerai-pas-a-voter-pour-lui-se-defend-jean-luc-melenchon-7781333623|publisher=RTL|date=14 January 2016|accessdate=9 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215185246/http://www.rtl.fr/actu/politique/primaire-a-gauche-si-francois-hollande-gagne-je-n-appelerai-pas-a-voter-pour-lui-se-defend-jean-luc-melenchon-7781333623|archivedate=15 February 2017}}</ref> He later reaffirmed this by saying that with the exclusion of the EELV and PRG the primary was not truly \"of the left\" but a \"primary of the Socialist Party\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Marie-Pierre Haddad|title=Primaire PS : pourquoi Valls et Cambad\u00e9lis veulent attirer Macron et M\u00e9lenchon|url=http://www.rtl.fr/actu/politique/primaire-ps-pourquoi-valls-et-cambadelis-veulent-attirer-macron-et-melenchon-7786204533|publisher=RTL|date=10 December 2016|accessdate=9 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170410052556/http://www.rtl.fr/actu/politique/primaire-ps-pourquoi-valls-et-cambadelis-veulent-attirer-macron-et-melenchon-7786204533|archivedate=10 April 2017}}</ref> On 1 December, Hollande declared that he would not seek a second term, becoming the first President of the Fifth Republic to renounce a reelection bid. His announcement reflected his high personal unpopularity and resentment among Socialist colleagues regarding remarks he made about cabinet members and other associates in the book ''[[Un pr\u00e9sident ne devrait pas dire \u00e7a...]]'' (A president should not say that...) by [[G\u00e9rard Davet]] and [[Fabrice Lhomme]], journalists at ''[[Le Monde]]''.<ref name=\"Hollande-renounce\">{{cite news|author=Nicolas Chapuis|title=Fran\u00e7ois Hollande : \" J\u2019ai d\u00e9cid\u00e9 de ne pas \u00eatre candidat \u00e0 l\u2019\u00e9lection pr\u00e9sidentielle \"|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2016/12/01/francois-hollande-s-exprimera-a-20-heures-en-direct-depuis-l-elysee_5041785_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=1 December 2016|accessdate=9 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Primaire pr\u00e9sidentielle du PS de 2017 T2.svg|thumb|right|200px|Second-round results by department {{legend|#d36027|Beno\u00eet Hamon}}{{legend|#0773b3|Manuel Valls}}]]\n\nOn 17 December, the High Authority declared that seven candidates qualified to appear on the ballot: four from the Socialist Party \u2013 former [[Prime Minister of France|Prime Minister]] [[Manuel Valls]], [[Arnaud Montebourg]], [[Beno\u00eet Hamon]], and [[Vincent Peillon]] \u2013 and [[Fran\u00e7ois de Rugy]] of the PE, Sylvia Pinel of the PRG, and [[Jean-Luc Bennahmias]] of the PD.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sept candidats retenus pour la primaire de la gauche|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/politique/article/2016/12/17/sept-candidats-retenus-pour-la-primaire-de-la-gauche_5050653_823448.html|agency=Agence France-Presse|newspaper=Le Monde|date=17 December 2016|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref> Early opinion polling placed Valls and Montebourg first and second, respectively, with Hamon a close third.<ref>{{cite web|title=Intentions et motivations de vote \u00e0 la Primaire du Parti socialiste et de ses alli\u00e9s|url=http://harris-interactive.fr/wp-content/uploads/sites/6/2017/01/Rapport-Harris-Intentions-de-vote-%C3%A0-la-primaire-du-PS-et-de-ses-alli%C3%A9s-France-TV.pdf|publisher=Harris Interactive|date=5 January 2017|accessdate=13 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170106033016/http://harris-interactive.fr/wp-content/uploads/sites/6/2017/01/Rapport-Harris-Intentions-de-vote-%C3%A0-la-primaire-du-PS-et-de-ses-alli%C3%A9s-France-TV.pdf|archivedate= 6 January 2017}}</ref> Shortly after declaring his candidacy on 5 December, Valls proposed to abolish [[49.3 (France)|article 49.3]] of the French constitution, a procedure that allows bypassing legislative approval, in a \"democratic renaissance\"; as Prime Minister, he invoked it on six occasions, using it to pass the [[Macron law|Macron]] and [[El Khomri law|El Khomri]] laws.<ref>{{cite news|author=Jules Pecnard|title=Valls propose de supprimer le 49.3, apr\u00e8s l'avoir utilis\u00e9 six fois|url=http://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/politique/elections/valls-propose-de-supprimer-le-49-3-apres-l-avoir-utilise-6-fois_1860595.html|newspaper=L'Express|date=15 December 2016|accessdate=13 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170413154300/http://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/politique/elections/valls-propose-de-supprimer-le-49-3-apres-l-avoir-utilise-6-fois_1860595.html|archivedate=13 April 2017}}</ref> He also proposed a 2.5% increase in public spending while keeping the budget deficit under 3%, guaranteeing a \"decent income\" of \u20ac800, reducing the [[gender pay gap#France|gender pay gap]] by half, pausing the [[enlargement of the European Union]], appending a charter of secularism to the Constitution, consolidating the nuclear industry, and mandating six months of civic service.<ref>{{cite news|author=Pierre-Alain Furbury|title=Primaire : Valls joue la \"\u2009continuit\u00e9\u2009\", pas les id\u00e9es neuves|url=http://www.lesechos.fr/elections/primaire-a-gauche/0211654210506-primaire-valls-presente-son-projet-entre-europe-refondee-et-droit-dinventer-2054177.php|newspaper=Les \u00c9chos|date=3 January 2017|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Bastien Bonnefous|title=Peillon et Valls pr\u00e9sentent leurs programmes|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2017/01/03/peillon-et-valls-presentent-leurs-programmes_5057018_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=3 January 2017|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref> He was twice physically attacked during the primary campaign: on 22 December, he was flour-bombed by a protester in [[Strasbourg]] saying \"we do not forget [the 49.3]!\",<ref>{{cite news|title=VID\u00c9O. Manuel Valls enfarin\u00e9 \u00e0 Strasbourg: \"49.3, on n'oublie pas!\"|url=http://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/politique/elections/video-manuel-valls-enfarine-a-strasbourg_1862927.html|newspaper=L'Express|date=22 December 2016|accessdate=13 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170413153430/http://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/politique/elections/video-manuel-valls-enfarine-a-strasbourg_1862927.html|archivedate=13 April 2017}}</ref> and on 17 January, he was slapped by a young Breton regionalist in [[Lamballe]], who was subsequently charged.<ref>{{cite news|author=Julien Muller|title=Manuel Valls gifl\u00e9 en Bretagne : Nolan, 18 ans, condamn\u00e9 \u00e0 3 mois de prison avec sursis|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/faits-divers/manuel-valls-gifle-en-bretagne-nolan-18-ans-condamne-a-3-mois-de-prison-avec-sursis-18-01-2017-6585879.php|newspaper=Le Parisien|date=18 January 2017|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nFormer [[French Ministry for the Economy and Finance|Minister of the Economy]] Arnaud Montebourg, a Socialist rebel known for promoting \"made in France\", presented a firmly left-wing project shortly after declaring his candidacy in August 2016. He promised to offer French enterprises preference in bidding, reverse the 2011 tax increases on the French middle class,<ref name=\"Montebourg-1\">{{cite news|author=Bastien Bonnefous|title=Le \" Projet France \" d\u2019Arnaud Montebourg|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2016/08/22/le-projet-france-d-arnaud-montebourg_4986026_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=22 August 2016|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref> and repeal most of the El Khomri labor law while preserving certain \"interesting\" social protections such as the \"right to disconnect\" and \"personal activity account\".<ref>{{cite news|author1=Sarah Belouezzane|author2=Bertrand Bissuel|title=Primaire de la gauche : le revenu universel cr\u00e9e un nouveau clivage|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2017/01/13/primaire-a-gauche-le-revenu-universel-cree-un-nouveau-clivage_5062061_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=13 January 2017|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref> Critical of European austerity, he declared that he would defy the requirement to maintain a budget deficit under 3% of GDP and intended to strengthen intelligence services, require six months of civic service, and achieve gender equality.<ref name=\"Montebourg-1\"/> He also proposed \u20ac30 billion in spending to stimulate economic growth, lower the [[general social contribution]] (CSG) to increase individuals' purchasing power by \u20ac800 a year, create 5,000 new posts in hospitals, call a referendum on a new republic, promulgate a law on the separation of banking activities (as Hollande did), impose a European carbon tax, and establish a national anti-terrorism prosecutor.<ref>{{cite news|title=Primaire \u00e0 gauche : Montebourg a mis en ligne son programme|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/elections/presidentielle/candidats-et-programmes/primaire-a-gauche-montebourg-a-mis-en-ligne-son-programme-27-12-2016-6499716.php|newspaper=Le Parisien|date=27 December 2016|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe signature proposal of [[Beno\u00eet Hamon]] was the implementation a [[basic income|universal basic income]] for all French citizens, rolled out in stages beginning in 2018, partially funded by a tax levied on property combining the existing property tax (''taxe fonci\u00e8re'') and the [[solidarity tax on wealth]] (ISF), in addition to a tax on robots to fund social protections in general. Like fellow Socialist dissidents, Hamon criticized the El Khomri labor law and promised to repeal it if elected, and suggested that it be replaced with legislation acknowledging the need for greater social protections, including the right to disconnect and recognizing burnout as an occupational disease.<ref>{{cite news|author=Marianne Rey|title=Beno\u00eet Hamon propose le revenu universel pour 2017, mais pas seulement|url=http://lentreprise.lexpress.fr/rh-management/droit-travail/au-programme-social-de-benoit-hamon-le-revenu-universel-mais-pas-seulement_1868821.html|newspaper=L'Express|date=13 January 2017|accessdate=13 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170126154136/http://lentreprise.lexpress.fr/rh-management/droit-travail/au-programme-social-de-benoit-hamon-le-revenu-universel-mais-pas-seulement_1868821.html|archivedate=26 January 2017}}</ref> He also proposed to reduce the [[35-hour workweek]] to 32 hours, saying that it was time to put an end to the \"myth\" of economic growth. Another of his flagship proposals was to legalize cannabis, using funds for \"prevention\" rather than \"repression\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Ecole, revenu universel, 32 heures\u2026 Ce qu\u2019il faut retenir de Beno\u00eet Hamon dans \" L\u2019\u00e9mission politique \"|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2016/12/09/ecole-revenu-universel-32-heures-ce-qu-il-faut-retenir-de-benoit-hamon-dans-l-emission-politique_5046001_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=9 December 2016|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Hamon at Maison de la Mutualit\u00e9, 29 January 2017 - Anne Hidalgo congratulations.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Beno\u00eet Hamon congratulated by [[Mayor of Paris]] [[Anne Hidalgo]] after his primary victory on 29 January]]\n\nIn the first round of the primary on 22 January, Hamon and Valls received 36.03% and 31.48%, respectively, and advanced to the runoff on 29 January. Montebourg, who secured only 17.52% of votes,<ref name=\"22Jan\">{{cite web|title=Communiqu\u00e9 de la Haute Autorit\u00e9 des Primaires Citoyennes \u2013 25 janvier 2017|url=http://www.lesprimairescitoyennes.fr/communique-de-haute-autorite-primaires-citoyennes-23-janvier-2017/|publisher=Haute Autorit\u00e9 des Primaires Citoyennes|date=25 January 2017|accessdate=13 April 2017|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217115820/http://www.lesprimairescitoyennes.fr/communique-de-haute-autorite-primaires-citoyennes-23-janvier-2017/|archivedate=17 February 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> declared that he would cast his second-round vote for Hamon soon after the result became apparent.<ref>{{cite news|author=Arthur Nazaret|title=Chez Montebourg, le soutien \u00e0 Hamon fait l'unanimit\u00e9|url=http://www.lejdd.fr/Politique/Chez-Montebourg-le-soutien-a-Hamon-fait-l-unanimite-842020|newspaper=Le Journal du Dimanche|date=22 January 2017|accessdate=13 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170413154057/http://www.lejdd.fr/Politique/Chez-Montebourg-le-soutien-a-Hamon-fait-l-unanimite-842020|archivedate=13 April 2017}}</ref> Among the remaining candidates, Peillon secured 6.81% of the vote, de Rugy 3.83%, Pinel 2.00%, and Bennahmias 1.02%. Overall turnout stood at 1.66 million.<ref name=\"22Jan\"/> The legitimacy of the first-round results published by the organizers of the primary was questioned by observers in the French press, who noted that an overnight update added 352,013 votes without significantly changing each candidate's percentage, with vote totals for each candidate increasing by 28%. {{Interlanguage link|Christophe Borgel|fr|Christophe Borgel}}, president of the organizing committee of the primary, claimed that the anomaly was nothing more than a \"bug\" induced by pressure to update the level of participation in the first round, effectively acknowledging that the results of the primary were manipulated. Only on 23 January did the High Authority of the primary publish \"validated\" results.<ref>{{cite news|author=Samuel Laurent|title=Primaire de la gauche : pourquoi le doute persiste sur les chiffres du scrutin|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/les-decodeurs/article/2017/01/23/primaire-a-gauche-comment-les-chiffres-des-votants-ont-ete-manipules_5067703_4355770.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=23 January 2017|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref> In the second round of the primary on 29 January, Hamon defeated Valls by a comfortable margin, 58.69% to 41.31%; turnout, at 2.05 million, was considerably higher than in the first round. As the winner of the primary, Hamon became the Socialist nominee for president.<ref>{{cite web|title=Les r\u00e9sultats nationaux du second tour|url=http://www.lesprimairescitoyennes.fr/|publisher=Haute Autorit\u00e9 des Primaires Citoyennes|date=5 February 2017|accessdate=13 April 2017|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170402152843/http://www.lesprimairescitoyennes.fr/|archivedate=2 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 February, Fran\u00e7ois de Rugy announced his support for Emmanuel Macron, breaking the commitment requested of former candidates to back the winner of the primary. While acknowledging that Hamon was the legitimate PS nominee, de Rugy said he preferred \"coherence to obedience\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Fran\u00e7ois de Rugy se rallie \u00e0 Emmanuel Macron, au nom de \" la coh\u00e9rence \"|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2017/02/22/francois-de-rugy-se-rallie-a-emmanuel-macron-au-nom-de-la-coherence_5083520_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=22 February 2017|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref> On 13 March, ''[[Le Parisien]]'' reported that Valls, rather than backing Hamon, would urge voters to support Macron in the first round of the presidential election;<ref name=\"Valls-Macron\">{{cite news|author=Nathalie Schuck|title=EXCLUSIF. Pr\u00e9sidentielle : Valls va appeler \u00e0 soutenir Macron d\u00e8s le premier tour|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/elections/presidentielle/presidentielle-l-appel-de-valls-a-soutenir-macron-des-le-premier-tour-13-03-2017-6759426.php|newspaper=Le Parisien|date=13 March 2017|accessdate=13 March 2017}}</ref> Valls denied the report at the time,<ref>{{cite news|title=Manuel Valls d\u00e9ment vouloir soutenir Emmanuel Macron|url=http://www.bfmtv.com/politique/manuel-valls-va-appeler-a-soutenir-emmanuel-macron-1121113.html|publisher=BFM TV|date=13 March 2017|accessdate=28 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170330052733/http://www.bfmtv.com/politique/manuel-valls-va-appeler-a-soutenir-emmanuel-macron-1121113.html|archivedate=30 March 2017}}</ref> but on 29 March declared that he would vote for Macron but would not rally behind his candidacy.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Bastien Bonnefous|author2=C\u00e9dric Pietralunga|title=Valls choisit Macron, quitte \u00e0 faire imploser le Parti socialiste|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2017/03/29/manuel-valls-annonce-qu-il-votera-pour-emmanuel-macron_5102394_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=29 March 2017|accessdate=29 March 2017}}</ref> On 8 April the High Authority of the PS reminded party members to abide by the \"principle of loyalty\".<ref>{{cite news|title=La Haute autorit\u00e9 du PS rappelle \u00e0 l\u2019ordre les socialistes qui l\u00e2chent Beno\u00eet Hamon|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2017/04/08/la-haute-autorite-du-ps-rappelle-a-l-ordre-les-socialistes-qui-lachent-benoit-hamon_5108307_4854003.html|agency=Agence France-Presse|newspaper=Le Monde|date=8 April 2017|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref> On 15 March, the PRG announced its support for Hamon, securing concessions on issues pertaining to European governance, and confirmed an agreement with the Socialist Party for the [[2017 French legislative election|legislative elections]]; this followed a period of hesitation after the primary in which the party contemplated Macron's candidacy, which secured several of its parliamentarians' support.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle : le Parti radical de gauche de Sylvia Pinel d\u00e9cide de soutenir Beno\u00eet Hamon|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2017/03/15/presidentielle-le-parti-radical-de-gauche-de-sylvia-pinel-decide-de-soutenir-benoit-hamon_5095060_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=15 March 2017|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Fillon affair (Penelopegate) ==\n{{Main|Fillon affair}}\n[[File:Penelope Fillon.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Penelope Fillon in 2007]]\nOn 25 January 2017, the satirical weekly ''[[Le Canard encha\u00een\u00e9]]'' alleged that [[Fran\u00e7ois Fillon]] employed his wife [[Penelope Fillon|Penelope]] as his parliamentary assistant from 1998 and 2002 and for six months in 2012, with no evidence that she completed any substantial work. She collected a monthly salary of \u20ac3,900 to \u20ac4,600. After her husband's appointment as [[Minister of Social Affairs (France)|Minister of Social Affairs]] in 2002 and during his later tenure as [[Ministry of National Education (France)|Minister of National Education]], she went on to serve until 2007 as a parliamentary aide to [[Marc Joulaud]], Fillon's substitute, earning an increased salary upwards of \u20ac7,900 and with still no evidence of substantial work. The article claimed that she received a total of over \u20ac500,000 as a parliamentary aide, as well as \u20ac100,000 as a literary adviser to the ''[[Revue des deux Mondes]]''. Its owner, billionaire [[Marc Ladreit de Lacharri\u00e8re]], is a close friend of Fran\u00e7ois Fillon. While deputies in the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]] can employ family members, those are still required to complete legitimate work, evidence of which the paper was unable to find.<ref name=\"LM-20170124\">{{cite news|author=Matthieu Goar|title=Fran\u00e7ois Fillon embarrass\u00e9 par l\u2019emploi de son \u00e9pouse en tant qu\u2019assistante parlementaire|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/politique/article/2017/01/24/la-femme-de-francois-fillon-a-percu-500-000-euros-comme-attachee-parlementaire_5068488_823448.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=24 January 2017|accessdate=2 March 2017}}</ref> Based on that information and on the same day, the PNF (''parquet national financier'', or national financial prosecutor's office) initiated a preliminary investigation into possible embezzlement and misuse of public funds.<ref>{{cite news|title=Le parquet financier ouvre une enqu\u00eate pr\u00e9liminaire dans l\u2019affaire Penelope Fillon|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/police-justice/article/2017/01/25/le-parquet-financier-ouvre-une-enquete-preliminaire-dans-l-affaire-penelope-fillon_5068964_1653578.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=25 January 2017|accessdate=2 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 January, Fran\u00e7ois Fillon appeared on [[TF1]] to respond to these allegations, stating that his wife had \"edited my speeches\" and \"stood in for me at events when I couldn\u2019t be there\",<!-- English quote from http://www.politico.eu/article/francois-fillon-fights-growing-penelopegate-scandal/ --> also claiming that the reason that she was never seen working in the Palais Bourbon was because \"she was never on the front line\". In the interview, he disclosed that he also paid two of his children while a [[Senate (France)|Senator]] for the [[Sarthe]] between 2005 and 2007, claiming that he employed them in their capacity as lawyers. He also pledged to resign if he would be personally placed under investigation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle : Fran\u00e7ois Fillon renoncera s\u2019il est mis en examen|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2017/01/26/francois-fillon-renoncera-a-la-presidentielle-s-il-est-mis-en-examen-dans-l-affaire-de-l-emploi-suppose-fictif-de-sa-femme_5069771_4854003.html|agency=Agence France-Presse|newspaper=Le Monde|date=26 January 2017|accessdate=2 March 2017}}</ref> However, on 27 January, it was revealed that both Marie and Charles Fillon were only law students when their father employed them during his stint in the Senate, contrary to his statements the previous day.<ref>{{cite news|author=J\u00e9r\u00f4me Jadot|title=Quand Fran\u00e7ois Fillon a fait travailler ses enfants, ils \u00e9taient encore \u00e9tudiants en droit|url=http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/francois-fillon/penelope-fillon/quand-francois-fillon-a-fait-travailler-ses-enfants-ils-etaient-encore-etudiants-en-droit_2038815.html|publisher=franceinfo|date=27 January 2017|accessdate=2 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170130093524/http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/francois-fillon/penelope-fillon/quand-francois-fillon-a-fait-travailler-ses-enfants-ils-etaient-encore-etudiants-en-droit_2038815.html|archivedate=30 January 2017}}</ref> Interrogated by investigators the same day, former editor-in-chief of the ''Revue des deux Mondes'' [[Michel Cr\u00e9pu]] claimed that only \"two or maybe three\" bylines in the review were attributed to her, also saying that he had seen \"no trace\" of any work by her that would \"resemble [that of] a literary adviser\".<ref>{{cite news|author=El\u00e9anor Douet|title=Affaire Penelope Fillon : une perquisition a eu lieu \u00e0 \"La Revue des Deux Mondes\"|url=http://www.rtl.fr/actu/politique/affaire-penelope-fillon-une-perquisition-a-eu-lieu-a-la-revue-des-deux-mondes-7786967853|agency=Agence France-Presse|publisher=RTL|date=28 January 2017|accessdate=2 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170130054933/http://www.rtl.fr/actu/politique/affaire-penelope-fillon-une-perquisition-a-eu-lieu-a-la-revue-des-deux-mondes-7786967853|archivedate=30 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:MJ wiki recadr\u00e9.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Marc Joulaud]] in 2014]]\n\nOn 1 February, a week after its initial report, ''Le Canard encha\u00een\u00e9'' published revelations that the total sum received by Penelope Fillon in fictitious jobs apparently totaled more than \u20ac930,000; with the addition of the period from 1988 to 1990, her income as a parliamentary assistant now totaled \u20ac831,440. In addition, the satirical weekly also revealed that the payments to two of Fillon's children reached nearly \u20ac84,000, with \u20ac57,084 net for Marie Fillon and \u20ac26,651 for Charles Fillon.<ref>{{cite news|title=\"Le Canard encha\u00een\u00e9\" affirme que Penelope Fillon a per\u00e7u plus de 930 000 euros et non 600 000 euros|url=http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/francois-fillon/penelope-fillon/le-canard-enchaine-affirme-que-penelope-fillon-a-percu-plus-de-930-000-euros-et-non-600-000-euros_2044697.html|agency=Agence France-Presse|publisher=franceinfo|date=31 January 2017|accessdate=2 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170303042757/http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/francois-fillon/penelope-fillon/le-canard-enchaine-affirme-que-penelope-fillon-a-percu-plus-de-930-000-euros-et-non-600-000-euros_2044697.html|archivedate= 3 March 2017}}</ref> Video excerpts of a May 2007 ''[[the Sunday Telegraph|Sunday Telegraph]]'' interview with Penelope Fillon surfaced on 2 February, in which she claimed that she had \"never been his assistant\", referring to her husband; The footage aired on ''[[Envoy\u00e9 sp\u00e9cial]]'' on [[France 2]] that evening.<ref>{{cite news|title=INFO \"ENVOYE SPECIAL\". A propos de son mari : \"Je n'ai jamais \u00e9t\u00e9 son assistante, ou quoi que ce soit de ce genre-l\u00e0\", affirmait Penelope Fillon en mai 2007|url=http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/francois-fillon/penelope-fillon/info-envoye-special-je-n-ai-jamais-ete-l-assistante-de-mon-mari-affirmait-penelope-fillon-en-mai-2007_2046177.html|publisher=franceinfo|date=2 February 2017|accessdate=3 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214051151/http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/francois-fillon/penelope-fillon/info-envoye-special-je-n-ai-jamais-ete-l-assistante-de-mon-mari-affirmait-penelope-fillon-en-mai-2007_2046177.html|archivedate=14 February 2017}}</ref> The PNF expanded investigation into the fictitious employment affair to include Fillon's two eldest children the same day to verify the veracity of their work, after ''Le Canard encha\u00een\u00e9'' reported that neither Marie nor Charles Fillon were lawyers at the time their father served in the Senate.<ref>{{cite news|title=Affaire Fillon : l\u2019enqu\u00eate visant Penelope Fillon \u00e9tendue aux deux enfants a\u00een\u00e9s du couple|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/affaire-penelope-fillon/article/2017/02/02/affaire-fillon-l-enquete-visant-penelope-fillon-etendue-aux-deux-enfants-aines-du-couple_5073476_5070021.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=2 February 2017|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref> In a video on 3 February, Fran\u00e7ois Fillon insisted that he would maintain his candidacy and called on his supporters to \"hold the line\", seeking to assuage worries from within his own camp about the maintenance of his candidacy.<ref>{{cite news|title=\" On se fait pourrir dans la rue \" : les appels au retrait de Fillon continuent|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/affaire-penelope-fillon/article/2017/02/04/on-se-fait-pourrir-dans-la-rue-les-appels-au-retrait-de-fillon-continuent_5074638_5070021.html|agency=Agence France-Presse|newspaper=Le Monde|date=4 February 2017|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 February, Fillon held a press conference at which he \"apologized to the French people\" and acknowledged that he had committed an \"error\" in employing family members as parliamentary assistants, but appended that he \"never broke the law\". He also argued that his wife's \"salary was perfectly justified\", adding that everything reported by the press on the issue was \"legal and transparent\". He said he would not reimburse the payments received by his wife or children, and, saying that he had \"nothing to hide\", divulged his property holdings. In addition to promising that his lawyers would question the competency of the PNF to carry out the investigation, he lambasted a \"media lynching\" of his campaign. His remarks followed Jupp\u00e9's declaration that \"NO means NO\" earlier in the day in response to rumors that he might replace Fillon as the party's candidate should he decide to drop his bid.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fran\u00e7ois Fillon \" pr\u00e9sente ses excuses \" et maintient sa candidature|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/affaire-penelope-fillon/article/2017/02/06/francois-fillon-presente-ses-excuses-et-maintient-sa-candidature_5075470_5070021.html|agency=Agence France-Presse|newspaper=Le Monde|date=6 February 2017|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Nicolas Sarkozy February 2015.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Sarkozy in 2015]]\n\n''Le Canard encha\u00een\u00e9'' continued its run of stories on Fillon in its issue of 8 February, revealing that Penelope Fillon collected severance payments totaling \u20ac45,000, with \u20ac16,000 in August 2002 for the period 1998\u20132002 and \u20ac29,000 in 2013 for seventeen months of employment for which she earned \u20ac65,839. The satirical weekly also asserted that she received a double salary during the summer of 2002, as she was hired by Joulaud's office on 13 July, more than a month before her contract as a parliamentary assistant with her husband expired, on 21 August. Although aides are eligible to collect severance payments, the law does not permit such a high level for parliamentary assistants. An article in the same issue reported that Marie Fillon was simultaneously employed as a parliamentary assistant while training to become a lawyer, taking the first post in October 2005 and entering the {{abbr|EFB|l'\u00e9cole de formation du barreau}} in January 2006. Fillon responded to the claims in a press release by saying that ''Le Canard encha\u00een\u00e9'' conflated the amount his wife collected in November 2013 with reported earnings in August 2007 after the conclusion of her work with Joulaud,<ref>{{cite news|title=Penelope Fillon a re\u00e7u 45 000 euros d\u2019indemnit\u00e9s de licenciement, selon \" Le Canard encha\u00een\u00e9 \"|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/affaire-penelope-fillon/article/2017/02/07/l-assemblee-a-verse-a-penelope-fillon-45-000-euros-d-indemnites-de-licenciement-selon-le-canard-enchaine_5076127_5070021.html|agency=Agence France-Presse|newspaper=Le Monde|date=7 February 2017|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref> and denounced the paper's allegations as \"lies\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Yohan Blavignat|title=Fran\u00e7ois Fillon d\u00e9nonce les \"mensonges\" du Canard encha\u00een\u00e9|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/elections/presidentielles/2017/02/07/35003-20170207ARTFIG00295-francois-fillon-denonce-les-mensonges-du-canard-enchaine.php|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=8 February 2017|accessdate=3 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170302073328/http://www.lefigaro.fr/elections/presidentielles/2017/02/07/35003-20170207ARTFIG00295-francois-fillon-denonce-les-mensonges-du-canard-enchaine.php|archivedate= 2 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 February, Fillon seemingly withdrew his earlier promise that he would terminate his candidacy if placed under formal investigation, saying \"even if I am put under investigation, nothing will stop me\" in private.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Dominique Tenza|author2=Marc-Olivier Fogiel|author3=L\u00e9a Stassinet|title=Fran\u00e7ois Fillon serait pr\u00eat \u00e0 rester candidat en cas de mise en examen|url=http://www.rtl.fr/actu/politique/francois-fillon-serait-pret-a-rester-candidat-meme-en-cas-de-mise-en-examen-7787283370|publisher=RTL|date=16 February 2017|accessdate=3 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170304192802/http://www.rtl.fr/actu/politique/francois-fillon-serait-pret-a-rester-candidat-meme-en-cas-de-mise-en-examen-7787283370|archivedate= 4 March 2017}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Le Figaro]]'' published on 17 February, he insisted on continuing his campaign, declaring \"I am the candidate and I will continue until victory\" and that the closer to the election it was, the \"more scandalous it would be to deprive the right and centre of a candidate\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Olivier Beaumont|title=Fillon candidat, m\u00eame s'il \u00e9tait mis en examen|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/politique/fillon-candidat-meme-s-il-etait-mis-en-examen-17-02-2017-6687711.php|newspaper=Le Parisien|date=17 February 2017|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref> On 24 February the PNF finally opened a judicial investigation into the \"embezzlement of public funds, [...] influence-peddling and failure to comply with transparency obligations of the [[Haute Autorit\u00e9 pour la transparence de la vie publique|HATVP]]\" against Fran\u00e7ois Fillon, his wife, two of his children, and Marc Joulaud (who were left unnamed, presumably, to allow for expanding the investigation to other suspects, if necessary). The OCLCIFF, which failed to unearth any tangible proof of work by Fillon's wife as a parliamentary assistant to her husband from 1988 to 1990, 1998 to 2000, and 2012 to 2013 or to Marc Joulaud from 2002 to 2007, and was unconvinced by the two reviews in the ''Revue des deux Mondes'' attributed to Penelope Fillon, tasked three investigative judges to continue pursuing the affair.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Franck Johann\u00e8s|author2=Maxime Vaudano|title=Affaire Fillon : le Parquet national financier ouvre une information judiciaire|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/affaire-penelope-fillon/article/2017/02/24/affaire-fillon-le-parquet-national-financier-ouvre-une-information-judiciaire_5085285_5070021.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=24 February 2017|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref> These three judges were identified on 27 February as [[Serge Tournaire]], St\u00e9phanie Tacheau, and Aude Buresi.<ref>{{cite news|title=Affaire Fillon : trois juges d'instruction, dont Serge Tournaire, nomm\u00e9s pour mener l'enqu\u00eate|url=http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/francois-fillon/affaires-fillon/affaire-fillon-trois-juges-d-instruction-dont-serge-tournaire-nommes-pour-mener-l-enquete_2074039.html|publisher=franceinfo|date=27 February 2017|accessdate=3 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170303012648/http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/francois-fillon/affaires-fillon/affaire-fillon-trois-juges-d-instruction-dont-serge-tournaire-nommes-pour-mener-l-enquete_2074039.html|archivedate= 3 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Lagarde photo profil (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|150px|Jean-Christophe Lagarde in 2015]]\n\nOn 1 March, Fillon was informed that he was summoned to appear before the judges and likely to be placed under formal investigation \u2013 generally a precursor to an eventual indictment \u2013 on 15 March.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Vivien Vergnaud|author2=Herv\u00e9 Gattegno|title=Fillon convoqu\u00e9 par les juges d'instruction aux fins de mise en examen|url=http://www.lejdd.fr/Politique/Fillon-convoque-par-les-juges-d-instruction-851132|newspaper=Le Journal du Dimanche|date=1 March 2017|accessdate=4 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170304115041/http://www.lejdd.fr/Politique/Fillon-convoque-par-les-juges-d-instruction-851132|archivedate= 4 March 2017}}</ref> In the subsequent hours and days, hundreds of campaign members, allies, and supporters rescinded their support for Fillon, including the [[Union of Democrats and Independents]] (UDI), a centre-right party whose president [[Jean-Christophe Lagarde]] backed Jupp\u00e9 in the primary, suspended its participation in the campaign.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Lucas Burel|author2=Alexandre Sulzer|title=Plantage de Jupp\u00e9, l\u00e2chage de Lagarde: la journ\u00e9e cauchemardesque de Fillon|url=http://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/politique/elections/plantage-de-juppe-lachage-de-lagarde-la-journee-cauchemardesque-de-fillon_1884650.html|newspaper=L'Express|date=1 March 2017|accessdate=4 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170303044240/http://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/politique/elections/plantage-de-juppe-lachage-de-lagarde-la-journee-cauchemardesque-de-fillon_1884650.html|archivedate= 3 March 2017}}</ref> fifteen campaign staffers,<ref>{{cite news|title=D\u00e9fections en cha\u00eene dans l\u2019\u00e9quipe de campagne de Fillon|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2017/03/02/defections-en-chaine-dans-la-campagne-de-francois-fillon_5088101_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=2 March 2017|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref> and hundreds of others; a total of 306 elected officials and members of the Fillon campaign withdrew their support for the candidate by 5 March.<ref>{{cite news|title=Le compteur des l\u00e2cheurs de Fillon|url=http://www.liberation.fr/apps/2017/03/compteur-lacheurs-fillon/|newspaper=Lib\u00e9ration|date=1 March 2017|accessdate=5 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170305135222/http://www.liberation.fr/apps/2017/03/compteur-lacheurs-fillon/|archivedate= 5 March 2017}}</ref> Many of those rescinding their support speculated about the potential return of Jupp\u00e9 to replace Fillon as the party's candidate, with Fenech urging elected officials file sponsorships for the ex-primary candidate.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Alexandre Lemari\u00e9|author2=Matthieu Goar|title=Fran\u00e7ois Fillon l\u00e2ch\u00e9 de toutes parts|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2017/03/03/francois-fillon-lache-de-toutes-parts_5088554_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=3 March 2017|accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref> Meanwhile, associates of Jupp\u00e9 indicated that he was apparently warming to the idea of stepping in to run if needed, \"ready but loyal\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Alain Auffray|title=Remplacer Fillon ? Jupp\u00e9 serait \"pr\u00eat mais loyal\"|url=http://www.liberation.fr/france/2017/03/02/remplacer-fillon-juppe-serait-pret-mais-loyal_1552764|newspaper=Lib\u00e9ration|date=2 March 2017|accessdate=5 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170303033258/http://www.liberation.fr/france/2017/03/02/remplacer-fillon-juppe-serait-pret-mais-loyal_1552764|archivedate= 3 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Alain Jupp\u00e9 \u00e0 Qu\u00e9bec en 2015 (cropped 2).jpg|thumb|right|150px|Alain Jupp\u00e9 in 2015]]\n\nDespite this chain of defections, Fran\u00e7ois Fillon remained defiant, holding a rally at the [[Trocad\u00e9ro]] on that afternoon intended as show of force.<ref>{{cite news|title=Affaire Fillon : le rassemblement au Trocad\u00e9ro, dimanche, suscite des oppositions \u00e0 droite|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/affaire-penelope-fillon/article/2017/03/02/affaire-fillon-le-rassemblement-au-trocadero-dimanche-suscite-des-oppositions-a-droite_5088320_5070021.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=2 March 2017|accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref> He then appeared on ''20 heures'' on France 2 that evening, during which he refused to give up his candidacy, saying that \"there is no alternative\" and adding that \"no one today can stop me from being a candidate\", insisting that \"it is not the party that will decide\" the fate of his candidacy. He said that the rally at the Trocad\u00e9ro cemented his legitimacy, and that though he would have stepped down two months ago if indicted then, it was now too close to the presidential election and it would be unfair to voters of the right if he quit now. With a \"political committee\" planned for the following day, he proposed to assemble a modified campaign team, naming Fran\u00e7ois Baroin, [[\u00c9ric Ciotti]], and [[Luc Chatel]], in an attempt to rally support around his candidacy.<ref>{{cite news|title=En direct : Fran\u00e7ois Fillon est l\u2019invit\u00e9 du 20 heures de France 2|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/affaire-penelope-fillon/live/2017/03/05/en-direct-rassemblement-au-trocadero-en-soutien-a-fillon_5089561_5070021.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=5 March 2017|accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref> Immediately after Fillon's appearance, Jupp\u00e9 announced on Twitter that he give a statement to the press in Bordeaux at 10:30 CET the day after.<ref>{{cite web|title=Alain Jupp\u00e9 fera une d\u00e9claration lundi \u00e0 10h30|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/2017/03/05/97001-20170305FILWWW00200-alain-juppe-fera-une-declaration-demain-a-10h30.php|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=5 March 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nJupp\u00e9 officially announced his abstention from the race on 6 March, saying that \"for me, it is too late\", and added that Fillon was at a \"dead end\" with his allegations of political assassination.<ref name=\"AJ-renounce\">{{cite news|author1=Alexandre Lemari\u00e9|author2=Matthieu Goar|title=Jupp\u00e9 renonce, la droite au bord de la rupture|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2017/03/06/juppe-renonce-la-droite-au-bord-de-la-rupture_5089836_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=6 March 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref> The same day, the party's \"political committee\" rallied behind Fillon, unanimously reaffirming its support for his candidacy.<ref>{{cite news|title=Les R\u00e9publicains font le pari d\u2019un rassemblement derri\u00e8re Fran\u00e7ois Fillon|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2017/03/06/nicolas-sarkozy-propose-une-reunion-avec-francois-fillon-et-alain-juppe-pour-trouver-une-voie-de-sortie_5089798_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=6 March 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref> The same day, ''Le Canard encha\u00een\u00e9'' revealed that Fillon had failed to declare to the HATVP a \u20ac50,000 loan from Marc Ladreit de Lacharri\u00e8re, president of the ''Revue des deux Mondes''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fran\u00e7ois Fillon a \"oubli\u00e9\" de d\u00e9clarer un pr\u00eat de 50.000 euros|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/elections/presidentielle/presidentielle-fillon-avait-emprunte-50-000-euros-a-ladreit-de-lacharriere-07-03-2017-6741180.php|agency=Agence France-Presse|newspaper=Le Parisien|date=7 March 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref> The UDI renewed its support for Fillon that evening, albeit only conditionally.<ref>{{cite news|title=L'UDI attend des \"initiatives\" de Fillon mais valide l'accord sur les investitures|url=http://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/politique/elections/l-udi-attend-des-initiatives-de-fillon-mais-valide-l-accord-sur-les-investitures_1886800.html|agency=Agence France-Presse|newspaper=L'Express|date=7 March 2017|accessdate=10 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170310051156/http://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/politique/elections/l-udi-attend-des-initiatives-de-fillon-mais-valide-l-accord-sur-les-investitures_1886800.html|archivedate=10 March 2017}}</ref> On 13 March, ''Le Parisien'' revealed that investigators discovered suspicious wire transfers made by Marie and Charles Fillon to their father while employed by him, with Marie returning \u20ac33,000 of the \u20ac46,000 she was paid. Charles Fillon, in his hearing, referred to similar transfers to his parents' joint account, worth about 30% of his salary.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Jean-Michel D\u00e9cugis|author2=Eric Pelletier|title=EXCLUSIF. Des virements des enfants Fillon intriguent les enqu\u00eateurs|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/elections/presidentielle/affaire-fillon-un-mariage-et-quelques-arrangements-13-03-2017-6759579.php|newspaper=Le Parisien|date=13 March 2017|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn the morning of 14 March, Fillon was placed under formal investigation for misuse of public funds, embezzlement, and failure to comply with HATVP disclosure requirements.<ref>{{cite news|author=L\u00e9a Stassinet|title=Fran\u00e7ois Fillon mis en examen : quels sont les motifs ?|url=http://www.rtl.fr/actu/politique/quels-sont-les-motifs-de-la-mise-en-examen-de-francois-fillon-7787668391|publisher=RTL|date=14 March 2017|accessdate=14 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315085704/http://www.rtl.fr/actu/politique/quels-sont-les-motifs-de-la-mise-en-examen-de-francois-fillon-7787668391|archivedate=15 March 2017}}</ref> On 16 March the investigation into Fillon was extended to \"aggravated fraud, forgery, and falsification of records\". In particular, the probe sought to determine whether documents seized during a search of the National Assembly in March were forged in order to corroborate the veracity of Penelope Fillon's work as a parliamentary assistant.<ref>{{cite news|title=Affaires Fillon : l'enqu\u00eate \u00e9largie \u00e0 des faits d\u2019\"escroquerie aggrav\u00e9e\", de \"faux et usage de faux\"|url=http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/francois-fillon/affaires-fillon/affaires-fillon-l-enquete-elargie-a-des-faits-d-escroquerie-aggravee-de-faux-et-usage-de-faux_2108340.html|publisher=franceinfo|date=21 March 2017|accessdate=21 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170322203236/http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/francois-fillon/affaires-fillon/affaires-fillon-l-enquete-elargie-a-des-faits-d-escroquerie-aggravee-de-faux-et-usage-de-faux_2108340.html|archivedate=22 March 2017}}</ref> The investigation was also expanded into possible influence-peddling related to Fillon's consulting firm 2F Conseil, which was previously hired by billionaire Marc Ladreit de Lacharri\u00e8re, owner of the ''Revue des deux Mondes'', which employed Penelope Fillon. In 2013 de Lacharri\u00e8re also provided a \u20ac50,000 loan to Fran\u00e7ois Fillon, who failed to declare it as legally required.<ref>{{cite news|author=Simon Piel|title=Affaire Fillon : l\u2019enqu\u00eate \u00e9largie \u00e0 des faits d\u2019\" escroquerie aggrav\u00e9e \", \" de faux et usage de faux \"|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/affaire-penelope-fillon/article/2017/03/21/affaire-fillon-l-enquete-elargie-a-des-faits-d-escroquerie-aggravee-de-faux-et-usage-de-faux_5098534_5070021.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=21 March 2017|accessdate=21 March 2017}}</ref> On ''[[L'\u00c9mission politique]]'' on 23 March, Fillon said that ''Bienvenue Place Beauvau'', a book co-authored by [[Didier Hassoux]] of ''Le Canard encha\u00een\u00e9'', suggested President Hollande ran a shadow cabinet to spread rumours about his opponents, a claim Hassoux subsequently denied.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fran\u00e7ois Hollande et le \"cabinet noir\" : \"On n'a jamais \u00e9crit \u00e7a\", dit un des auteurs du livre cit\u00e9 par Fran\u00e7ois Fillon|url=http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/francois-fillon/penelope-fillon/francois-hollande-et-le-cabinet-noir-on-n-a-jamais-ecrit-ca-selon-un-des-auteurs_2111685.html|publisher=franceinfo|date=23 March 2017|accessdate=25 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170325205300/http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/francois-fillon/penelope-fillon/francois-hollande-et-le-cabinet-noir-on-n-a-jamais-ecrit-ca-selon-un-des-auteurs_2111685.html|archivedate=25 March 2017}}</ref> On 24 March, Marc Joulaud, Fillon's former substitute, was formally placed under investigation for embezzlement of public funds.<ref>{{cite news|title=Affaire Penelope : l'ex-suppl\u00e9ant de Fillon, Marc Joulaud, mis en examen|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/elections/presidentielle/affaire-penelope-l-ex-suppleant-de-fillon-marc-joulaud-entendu-par-les-juges-financiers-24-03-2017-6792627.php|newspaper=Le Parisien|date=24 March 2017|accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref> Penelope Fillon was placed under formal investigation for complicity in and concealment of embezzlement and misuse of public funds, as well as aggravated fraud, on 28 March.<ref>{{cite news|title=Soup\u00e7ons d\u2019emplois fictifs : Penelope Fillon mise en examen|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/affaire-penelope-fillon/article/2017/03/28/soupcons-d-emplois-fictifs-penelope-fillon-mise-en-examen_5102234_5070021.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=28 March 2017|accessdate=28 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 April, ''Mediapart'' revealed that Penelope Fillon had in fact been paid by the National Assembly starting in 1982, not 1986, as earlier claimed by Fran\u00e7ois Fillon.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Michel Del\u00e9an|author2=Mathilde Mathieu|author3=Ellen Salvi|title=Penelope Fillon a \u00e9t\u00e9 r\u00e9mun\u00e9r\u00e9e par l\u2019Assembl\u00e9e nationale d\u00e8s 1982|url=https://www.mediapart.fr/journal/france/100417/penelope-fillon-ete-remuneree-par-l-assemblee-nationale-des-1982|newspaper=Mediapart|date=10 April 2017|accessdate=10 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170410215201/https://www.mediapart.fr/journal/france/100417/penelope-fillon-ete-remuneree-par-l-assemblee-nationale-des-1982|archivedate=10 April 2017}}</ref> The edition of ''Le Canard encha\u00een\u00e9'' set for publication on 12 April revealed that Fran\u00e7ois Fillon secured his then-fianc\u00e9e a job three times the minimum wage in a Parisian ministry as early as 1980 while he was serving as deputy chief of staff to [[Minister of Defence (France)|Minister of Defence]] [[Jo\u00ebl Le Theule]]; her contract ended in 1981, after 15 months, after the Socialists swept into power.<ref>{{cite news|title=Penelope Fillon embauch\u00e9e gr\u00e2ce \u00e0 son mari depuis 1980, selon le \"Canard Encha\u00een\u00e9\"|url=http://tempsreel.nouvelobs.com/en-direct/a-chaud/35699-fillon-presidentielle2017-presidentielle-penelope-penelope.html|newspaper=L'Obs|date=11 April 2017|accessdate=11 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170412062552/http://tempsreel.nouvelobs.com/en-direct/a-chaud/35699-fillon-presidentielle2017-presidentielle-penelope-penelope.html|archivedate=12 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Other incidents ==\n[[File:Yannick Jadot Europe Ecologie 2009-06-03.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Yannick Jadot (EELV) withdrew to support Hamon]]\nAfter securing his party's nomination in its [[French Socialist Party presidential primary, 2017|presidential primary]] on 29 January 2017, [[Socialist Party (France)|Socialist Party]] (PS) dissident [[Beno\u00eet Hamon]] proposed forming a \"governmental majority\" with [[Jean-Luc M\u00e9lenchon]] of [[la France Insoumise]] (FI) and [[Yannick Jadot]] of [[Europe Ecology \u2013 The Greens]] (EELV), seeking to \"reconcile the left and the environmentalists\". Though M\u00e9lenchon had earlier demonstrated hostility to the possibility of an alliance, he expressed \"satisfaction\" with Hamon's sentiments shortly after the primary.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hamon propose une \" majorit\u00e9 gouvernementale \" \u00e0 M\u00e9lenchon et Jadot|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2017/01/29/hamon-propose-une-majorite-gouvernementale-a-melenchon-et-jadot_5071177_4854003.html|agency=Agence France-Presse|newspaper=Le Monde|date=29 January 2017|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref> On 23 February, Jadot cemented an agreement to withdraw his candidacy in favor of Hamon,<ref name=\"Jadot-withdraw\"/> but on 26 February Hamon acknowledged that talks to secure an alliance with M\u00e9lenchon had failed, the pair only agreeing to a code of mutual respect.<ref>{{cite news|author=Rapha\u00eblle Besse Desmouli\u00e8res|author2=Bastien Bonnefous|title=Beno\u00eet Hamon cl\u00f4t le premier chapitre de sa campagne : celui des alliances|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2017/02/27/benoit-hamon-clot-le-premier-chapitre-de-sa-campagne-celui-des-alliances_5086030_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=27 February 2017|accessdate=7 April 2017}}</ref> The talks failed in part because of the candidates' differing positions on matters related to the [[European Union]] (EU), [[European Central Bank]] (ECB), EU treaties, European defense, and the obligation to maintain a budget deficit below 3% of GDP, among other divergences.<ref>{{cite news|author=Kim Hullot-Guiot|title=Hamon, M\u00e9lenchon et l\u2019Europe : le jeu des sept diff\u00e9rences|url=http://www.liberation.fr/elections-presidentielle-legislatives-2017/2017/03/15/hamon-melenchon-et-l-europe-le-jeu-des-sept-differences_1555657|newspaper=Lib\u00e9ration|date=15 March 2017|accessdate=7 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408083030/http://www.liberation.fr/elections-presidentielle-legislatives-2017/2017/03/15/hamon-melenchon-et-l-europe-le-jeu-des-sept-differences_1555657|archivedate= 8 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring a trip to [[Algeria]] on 15 February, [[Emmanuel Macron]], candidate of [[En Marche!]], remarked in an interview with local press that the French presence in the country had been a \"crime against humanity\" and \"truly barbaric\", drawing the ire of numerous right-wing French politicians. [[Fran\u00e7ois Fillon]] of [[the Republicans (France)|the Republicans]] denounced Macron's remarks as a \"hatred of our history, this constant repentance is unworthy of a candidate for the presidency of the Republic\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Emmanuel Macron qualifie la colonisation de \"crime contre l'humanit\u00e9\" : la pol\u00e9mique en quatre questions|url=http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/emmanuel-macron/emmanuel-macron-qualifie-la-colonisation-de-crime-contre-l-humanite-la-polemique-en-quatre-questions_2062385.html|publisher=franceinfo|date=16 February 2017|accessdate=3 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307024311/http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/emmanuel-macron/emmanuel-macron-qualifie-la-colonisation-de-crime-contre-l-humanite-la-polemique-en-quatre-questions_2062385.html|archivedate= 7 March 2017}}</ref> Seeking to put aside the controversy in a meeting in [[Toulon]] on 18 February, he attempted to qualify his remarks, saying that he was \"sorry\" for having \"hurt\" and \"offended\" many as a result, but nevertheless continued to insist on acknowledging that France had a responsibility for its colonial past, not just in Algeria.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pol\u00e9mique sur la colonisation : \u00e0 Toulon, Macron ose un \"Je vous ai compris\"|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/elections/presidentielle/candidats-et-programmes/polemique-sur-la-colonisation-a-toulon-macron-ose-un-je-vous-ai-compris-18-02-2017-6691947.php|agency=Agence France-Presse|newspaper=Le Parisien|date=18 February 2017|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref> His remarks were followed by a temporary resurgence for Fillon in polls of voting intentions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle-Sondage : Fillon, deuxi\u00e8me, repasse devant Macron au premier tour|url=http://www.europe1.fr/politique/presidentielle-fillon-deuxieme-double-desormais-macron-au-premier-tour-2984330|publisher=Europe 1|date=21 February 2017|accessdate=3 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170223070409/http://www.europe1.fr/politique/presidentielle-fillon-deuxieme-double-desormais-macron-au-premier-tour-2984330|archivedate=23 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Marine Le Pen Parlement europ\u00e9en Strasbourg 1er juillet 2014.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Marine Le Pen at [[Seat of the European Parliament in Strasbourg|Strasbourg]] in 2014]]\n\n{{anchor|FN use of European Parliament assistants}}The various investigations of the fictitious employment of 29 parliamentary assistants to 23 [[National Front (France)|National Front]] (FN) [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]]s, implicating the entourage of [[Marine Le Pen]],<ref>{{cite news|author=Abel Mestre|title=Qui sont les frontistes vis\u00e9s par l\u2019enqu\u00eate europ\u00e9enne pour fraude ?|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/politique/article/2015/03/11/qui-sont-les-frontistes-vises-par-l-enquete-europeenne-pour-fraude_4591161_823448.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=11 March 2015|accessdate=9 April 2017}}</ref> continued through 2017. These fictitious jobs would constitute \u20ac7.5 million in losses for European taxpayers from the period 2010 to 2016. The [[European Anti-fraud Office]] ({{abbr|OLAF|Office europ\u00e9en de lutte antifraude}}) pursued the case, establishing that one of Le Pen's parliamentary assistants, Catherine Griset, never secured a lease in Brussels during the five years she was employed and only rarely appeared in the European Parliament, while another, Thierry L\u00e9gier, worked as a bodyguard at the same time.<ref>{{cite news|author=Maxime Vaudano|title=Les trois affaires qui menacent Marine Le Pen et le Front national|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/les-decodeurs/article/2017/02/02/les-trois-affaires-qui-menacent-marine-le-pen-et-le-front-national_5073473_4355770.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=2 February 2017|accessdate=9 April 2017}}</ref> Though the European Parliament demanded that Le Pen return \u20ac298,392 by 31 January 2018,<ref name=\"MLP-refuse\">{{cite news|title=Marine Le Pen refuse de restituer 300 000 euros au Parlement europ\u00e9en|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/politique/article/2017/01/31/marine-le-pen-refuse-de-restituer-300-000-euros-au-parlement-europeen_5072351_823448.html|agency=Reuters|newspaper=Le Monde|date=31 January 2017|accessdate=9 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"MLP-amt\">{{cite news|title=Assistants parlementaires : le Parlement europ\u00e9en r\u00e9pond \u00e0 Marine Le Pen|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/europe/article/2017/02/03/assistants-parlementaires-le-parlement-europeen-repond-a-marine-le-pen_5074271_3214.html|agency=Agence France-Presse|newspaper=Le Monde|date=3 February 2017|accessdate=9 April 2017}}</ref> representing the salary \"unduly paid\" to Griset,<ref>{{cite news|author=Marc de Boni|title=Marine Le Pen refuse de rembourser 300.000 euros \u00e0 Bruxelles|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/elections/presidentielles/2017/01/27/35003-20170127ARTFIG00190-assistants-parlementaires-marine-le-pen-sommee-de-payer-340000-euros.php|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=27 January 2017|accessdate=9 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170407111916/http://www.lefigaro.fr/elections/presidentielles/2017/01/27/35003-20170127ARTFIG00190-assistants-parlementaires-marine-le-pen-sommee-de-payer-340000-euros.php|archivedate= 7 April 2017}}</ref> she refused to do so,<ref name=\"MLP-refuse\"/> and the European Parliament began to reduce her salary to reclaim the money.<ref name=\"MLP-amt\"/> On 20 February, investigators raided the FN's headquarters in [[Nanterre]] for a second time in connection to the case;<ref>{{cite news|title=Perquisition au FN : le parti d\u00e9nonce une \"op\u00e9ration\" pour \"nuire\" \u00e0 Marine Le Pen|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/elections/presidentielle/perquisition-au-fn-le-parti-denonce-une-operation-pour-nuire-a-marine-le-pen-20-02-2017-6696579.php|agency=Agence France-Presse|newspaper=Le Parisien|date=20 February 2017|accessdate=9 April 2017}}</ref> though Le Pen was summoned to appear before judges on 22 February in the Griset case, she refused to do so until after the [[2017 French legislative election|June legislative elections]], invoking the parliamentary immunity granted to her as a MEP.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Olivier Faye|author2=Simon Piel|title=Assistants parlementaires du FN : Marine Le Pen a refus\u00e9 d\u2019\u00eatre entendue par la police judiciaire|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/police-justice/article/2017/02/24/assistants-parlementaires-marine-le-pen-a-refuse-d-etre-entendue-par-la-police-judiciaire_5084758_1653578.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=24 February 2017|accessdate=9 April 2017}}</ref> On 3 March, summoned to appear before judges to potentially be charged for breach of confidence, Le Pen was absent, again affirming that she would not respond to the case before the end of the campaign.<ref>{{cite news|title=Marine Le Pen convoqu\u00e9e par les juges dans l'affaire des assistants parlementaires|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/elections/presidentielles/2017/03/03/35003-20170303ARTFIG00336-marine-le-pen-convoquee-par-les-juges-dans-l-affaire-des-assistants-parlementaires.php|agency=Agence France-Presse|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=3 March 2017|accessdate=9 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408104703/http://www.lefigaro.fr/elections/presidentielles/2017/03/03/35003-20170303ARTFIG00336-marine-le-pen-convoquee-par-les-juges-dans-l-affaire-des-assistants-parlementaires.php|archivedate= 8 April 2017}}</ref> On 6 March, Charles Hourcade, who served as parliamentary assistant to FN MEP [[Marie-Christine Boutonnet]], faced charges of \"concealment of breach of confidence\" in a separate case; like Le Pen, who described the investigations into the FN's fictitious employment of parliamentary assistants as a \"political operation\", Boutonnet declined to appear before judges.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mise en examen d\u2019un deuxi\u00e8me assistant parlementaire du FN au Parlement europ\u00e9en|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/police-justice/article/2017/03/10/mise-en-examen-d-un-deuxieme-assistant-parlementaire-du-front-national-au-parlement-europeen_5092652_1653578.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=10 March 2017|accessdate=9 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 April, three days before the first round, three police officers were shot and one killed in [[2017 shooting of Paris police officers|an attack]] on the [[Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es]], interrupting the ''15 minutes pour convaincre'' (15 minutes to convince) on [[France 2]], a program featuring successive interviews with the 11 candidates; in the following interviews, the remaining candidates paid tribute to the victims of the attack.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Pierre Godon|author2=Thomas Ba\u00efetto|author3=Louis San|title=REPLAY. Pr\u00e9sidentielle : revivez \"15 minutes pour convaincre\" sur France 2, le grand oral des candidats \u00e0 l'Elys\u00e9e|url=http://www.francetvinfo.fr/elections/presidentielle/direct-presidentielle-sur-france-2-l-emission-politique-recoit-les-candidats-pour-un-grand-oral-faute-de-debat_2154433.html|publisher=franceinfo|date=20 April 2017|accessdate=23 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170421225916/http://www.francetvinfo.fr/elections/presidentielle/direct-presidentielle-sur-france-2-l-emission-politique-recoit-les-candidats-pour-un-grand-oral-faute-de-debat_2154433.html|archivedate=21 April 2017}}</ref> In the wake of the attack, Le Pen and Fillon, suspended campaign activities the following day \u2013 the final day of campaigning \u2013 while Macron canceled two trips and M\u00e9lenchon insisted on maintaining his schedule to demonstrate that he would not allow violence to interrupt the democratic process; Hamon made similar remarks, proceeding with one campaign event the following day.<ref>{{cite news|title=Apr\u00e8s la fusillade sur les Champs-Elys\u00e9es, certains candidats annulent leurs d\u00e9placements|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2017/04/21/apres-la-fusillade-sur-les-champs-elysees-certains-candidats-annulent-leurs-deplacements_5114604_4854003.html|agency=Agence France-Presse|newspaper=Le Monde|date=21 April 2017|accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nA report published on 25 April by the Japan-based security firm [[Trend Micro]] alleged that a group of hackers was targeting the Macron campaign. The group, known as \"Pawn Storm\" (better known as [[APT28]] or \"Fancy Bear\"), is believed to be linked to the Russian state, and was responsible for previous attacks, including on [[TV5Monde]] in April and the Bundestag in May 2015. In particular, the group attempted a [[phishing]] operation, registering four domains strongly resembling those actually used by En Marche!, of which three were domiciled in Ukraine and one in France.<ref>{{cite news|author=Martin Untersinger|title=La campagne d\u2019Emmanuel Macron dans le viseur de pirates russes|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/pixels/article/2017/04/25/la-campagne-d-emmanuel-macron-dans-le-viseur-de-pirates-russes_5117304_4408996.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=25 April 2017|accessdate=28 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n== First round ==\n[[File:French presidential election-Morges CH-IMG 7538.JPG|thumb|right|250px|A voting line of French expatriates in [[Morges]], Switzerland]]\nThe official campaign began on 10 April and ended at midnight on 21 April. During this period, the [[Conseil sup\u00e9rieur de l'audiovisuel]] was to ensure equal speaking time for candidates in audiovisual media.<ref name=\"rules\"/> On French public broadcasters, ten slots were allotted to the eleven candidates from 10 to 18 and 20 April, with nine slots on 19 April and eleven slots \u2013 one for each candidate \u2013 on 21 April, the final day of active campaigning.<ref>{{cite news|title=Suivez la campagne pr\u00e9sidentielle en direct|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/live/2017/04/11/en-direct-posez-vos-questions-sur-l-actualite-politique_5109184_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=11 April 2017|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nVoting in the first round took place on Saturday 22 April from 08:00 to 19:00 (local time) in the [[Overseas France|French overseas departments and territories]] situated east of the [[International Date Line]] and west of [[metropolitan France]] (i.e. [[French Guiana]], [[French Polynesia]], [[Guadeloupe]], [[Martinique]], [[Collectivity of Saint Martin|Saint Martin]], [[Saint Barth\u00e9lemy]] and [[Saint Pierre and Miquelon]]), as well as at [[List of diplomatic missions of France|French diplomatic missions]] in the [[Americas]].<ref name=\"CircularINTA1702262C\">{{cite web|title=Circulaire no INTA1 702262C|url=https://presidentielle2017.conseil-constitutionnel.fr/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Circulaire_INTA1702262C_prefets.pdf|publisher=Conseil constitutionnel|date=17 February 2017|accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref> As of 17:00 (local time), the official turnout figures announced were lower in the overseas departments and territories (except for [[Saint Barth\u00e9lemy]]) than in the [[2012 French presidential election|2012 election]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Pierre Lacombe|title=Election pr\u00e9sidentielle: synth\u00e8se de la participation \u00e0 17 heures dans les Outre-mer|url=http://la1ere.francetvinfo.fr/election-presidentielle-outre-mer-synthese-participation-17-heures-466705.html|publisher=R\u00e9seau Outre-Mer 1re|date=23 April 2017|accessdate=23 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424010232/http://la1ere.francetvinfo.fr/election-presidentielle-outre-mer-synthese-participation-17-heures-466705.html|archivedate=24 April 2017}}</ref> Although overseas voting took place one day before that in [[metropolitan France]], the election results and final turnout figures were announced at the same time, starting at 20:00 ([[Central European Time|Paris time]]) on 23 April, once voting ended in [[metropolitan France]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Cl\u00f4ture du premier tour et proclamation des r\u00e9sultats demain|url=http://la1ere.francetvinfo.fr/guadeloupe/cloture-du-premier-tour-proclamation-resultats-demain-466581.html|publisher=R\u00e9seau Outre-Mer 1re|date=22 April 2017|accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Code \u00e9lectoral - Article L52-2|url=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichCodeArticle.do?cidTexte=LEGITEXT000006070239&idArticle=LEGIARTI000006353106&dateTexte=&categorieLien=cid|publisher=L\u00e9gifrance|date=27 April 2016|accessdate=23 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424174603/https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichCodeArticle.do?cidTexte=LEGITEXT000006070239&idArticle=LEGIARTI000006353106&dateTexte=&categorieLien=cid|archivedate=24 April 2017}}</ref> Voting in [[metropolitan France]] (as well as the [[Overseas France|French overseas departments and territories]] of [[Mayotte]], [[New Caledonia]], [[R\u00e9union]] and [[Wallis and Futuna]], and [[List of diplomatic missions of France|French diplomatic missions]] outside the [[Americas]]) took place on 23 April from 08:00 to 19:00 or 20:00 (local time).<ref name=\"CircularINTA1702262C\"/>\n\nThe official election results were declared by the [[Constitutional Council (France)|Constitutional Council]] on 26 April, with Macron and Le Pen advancing to the second round.<ref name=\"rules\"/>\n\n=== Debates ===\n{{See also|French presidential debates}}\nA debate between [[Fran\u00e7ois Fillon]], [[Beno\u00eet Hamon]], [[Marine Le Pen]], [[Emmanuel Macron]], and [[Jean-Luc M\u00e9lenchon]] took place on 20 March, hosted by [[TF1]] and moderated by journalists [[Anne-Claire Coudray]] and [[Gilles Bouleau]]. It is the first time that a debate prior to the first round was held. The choice of date means that TF1 will not be required to provide candidates with equal speaking time, as [[Conseil sup\u00e9rieur de l'audiovisuel]] (CSA) regulations do not go into force until 9 April, the start of the official campaign. [[Nicolas Dupont-Aignan]], who was not invited, denounced the debate as a \"rape of democracy\",<ref name=\"TF1-20170221\">{{cite news|author1=Maud Pierron|author2=Audrey Kucinskas|title=C'est in\u00e9dit, il y aura deux d\u00e9bats avant le premier tour de la pr\u00e9sidentielle|url=http://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/politique/elections/le-pen-fillon-macron-hamon-et-melenchon-debattront-le-20-mars-sur-tf1_1881403.html|newspaper=L'Express|date=21 February 2017|accessdate=7 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308043605/http://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/politique/elections/le-pen-fillon-macron-hamon-et-melenchon-debattront-le-20-mars-sur-tf1_1881403.html|archivedate= 8 March 2017}}</ref> and the CSA urged TF1 to guarantee fair speaking time for other candidates.<ref>{{cite news|title=D\u00e9bat pr\u00e9sidentiel sur TF1 : Nicolas Dupont-Aignan saisit le conseil d'\u00c9tat|url=http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/nicolas-dupont-aignan/debat-presidentiel-sur-tf1-nicolas-dupont-aignan-saisit-le-conseil-d-etat_2085713.html|publisher=franceinfo|date=7 March 2017|accessdate=12 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313043748/http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/nicolas-dupont-aignan/debat-presidentiel-sur-tf1-nicolas-dupont-aignan-saisit-le-conseil-d-etat_2085713.html|archivedate=13 March 2017}}</ref> Dupont-Aignan filed an appeal that was rejected in part because he had already received airtime proportionate to his support.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle: TF1 n'invitera pas Dupont Aignan|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-eco/2017/03/16/97002-20170316FILWWW00358-presidentielle-tf1-n-invitera-pas-dupont-aignan.php|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=16 March 2017|accessdate=17 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316221601/http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-eco/2017/03/16/97002-20170316FILWWW00358-presidentielle-tf1-n-invitera-pas-dupont-aignan.php|archivedate=16 March 2017}}</ref> On 18 March, appearing on TF1, he quit mid-interview, furious at his exclusion from the network's debate.<ref>{{cite news|title=Furieux contre TF1, Dupont-Aignan quitte en direct le plateau du JT|url=http://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/politique/la-democratie-est-en-danger-nicolas-dupont-aignan-quitte-tf1-en-direct_1890582.html|newspaper=L'Express|date=18 March 2017|accessdate=24 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170325132254/http://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/politique/la-democratie-est-en-danger-nicolas-dupont-aignan-quitte-tf1-en-direct_1890582.html|archivedate=25 March 2017}}</ref> The first debate began with an introductory question \u2013 \"What kind of president do you want to be?\" \u2013 followed by segments on three themes lasting about 50 minutes each: what type of society France should have, what type of economic model France should adopt, and the place of France in the world. The five candidates were given two minutes to answer each question, but opponents had the opportunity to interject 90 seconds in.<ref>{{cite news|author=Louis Hausalter|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle : le programme du premier d\u00e9bat t\u00e9l\u00e9vis\u00e9 sur TF1 le 20 mars|url=https://www.marianne.net/politique/presidentielle-le-programme-du-premier-debat-televise-sur-tf1-le-20-mars|newspaper=Marianne|date=15 March 2017|accessdate=15 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315144150/https://www.marianne.net/politique/presidentielle-le-programme-du-premier-debat-televise-sur-tf1-le-20-mars|archivedate=15 March 2017}}</ref> The debate was three and a half hours long,<ref>{{cite news|author1=Arnaud Forcraud|author2=Ga\u00ebl Vaillant|title=Le Pen, Macron, Fillon, Hamon, M\u00e9lenchon : ce qu'il faut retenir de leur prestation|url=http://www.lejdd.fr/Politique/Le-Pen-Macron-Fillon-Hamon-Melenchon-ce-qu-il-faut-retenir-de-leur-prestation-855737|newspaper=Le Journal du Dimanche|date=21 March 2017|accessdate=21 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170508191456/http://www.lejdd.fr/Politique/Le-Pen-Macron-Fillon-Hamon-Melenchon-ce-qu-il-faut-retenir-de-leur-prestation-855737|archivedate= 8 May 2017}}</ref> and was watched by 9.8 million (47% of the audience share) on [[TF1]], peaking at 11.5 million.<ref>{{cite news|title=Audience : 9,8 millions t\u00e9l\u00e9spectateurs devant le d\u00e9bat pour la pr\u00e9sidentielle sur TF1|url=http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/benoit-hamon/audiences-9-8-millions-telespectateurs-devant-le-debat-pour-la-presidentielle-sur-tf1_2107550.html|publisher=franceinfo|date=21 March 2017|accessdate=21 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170321175315/http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/benoit-hamon/audiences-9-8-millions-telespectateurs-devant-le-debat-pour-la-presidentielle-sur-tf1_2107550.html|archivedate=21 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[BFM TV]] and [[CNews]] hosted the second debate on 4 April at 20:40 CEST, moderated by [[Ruth Elkrief]] and [[Laurence Ferrari]],<ref name=\"debate-BFMTV\">{{cite news|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/medias/2017/02/27/20004-20170227ARTFIG00283-presidentielle-bfmtv-et-cnews-veulent-organiser-un-grand-debat-le-3-ou-4avril.php|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle : BFMTV et CNews veulent organiser un grand d\u00e9bat le 3 ou 4 avril|date=27 February 2017|author=Caroline Sall\u00e9|newspaper=Le Figaro|accessdate=17 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170309182846/http://www.lefigaro.fr/medias/2017/02/27/20004-20170227ARTFIG00283-presidentielle-bfmtv-et-cnews-veulent-organiser-un-grand-debat-le-3-ou-4avril.php|archivedate= 9 March 2017}}</ref> inviting all candidates who qualified to appear on the first-round ballot.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/2017/03/08/97001-20170308FILWWW00306-presidentielle-debat-sur-bfmtv-et-cnews-le-4-avril.php|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle: d\u00e9bat sur BFMTV et CNews le 4 avril|date=8 March 2017|agency=Agence France-Presse|newspaper=Le Figaro|accessdate=15 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316113345/http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/2017/03/08/97001-20170308FILWWW00306-presidentielle-debat-sur-bfmtv-et-cnews-le-4-avril.php|archivedate=16 March 2017}}</ref> The start time, earlier than that of the TF1 debate, was chosen to avoid continuing well past midnight. Three themes were addressed: employment, the French social model, and the protection of the French. The final part of the debate concerned the exercise of power and moralization of public officials. Each of the 11 candidates invited had a minute and a half to answer each question, and other candidates were permitted to challenge their answers. This was the first ever debate including all first-round candidates;<ref name=\"BFMTV-Marianne\">{{cite news|author=Louis Hausalter|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle : voici comment BFMTV et CNews vont faire d\u00e9battre les onze candidats le 4 avril|url=https://www.marianne.net/politique/presidentielle-voici-comment-bfmtv-et-cnews-vont-faire-debattre-les-onze-candidats-le-4|newspaper=Marianne|date=24 March 2017|accessdate=25 March 2017}}</ref> A total of 6.3 million people representing an audience share of 32% viewed the debate; BFM TV alone claimed 5.5 million viewers, equivalent to 28% audience share \u2013 an all-time record for the channel.<ref name=\"BFMTV-1\">{{cite news|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle : le d\u00e9bat \u00e0 onze pulv\u00e9rise les records d'audience de la TNT|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/culture-loisirs/tv/audiences-tv-le-debat-a-onze-pulverise-les-records-de-la-tnt-05-04-2017-6826446.php|newspaper=Le Parisien|date=5 April 2017|accessdate=9 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[France 2]] intended to host a debate with all candidates on 20 April,<ref name=\"TF1-20170221\"/> but on 28 March M\u00e9lenchon stated he was unhappy with its timing, planning not to attend, and would prefer that it be held before 17 April.<ref name=\"JLM-refuse\">{{cite news|author=Caroline Sall\u00e9|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle : M\u00e9lenchon refuse de participer au d\u00e9bat de France 2|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-eco/2017/03/28/97002-20170328FILWWW00111-presidentielle-melenchon-refuse-de-participer-au-debat-de-france-2.php|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=28 March 2017|accessdate=28 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328120712/http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-eco/2017/03/28/97002-20170328FILWWW00111-presidentielle-melenchon-refuse-de-participer-au-debat-de-france-2.php|archivedate=28 March 2017}}</ref> Macron also expressed reservations about the proposed third debate, stating that he wanted only one debate with all 11 candidates before the first round, and preferably not just three days before the first round of voting.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Caroline Sall\u00e9|author2=Marc de Boni|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle : M\u00e9lenchon et Macron remettent en cause le dernier d\u00e9bat sur France 2|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/medias/2017/03/28/20004-20170328ARTFIG00141-presidentielle-jean-luc-melenchon-menace-de-ne-pas-participer-au-debat-de-france-2.php|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=28 March 2017|accessdate=28 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328222356/http://www.lefigaro.fr/medias/2017/03/28/20004-20170328ARTFIG00141-presidentielle-jean-luc-melenchon-menace-de-ne-pas-participer-au-debat-de-france-2.php|archivedate=28 March 2017}}</ref> On 29 March, the CSA indicated that it was \"concerned\" that the date of the debate was too close to the first round, and recommended that candidates and broadcasters work to find an agreement as quickly as possible.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle : le CSA \"pr\u00e9occup\u00e9\" par la date du d\u00e9bat de France 2 le 20 avril|url=http://www.francetvinfo.fr/elections/presidentielle/presidentielle-le-csa-preoccupe-par-la-date-du-debat-de-france-2-le-20-avril_2120147.html|agency=Agence France-Presse|publisher=franceinfo|date=29 March 2017|accessdate=29 March 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170329151048/http://www.francetvinfo.fr/elections/presidentielle/presidentielle-le-csa-preoccupe-par-la-date-du-debat-de-france-2-le-20-avril_2120147.html|archivedate=29 March 2017}}</ref> [[France T\u00e9l\u00e9visions]] decided to maintain the date of 20 April due to the lack of a consensus on an alternative the following day,<ref>{{cite news|title=D\u00e9bat du 20 avril: France T\u00e9l\u00e9visions maintient la date|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/2017/03/30/97001-20170330FILWWW00399-debat-du-20-avril-france-televisions-maintient-la-date.php|agency=Agence France-Presse|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=30 March 2017|accessdate=4 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170404130952/http://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/2017/03/30/97001-20170330FILWWW00399-debat-du-20-avril-france-televisions-maintient-la-date.php|archivedate= 4 April 2017}}</ref> but abandoned plans for a third debate on 5 April, instead proposing that individual candidates be interviewed by [[L\u00e9a Salam\u00e9]] and [[David Pujadas]] during that timeslot.<ref>{{cite news|author=Engu\u00e9rand Renault|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle: France 2 abandonne le second d\u00e9bat entre les onze candidats|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/le-scan/2017/04/05/25001-20170405ARTFIG00248-presidentielle-france-2-abandonne-le-second-debat-entre-les-onze-candidats.php|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=5 April 2017|accessdate=5 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170407063334/http://www.lefigaro.fr/politique/le-scan/2017/04/05/25001-20170405ARTFIG00248-presidentielle-france-2-abandonne-le-second-debat-entre-les-onze-candidats.php|archivedate= 7 April 2017}}</ref> The plan was finally confirmed on 18 April, with France 2 offering successive 15-minute interviews to the 11 candidates with the two hosts.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle : France 2 confirme la tenue de son \u00e9mission politique avec onze candidats|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/elections/presidentielle/presidentielle-france-2-confirme-la-tenue-de-son-emission-politique-avec-onze-candidats-18-04-2017-6863784.php|newspaper=Le Parisien|date=18 April 2017|accessdate=18 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible\" style=\"font-size:90%;text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" colspan=\"15\"|2017 French presidential election first-round debates\n|-\n!style=\"white-space:nowrap;\" rowspan=\"3\"|Date\n!rowspan=\"3\"|Organizers\n!rowspan=\"3\"|Moderators\n!scope=\"col\" colspan=\"11\"|{{Colors|black|#90ff90|&nbsp;P&nbsp;}} Present {{Colors|black|#ff9090|&nbsp;NI&nbsp;}} Non-invitee\n!rowspan=\"3\"|Notes\n|-\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:60px;\"|[[Nathalie Arthaud|Arthaud]]\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:60px;\"|[[Philippe Poutou|Poutou]]\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:60px;\"|[[Jean-Luc M\u00e9lenchon|M\u00e9lenchon]]\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:60px