\"background:#FFED99;\"| '''29%'''\n| 11%\n| 14%\n| 10%\n| colspan=\"3\"| 5%\n| 100%\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| At the last moment\n| colspan=\"2\"| 5%\n| style=\"background:#FBD7D2;\"| '''21%'''\n| 9%\n| style=\"background:#FFED99;\"| '''23%'''\n| 17%\n| 8%\n| 11%\n| colspan=\"3\"| 6%\n| 100%\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! colspan=\"14\"| Agglomeration\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Rural\n| colspan=\"2\"| 3%\n| 18%\n| 5%\n| style=\"background:#FFF7CE;\"| '''21%'''\n| 19%\n| 7%\n| style=\"background:#C1C9FF;\"| '''23%'''\n| colspan=\"3\"| 4%\n| 80%\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Fewer than 20,000 inhabitants\n| colspan=\"2\"| 2%\n| 20%\n| 5%\n| style=\"background:#FFF7CE;\"| '''23%'''\n| 17%\n| 5%\n| style=\"background:#C1C9FF;\"| '''25%'''\n| colspan=\"3\"| 3%\n| 76%\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| 20,000 to 100,000 inhabitants\n| colspan=\"2\"| 1%\n| 21%\n| 7%\n| style=\"background:#FFED99;\"| '''26%'''\n| 18%\n| 2%\n| style=\"background:#E1E6FF;\"| '''24%'''\n| colspan=\"3\"| 1%\n| 73%\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| More than 100,000 inhabitants\n| colspan=\"2\"| 1%\n| 20%\n| 7%\n| style=\"background:#FFED99;\"| '''24%'''\n| style=\"background:#DFEEFF;\"| '''21%'''\n| 4%\n| style=\"background:#E1E6FF;\"| '''21%'''\n| colspan=\"3\"| 2%\n| 78%\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Paris agglomeration\n| colspan=\"2\"| 1%\n| 19%\n| 6%\n| style=\"background:#FFED99;\"| '''29%'''\n| style=\"background:#DFEEFF;\"| '''25%'''\n| 5%\n| 14%\n| colspan=\"3\"| 1%\n| 76%\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! colspan=\"14\"| Religion\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Catholic\n| colspan=\"2\"| 2%\n| 13%\n| 4%\n| style=\"background:#FFF7CE;\"| '''23%'''\n| style=\"background:#B9DAFF;\"| '''28%'''\n| 6%\n| 22%\n| colspan=\"3\"| 2%\n| 80%\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| ''Regular practitioner''\n| colspan=\"2\"| 1%\n| 8%\n| 3%\n| style=\"background:#FFF7CE;\"| '''20%'''\n| style=\"background:#B9DAFF;\"| '''51%'''\n| 5%\n| 11%\n| colspan=\"3\"| 1%\n| 87%\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| ''Occasional practitioner''\n| colspan=\"2\"| 2%\n| 13%\n| 4%\n| style=\"background:#FFF7CE;\"| '''23%'''\n| style=\"background:#B9DAFF;\"| '''27%'''\n| 6%\n| 22%\n| colspan=\"3\"| 3%\n| 80%\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| ''Non-practitioner''\n| colspan=\"2\"| 2%\n| 17%\n| 6%\n| style=\"background:#FFF7CE;\"| '''22%'''\n| 16%\n| 4%\n| style=\"background:#C1C9FF;\"| '''29%'''\n| colspan=\"3\"| 4%\n| 77%\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Others\n| colspan=\"2\"| 2%\n| style=\"background:#F8B3AB;\"| '''23%'''\n| 9%\n| style=\"background:#FFED99;\"| '''23%'''\n| 21%\n| 4%\n| 15%\n| colspan=\"3\"| 3%\n| 72%\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| None\n| colspan=\"2\"| 2%\n| style=\"background:#F8B3AB;\"| '''28%'''\n| 9%\n| style=\"background:#FFF7CE;\"| '''25%'''\n| 7%\n| 4%\n| 23%\n| colspan=\"3\"| 2%\n| 74%\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\"| Demographic\n! style=\"background:{{Lutte Ouvri\u00e8re/meta/color}};\"|\n! style=\"background:{{New Anticapitalist Party/meta/color}};\"|\n! style=\"background:{{La France insoumise/meta/color}};\"|\n! style=\"background:{{Socialist Party (France)/meta/color}};\"|\n! style=\"background:{{En Marche!/meta/color}};\"|\n! style=\"background:{{The Republicans (France)/meta/color}};\"|\n! style=\"background:{{Debout la France/meta/color}};\"|\n! style=\"background:{{National Front (France)/meta/color}};\"|\n! style=\"background:{{Miscellaneous right/meta/color}};\"|\n! style=\"background:{{Popular Republican Union/meta/color}};\"|\n! style=\"background:{{Solidarity and Progress/meta/color}};\"|\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:60px;\"| Turnout\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:60px;\"| [[Nathalie Arthaud|Arthaud]]/<br />[[Philippe Poutou|Poutou]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:60px;\"| [[Jean-Luc M\u00e9lenchon|M\u00e9lenchon]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:60px;\"| [[Beno\u00eet Hamon|Hamon]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:60px;\"| [[Emmanuel Macron|Macron]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:60px;\"| [[Fran\u00e7ois Fillon|Fillon]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:60px;\"| [[Nicolas Dupont-Aignan|Dupont-Aignan]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:60px;\"| [[Marine Le Pen|Le Pen]]\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"3\" style=\"width:60px;\"| Others\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! colspan=\"14\"| Sociology of the electorate\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| colspan=\"14\"| Source: Ipsos France<ref>{{cite web|title=1er tour pr\u00e9sidentielle 2017 : sociologie de l'\u00e9lectorat|url=https://www.ipsos.com/sites/default/files/files-fr-fr/doc_associe/ipsos-sopra-steria_sociologie-des-electorats_23-avril-2017-21h.pdf|publisher=Ipsos France|date=23 April 2017|accessdate=24 April 2017}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Second round ==\n[[File:La Rotonde 2.JPG|thumb|right|250px|''[[Caf\u00e9 de la Rotonde|La Rotonde]]'', where Macron celebrated the results of the first round]]\n[[File:Macron and Le Pen Voting Cards.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Voting cards for the second round.]]\n[[File:French Election- Celebrations at The Louvre, Paris (33707026433).jpg|thumb|right|250px|Supporters of Macron celebrating his victory at the [[Louvre]] on 7 May]]\nAfter being eliminated in the first round, both [[Fran\u00e7ois Fillon]] and [[Beno\u00eet Hamon]] called to vote for [[Emmanuel Macron]], while [[Jean-Luc M\u00e9lenchon]] refused to pronounce in favor of either candidate, preferring to first consult activists from his movement.<ref name=\"live-20170423\">{{cite news|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle 2017 : revivez la soir\u00e9e \u00e9lectorale du premier tour|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/live/2017/04/23/presidentielle-2017-resultats-analyses-reactions-suivez-la-soiree-du-premier-tour-en-direct_5115904_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=23 April 2017|accessdate=28 April 2017}}</ref> [[Jean Lassalle]] and [[Nathalie Arthaud]] opted to cast a [[protest vote|blank vote]],<ref name=\"live-20170423\"/><ref name=\"Lassalle-blanc\">{{cite news|title=DIRECT. Pr\u00e9sidentielle : Jean Lassalle votera blanc au second tour|url=http://www.ouest-france.fr/elections/presidentielle/direct-presidentielle-le-pen-renforcee-par-l-episode-whirlpool-4955884|newspaper=Ouest-France|date=28 April 2017|accessdate=28 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428094112/http://www.ouest-france.fr/elections/presidentielle/direct-presidentielle-le-pen-renforcee-par-l-episode-whirlpool-4955884|archivedate=28 April 2017}}</ref> [[Philippe Poutou]] and [[Fran\u00e7ois Asselineau]] gave no voting instructions,<ref name=\"live-20170423\"/> and [[Jacques Cheminade]] only stated that he would personally refuse to vote for Le Pen and denounced the forces of \"financial occupation\".<ref name=\"Cheminade\"/> [[Nicolas Dupont-Aignan]] endorsed Le Pen during the evening of 28 April,<ref name=\"NDA-MLP\"/> and was subsequently revealed as her choice for Prime Minister the following day.<ref>{{cite news|title=Marine Le Pen annonce qu'elle nommera Nicolas Dupont-Aignan Premier ministre si elle est \u00e9lue|url=http://www.bfmtv.com/politique/marine-le-pen-annonce-qu-elle-nommera-nicolas-dupont-aignan-premier-ministre-si-elle-est-elue-1153450.html|publisher=BFM TV|date=29 April 2017|accessdate=30 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170429125747/http://www.bfmtv.com/politique/marine-le-pen-annonce-qu-elle-nommera-nicolas-dupont-aignan-premier-ministre-si-elle-est-elue-1153450.html|archivedate=29 April 2017}}</ref> On 2 May, the result of M\u00e9lenchon's consultation was published, with 36.12% voting for a blank vote, 34.83% supporting a vote for Macron, and 29.05% opting to abstain;<ref>{{cite news|author=Charlie Vandekerkhove|title=Les militants de la France insoumise pl\u00e9biscitent le vote blanc ou l'abstention au second tour|url=http://www.bfmtv.com/politique/la-france-insoumise-devoile-le-resultat-de-sa-consultation-sur-le-second-tour-1155324.html|agency=Agence France-Presse|publisher=BFM TV|date=2 May 2017|accessdate=2 May 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170502192106/http://www.bfmtv.com/politique/la-france-insoumise-devoile-le-resultat-de-sa-consultation-sur-le-second-tour-1155324.html|archivedate= 2 May 2017}}</ref> M\u00e9lenchon, for his part, issued no voting instructions, only urging his supporters not to make the \"terrible error\" of voting for Le Pen.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle : deux tiers des Insoumis de M\u00e9lenchon choisissent le vote blanc ou l'abstention|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/elections/presidentielle/presidentielle-les-insoumis-de-melenchon-choisissent-de-voter-blanc-a-36-02-05-2017-6909717.php|newspaper=Le Parisien|date=2 May 2017|accessdate=7 May 2017}}</ref> [[Jean-Marie Le Pen]] supported his daughter.<ref>{{cite news|author=Arthur Berdah|title=\"Moi, je vote Marine\", annonce Jean-Marie Le Pen|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/elections/presidentielles/2017/04/17/35003-20170417ARTFIG00049-moi-je-vote-marine-annonce-jean-marie-le-pen.php|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=17 April 2017|accessdate=1 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn the evening of the first round, Macron and members of his entourage celebrated the result at ''[[Caf\u00e9 de la Rotonde|La Rotonde]]'', a ''[[brasserie]]'' in the [[6th arrondissement of Paris]]; the move was criticized as premature and complacent, viewed as reminiscent of [[Nicolas Sarkozy]]'s widely criticized post-election celebration at ''[[Fouquet's]]'' in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Le \" moment de c\u0153ur \" de Macron \u00e0 La Rotonde se m\u00eale aux souvenirs du Fouquet\u2019s de Sarkozy|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/big-browser/article/2017/04/24/le-moment-de-c-ur-de-macron-a-la-rotonde-se-mele-aux-souvenirs-du-fouquet-s-de-sarkozy_5116597_4832693.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=24 April 2017|accessdate=27 April 2017}}</ref> On 24 April, Le Pen vacated her position as leader of the National Front on 24 April to focus on her presidential candidacy but remained a member of the party.<ref>{{cite news|title=Marine Le Pen se \" met en cong\u00e9 de la pr\u00e9sidence du Front national \"|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/article/2017/04/24/marine-le-pen-se-met-en-conge-de-la-presidence-du-front-national_5116791_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=24 April 2017|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref> On 26 April, while Macron met with union representatives in his hometown of [[Amiens]] employed at the local [[Whirlpool Corporation|Whirlpool]] factory, slated to close in 2018, Le Pen arrived at the site of the factory outdoors around noon in a visit to speak with workers, catching Macron by surprise. When Macron subsequently arrived at the factory site in mid-afternoon, he was whistled and heckled by a hostile crowd, with some shouting \"Marine pr\u00e9sidente\", before he subsequently spoke with the workers for half an hour.<ref>{{cite news|title=Whirlpool : la folle journ\u00e9e d'Emmanuel Macron et Marine Le Pen en quatre actes|url=http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/emmanuel-macron/whirlpool-le-bras-de-fer-entre-emmanuel-macron-et-marine-le-pen-en-quatre-actes_2162846.html|publisher=franceinfo|date=26 April 2017|accessdate=27 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427012157/http://www.francetvinfo.fr/politique/emmanuel-macron/whirlpool-le-bras-de-fer-entre-emmanuel-macron-et-marine-le-pen-en-quatre-actes_2162846.html|archivedate=27 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe official campaign ended at midnight on 5 May.<ref>{{cite news|title=Revivez le dernier jour de la campagne pr\u00e9sidentielle|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/live/2017/05/05/presidentielle-en-direct-dernier-jour-de-campagne-pour-emmanuel-macron-et-marine-le-pen_5122576_4854003.html|newspaper=Le Monde|date=5 May 2017|accessdate=5 May 2017}}</ref> Just minutes before the election silence went into effect, [[2017 Macron e-mail leaks|emails and documents from the Macron campaign were leaked]] on a file-sharing website. The campaign team subsequently issued a statement claiming that they had been compromised, and alleged that the leak contained both real as well and some fabricated documents. Numerama, an online publication focusing on digital life, described the leaked material as \"utterly mundane\", consisting of \"the contents of a hard drive and several emails of co-workers and En Marche political officials.\" Leaked documents included \"memos, bills, loans for amounts that are hardly over-the-top, recommendations and other reservations, amidst, of course, exchanges that are strictly personal and private \u2014 personal notes on the rain and sunshine, a confirmation email for the publishing of a book, reservation of a table for friends, etc.\", in addition to some documents unrelated to Macron.<ref>{{cite news|author=Julien Cadot|title=#MacronLeaks : \u00e0 24h du vote, des opposants au candidat En Marche jouent leurs derni\u00e8res cartes|url=http://www.numerama.com/politique/255850-macronleaks-a-24h-du-vote-des-opposants-au-candidat-en-marche-jouent-leurs-dernieres-cartes.html|publisher=Numerama|date=5 May 2017|accessdate=7 May 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170506180719/http://www.numerama.com/politique/255850-macronleaks-a-24h-du-vote-des-opposants-au-candidat-en-marche-jouent-leurs-dernieres-cartes.html|archivedate= 6 May 2017}}</ref><!-- translation sourced from https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/05/world/europe/france-macron-hacking.html -->\n\nVoting in the second round took place on Saturday 6 May from 08:00 to 19:00 (local time) in the [[Overseas France|French overseas departments and territories]] situated east of the [[International Date Line]] and west of [[metropolitan France]] (i.e. [[French Guiana]], [[French Polynesia]], [[Guadeloupe]], [[Martinique]], [[Collectivity of Saint Martin|Saint Martin]], [[Saint Barth\u00e9lemy]] and [[Saint Pierre and Miquelon]]), as well as at [[List of diplomatic missions of France|French diplomatic missions]] in the [[Americas]]. Voting in [[metropolitan France]] (as well as the French overseas departments and territories of [[Mayotte]], [[New Caledonia]], [[R\u00e9union]] and [[Wallis and Futuna]], and [[List of diplomatic missions of France|French diplomatic missions]] outside the [[Americas]]) took place on Sunday 7 May from 08:00 to 19:00 or 20:00 (local time).<ref name=\"CircularINTA1702262C\"/> The results of the second round were officially proclaimed on 10 May.<ref>{{cite web|title=Communiqu\u00e9 sur l'annonce des r\u00e9sultats officiels du second tour de l\u2019\u00e9lection pr\u00e9sidentielle|url=http://www.conseil-constitutionnel.fr/conseil-constitutionnel/francais/actualites/2017/communique-sur-l-annonce-des-resultats-officiels-du-second-tour-de-l-election-presidentielle.148975.html|publisher=Conseil constitutionnel|date=5 May 2017|accessdate=8 May 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170508154225/http://www.conseil-constitutionnel.fr/conseil-constitutionnel/francais/actualites/2017/communique-sur-l-annonce-des-resultats-officiels-du-second-tour-de-l-election-presidentielle.148975.html|archivedate= 8 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Debate ===\nThough TF1 initially had plans to hold its own debate between the first and second round, it instead jointly hosted one with France 2.<ref name=\"challenges-debat\">{{cite news|author=Marc Baudriller|title=TF1 renonce \u00e0 organiser son propre d\u00e9bat d'entre les deux tours|url=https://www.challenges.fr/election-presidentielle-2017/la-campagne-dans-les-medias/tf1-renonce-a-organiser-son-propre-debat-d-entre-les-deux-tours_464955|newspaper=Challenges|date=5 April 2017|accessdate=6 April 2017}}</ref> BFM TV also originally intended to host a debate between the two rounds, and it sought to join France 2 and TF1 in co-hosting a single debate but was rebuffed; while all channels were welcome to broadcast the debate, CEO of France T\u00e9l\u00e9visions [[Delphine Ernotte]] said, it would not accept such an arrangement with BFM TV, which would mean three journalists moderating the debate.<ref>{{cite news|author=Louis Hausalter|title=D\u00e9bat du second tour : TF1 et France 2 refusent un plan \u00e0 trois avec BFMTV|url=https://www.marianne.net/medias/debat-du-second-tour-tf1-et-france-2-refusent-un-plan-trois-avec-bfmtv|newspaper=Marianne|date=12 April 2017|accessdate=19 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419002629/https://www.marianne.net/medias/debat-du-second-tour-tf1-et-france-2-refusent-un-plan-trois-avec-bfmtv|archivedate=19 April 2017}}</ref> Unlike [[Jacques Chirac]], who refused to debate [[Jean-Marie Le Pen]] after the latter's surprise advancement to the second round in the [[2002 French presidential election|2002 presidential election]], Macron agreed to debate Marine Le Pen on 3 May.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle : Macron accepte de participer au d\u00e9bat TV de l'entre-deux-tours face \u00e0 Le Pen|url=http://www.europe1.fr/politique/presidentielle-macron-accepte-de-participer-au-debat-tv-de-lentre-deux-tours-face-a-le-pen-3310136|agency=Agence France-Presse|publisher=Europe 1|date=24 April 2017|accessdate=27 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426055932/http://www.europe1.fr/politique/presidentielle-macron-accepte-de-participer-au-debat-tv-de-lentre-deux-tours-face-a-le-pen-3310136|archivedate=26 April 2017}}</ref> The debate, planned to start at 21:00 CEST and last 2 hours and 20 minutes, was originally to be moderated by [[Gilles Bouleau]] and [[David Pujadas]]; however, after the [[Conseil sup\u00e9rieur de l'audiovisuel]] (CSA) raised concerns that the moderators would both be men for the first time since 1995, the final pair of [[Christophe Jakubyszyn]] of TF1 and [[Nathalie Saint-Cricq]] of France 2 was chosen.<ref name=\"debatedetails\">{{cite news|author=L\u00e9a Stassinet|title=Pr\u00e9sidentielle 2017 : comment va se d\u00e9rouler le d\u00e9bat de l'entre-deux tours ?|url=http://www.rtl.fr/actu/politique/presidentielle-2017-comment-va-se-derouler-le-debat-de-l-entre-deux-tours-7788296316|publisher=RTL|date=26 April 2017|accessdate=27 April 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427004120/http://www.rtl.fr/actu/politique/presidentielle-2017-comment-va-se-derouler-le-debat-de-l-entre-deux-tours-7788296316|archivedate=27 April 2017}}</ref> A total of 16.5 million people (60% of the audience share) watched the debate.<ref>{{cite news|title=16,5 millions de Fran\u00e7ais devant le dernier d\u00e9bat|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/medias/2017/05/04/20004-20170504ARTFIG00106-165-millions-de-francais-devant-le-dernier-debat.php|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=4 May 2017|accessdate=9 May 2017|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170509104958/http://www.lefigaro.fr/medias/2017/05/04/20004-20170504ARTFIG00106-165-millions-de-francais-devant-le-dernier-debat.php|archivedate= 9 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe debate was considered to have significantly damaged the image of Le Pen and the FN before the second round of the election, with Le Pen criticized for being overly aggressive, arrogant, and amateur in the topics at hand, and was also attributed as a cause of the poor performance of the FN in the subsequent legislative elections.<ref>{{cite news|author=Dominique Albertini|title=Un d\u00e9bat et de gros d\u00e9g\u00e2ts pour le FN|url=http://www.liberation.fr/france/2017/08/09/un-debat-et-de-gros-degats-pour-le-fn_1589086|newspaper=Lib\u00e9ration|date=9 August 2017|accessdate=21 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible\" style=\"font-size:90%;text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" colspan=\"6\"|2017 French presidential election second-round debate\n|-\n!style=\"white-space:nowrap;\" rowspan=\"3\"|Date\n!rowspan=\"3\"|Organizers\n!rowspan=\"3\"|Moderators\n!scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\"|{{Colors|black|#90ff90|&nbsp;P&nbsp;}} Present\n!rowspan=\"3\"|Notes\n|-\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:60px;\"|[[Emmanuel Macron|Macron]]\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:60px;\"|[[Marine Le Pen|Le Pen]]