hTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000036593761|publisher=L\u00e9gifrance|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=13 February 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*Elgie, Robert. \"The election of Emmanuel Macron and the new French party system: a return to the \u00e9ternel marais?.\" ''Modern & Contemporary France'' 26.1 (2018): 15\u201329.\n*Gil, Cameron Michael. \"Spatial analysis of La R\u00e9publique En Marche and French Parties, 2002\u20132017.\" ''French Politics'' (2018): 1\u201327.\n*Gougou, Florent, and Simon Persico. \"A new party system in the making? The 2017 French presidential election.\" ''French Politics'' 15.3 (2017): 303\u2013321.\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikinews|Emmanuel Macron wins French presidential election race}}\n{{Commons category|French presidential election (2017)}}\n*[http://presidentielle2017.conseil-constitutionnel.fr/ Constitutional Council] {{in lang|fr}}\n*[http://elections.interieur.gouv.fr/presidentielle-2017/ Ministry of the Interior] {{in lang|fr}}\n*[https://presidentielle2017.conseil-constitutionnel.fr/les-parrainages/tous-les-parrainages/ List of all sponsorships by elected officials] {{in lang|fr}}\n*[https://presidentielle2017.conseil-constitutionnel.fr/les-parrainages/donnees-et-graphiques/ Data and graphics for sponsorships] {{in lang|fr}}\n*[https://www.data.gouv.fr/s/resources/election-presidentielle-des-23-avril-et-7-mai-2017-resultats-definitifs-du-1er-tour-1/20170427-100131/Presidentielle_2017_Resultats_Tour_1_c.xls Results of the first round of the presidential election by constituency] {{in lang|fr}}\n\n{{French elections}}\n{{Candidates in the French presidential election, 2017}}\n\n[[Category:2017 French presidential election| ]]\n[[Category:2017 elections in France]]\n[[Category:April 2017 events in France]]\n[[Category:May 2017 events in France]]\n[[Category:Presidential elections in France|2017]]\n[[Category:2017 establishments in France]]\n", "name_user": "99.23.37.10", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2017_French_presidential_election"}
{"title_page": "Keith Maillard", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian writer}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n[[File:Keith Maillard, Salt Spring Island, BC, 2015.jpg|thumb|Keith Maillard, Salt Spring Island, 2015]]\n'''Keith Maillard''' (born 28 February 1942 in [[Wheeling, West Virginia|Wheeling]], [[West Virginia]]) is a Canadian-American novelist, poet, and professor of creative writing at the [[University of British Columbia]].<ref>[https://creativewriting.ubc.ca/program-information/people/keith-maillard/ Keith Maillard, UBC Creative Writing]</ref> He moved to Canada in 1970 (due to his opposition to the Vietnam War)<ref>Marilyn B. Young and Robert Buzzanco, eds., ''A Companion to the Vietnam War'' (John Wiley & Sons, 2002), 431.</ref><ref>Robert McGill, ''War is Here: The Vietnam War and Canadian Literature'' (McGill Queens, 2017), 198, 277.</ref> and became a Canadian citizen in 1976.<ref name=Maillardfame>[http://www.ohiocountylibrary.org/wheeling-history/wheeling-hall-of-fame-keith-lee-maillard--/4194 Ohio County Public Library, \"Wheeling Hall of Fame: Keith Maillard,\"]</ref><ref name=New>William H. New, \"Keith Maillard,\" ''Encyclopedia of Literature in Canada'' (University of Toronto Press, 2002), 700.</ref>\n\n== Family background ==\n\nMaillard has French, Canadian, and American roots. His [[Huguenots]] great grandparents immigrated to Montreal from Lyon, France, in the early 1880s. His Maillard grandfather and two Montreal-born uncles continued the family tradition of glass-blowing, working for Dominion Glass in Montreal and in [[Redcliff, Alberta]].<ref>Keith Maillard, ''Fatherless: A Memoir'' (West Virginia University Press, 2019).</ref>\n\nMaillard's parents divorced when he was a baby and he never knew his father.<ref name=New /><ref>[http://www.southerncultures.org/article/hot-springs-arkansas/ Keith Maillard, \"Hot Springs, Arkansas,\" ''Southern Cultures'', Volume 17, Number 3, Fall 2011.]</ref> His father, Eugene C. Maillard, avoided glassblowing work, trained as a draughtsman, and worked for twenty-five years at the [[Hanford Site]] nuclear plant in Richland, Washington.<ref>[http://numerocinqmagazine.com/2011/03/29/from-fatherless-nonfiction-by-keith-maillard/ Keith Maillard, \"Richland,\" ''Numero Cinq Magazine'', Vol.II No.3, March 2011.]</ref> Maillard's mother's family settled in the [[Ohio River]] Valley in the late 18th century and it is from her family stories that Maillard draws inspiration for much of his [[historical fiction]]. He describes the process of his earliest childhood fiction in his 2011 essay, \"Kilroy: A Writer's Childhood.\"<ref>[http://numerocinqmagazine.com/2011/05/13/kilroy-a-writers-childhood-by-keith-maillard/ Keith Maillard, \"Kilroy: A Writer's Childhood,\" ''Numero Cinq Magazine'', Vol. II No. 5, May 2011.]</ref>\n\nKeith Maillard and his wife Mary<ref>https://keithmaillard.com/an-expanded-more-personal-statement-about-keiths-life/</ref> have two daughters<ref name=Gale>[http://go.galegroup.com/ps/i.do?p=LitRC&u=ubcolumbia&id=GALE%7CH1000063179&v=2.1&it=r&sid=LitRC&asid=de1c0d0d \"Keith Maillard,\" Contemporary Authors Online, Detroit: Gale, 2012]</ref> and lives in West Vancouver. His mother-in-law is Canadian novelist [[Rohan O'Grady]].<ref>[http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/vancouversun/obituary.aspx?pid=170294990 \"June Margaret nee O'Grady Skinner,\" ''The Vancouver Sun,'' 22 March 2014]</ref>\n\n== 1960s ==\n\nMaillard left his native West Virginia in 1965 and moved to Boston where he lived for five years. He worked in the anti-Vietnam-war movement from 1968-1970 and contributed numerous articles to Boston underground newspapers and radio.<ref name=Maillardfonds>[https://www.library.ubc.ca/archives/u_arch/maillard.pdf Keith Maillard fonds, University of British Columbia]</ref> In 1970, disillusioned after the [[Kent State shootings]], he emigrated to Canada.<ref>Keith Maillard, ''Dementia Americana'' (Ronsdale Press, 1994), 12.</ref> He was not eligible for the draft and was a war resister rather than a draft dodger.\n\n== 1970s ==\n\nIn the early 1970s, Maillard worked as a freelancer for [[CBC radio]], contributing pieces to ''This Country in the Morning'', ''Five Nights'', and ''Our Native Land.''<ref name=Maillardfonds>[https://www.library.ubc.ca/archives/u_arch/maillard.pdf Keith Maillard fonds, University of British Columbia]</ref><ref name=Gale />  He also contributed to periodicals, including ''Fusion'', ''Body Politic'', ''Malahat Review'', ''Books in Canada'', ''Canadian Literature'', and newspapers.<ref name=Gale />  He was in the [[Writers' Union of Canada]], served on the National Council for two years,<ref>Anne Innis Dagg, ''Smitten by a Giraffe: My Life as a Citizen Scientist'' (McGill-Queens, 2016), 131.</ref> and co-founded the [[Federation of BC Writers]].<ref>[https://bcbooklook.com/2007/12/12/25-years-of-the-federation-of-bc-writers-by-carolan-trevor/ Trevor Carolan, \"25 Years of the Federation of BC Writers,\" ''BC Booklook'', 12 December 2007]</ref><ref>[https://www.bcwriters.ca/history-of-the-fbcw/ Ben Nuttall-Smith, \"The History of the Federation of BC Writers Extended,\" 7 July 2016]</ref> Maillard studied music at [[Vancouver Community College]], played the Irish pipes, taught recorder and the rudiments of music for the [[Vancouver School Board]] and Vancouver Community College,<ref name=New /><ref name=Gale /> and played bass in the first band formed by Vancouver singer-songwriter, [[Ferron]]. In the late 1970s Maillard taught writing workshops in Vancouver's literary centre, The Literary Storefront, and participated in a number of readings and other events there.<ref>Trevor Carolan, ''The Literary Storefront: The Glory Years 1978\u20131985'' (Mother Tongue Publishing, 2015), 61, 101, 117, 121, 122, 126, 135-36, 227. {{ISBN|978-1-896949-52-9}}.</ref><ref>Nicholas Bradley, review of ''The Literary Storefront: The Glory Years 1878\u20131985'', ''BC Studies'', No. 191, Autumn 2016.</ref> In 1979 Maillard interviewed Canadian novelist Howard O\u2019Hagan who explained to him his writing process; the interview appeared as a chapter in [[Margery Fee]]'s ''Silence Made Visible: Howard O\u2019Hagan and Tay John'' (1992).<ref>Margery Fee, ed. ''Silence Made Visible: Howard O\u2019Hagan and Tay John'' (ECW Press, 1992), 21-38.</ref>\n\nMaillard's first published novel, ''Two Strand River,'' appeared in 1976, published by [[Dave Godfrey]]'s Press Porc\u00e9pic. Most reviewers were confounded by this strange book with its cross-gendered protagonists and weird events, but ''Two Strand River'' soon acquired a cult following, came to be labeled a classic of Canadian [[magic realism]],<ref name=Hancock>Geoff Hancock, \"Keith Maillard,\" ''The Oxford Companion to Canadian Literature,'' eds., William Toy and Eugene Benson (Oxford University Press, 1997, online 2006), 717-718.</ref><ref>Peter Hinchcliffe and Ed Jewinski, ''Magic Realism and Canadian Literature'' (Wilfrid Laurier University, 1985), 82.</ref><ref>Stephen Slemon, \"Magic Realism as Post Colonial Discourse,\" chapter in Lois Parkinson Zamora and Wendy B. Faris, eds., ''Magic Realism: Theory, History, Community'' (Duke University Press, 1995), 409.</ref> and has been republished twice.\n\n== 1980s ==\n\nMaillard's second published novel was actually the first one he had begun; the book rejected by 26 publishers finally&nbsp;\u2013 after having passed through eight major rewrites&nbsp;\u2013 appeared in 1980 as ''Alex Driving South''.<ref>Clark Blaise, \"Relearning Freedom,\" review of ''Alex Driving South'', ''Canadian Literature'' 89 (Summer 1981): 131-133.</ref><ref>[https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/keith-maillard-2/alex-driving-south/ Kirkus Reviews ''Alex Driving South'']</ref> In this gritty, naturalistic tale, Maillard first introduced the fictional town of Raysburg, West Virginia, where most of his novels have been set. ''The Knife in My Hands,'' influenced by American writer [[Jack Kerouac]],<ref name=New /><ref name=Hancock /> followed in 1981, and its sequel, ''Cutting Through,'' in 1982. Then, with a fifth book half-completed, Maillard was afflicted with writer's block.\n\nFrom 1985 through 1988 Maillard applied his writing skills to designing university and adult education courses for the [[Open Learning Agency]] and, from 1986\u20131989, he workshopped his screenplay, ''Two Strand River'', with [[Patricia Gruben]]'s Praxis Film Development Workshop (Simon Fraser University).<ref name=Gale /><ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/british-columbia/celebrated-bc-screenwriting-program-praxis-to-fold/article15508306/ Marsha Lederman, \"Celebrated B.C. screenwriting program Praxis to fold,\" ''The Globe and Mail'', 19 November 2013.]</ref>\n\nMaillard's fifth novel, ''Motet,'' published in 1989, won the [[Ethel Wilson Fiction Prize]].<ref>[http://www.canadianauthors.net/awards/bc_book_prizes/ethel_wilson_fiction_prize/ Ethel Wilson Fiction Prize]</ref> Reviewer David Homel assured readers that despite the novel's sixteenth-century Dutch choral mystery and Vancouver setting, \"power and madness made in the USA is still at the heart of Maillard's creativity.\"<ref>[http://www.booksincanada.com/article_view.asp?id=2291 David Homel, \"Harmonics,\" ''Books in Canada'', 1989]</ref>\n\nHaving taught as a sessional lecturer at both the [[University of British Columbia]] (UBC) and [[Simon Fraser University]], Maillard was appointed in 1989 to a regular teaching position in UBC's Creative Writing Department, where he has taught every genre except stage writing.<ref name=New>William H. New, \"Keith Maillard,\" ''Encyclopedia of Literature in Canada'' (University of Toronto Press, 2002), 700.</ref> He served as Advisory Editor of ''[[PRISM international]]'' for 10 years.\n\n== 1990s ==\n\nWhile at UBC, Maillard began what he considers his mature work \u2013 what has come to be known as the \"Raysburg Series.\"<ref name=Hancock /><ref>Meredith Sue Willis, \"Keith Maillard: Five Novels of Raysburg,  West Virginia,\" ''Appalachian Journal'', Vol. 31, No. 3/4 (2004): 358-366.</ref><ref>[http://www.wvencyclopedia.org/articles/1417 Gordon Simmons, \"Literature,\" e-WV: The West Virginia Encyclopedia, 4 February 2014. Web. 1 May 2018]</ref><ref>Gordon K. Neufeld, \"Laugh, cry, and laugh again,\" ''Books in Canada'', Vol. 31, Issue 9, December 2002.</ref><ref name=New /> Called \"a small masterpiece\" by the ''Georgia Straight'', ''Light in the Company of Women'' was published in 1993<ref>Lorraine York, \"Photographic Mixtures,\" ''Canadian Literature'' 141 (Summer 1994): 115-116.</ref> and was runner-up for the [[Ethel Wilson Fiction Prize]].<ref>[http://www.canadianauthors.net/awards/bc_book_prizes/ethel_wilson_fiction_prize/ Ethel Wilson Fiction Prize]</ref> It was followed in 1995 by ''Hazard Zones'', which was included on the ''[[Toronto Star]]'''s list of the best Canadian books for that year and was short-listed for the [[Commonwealth Writers' Prize]].<ref>[https://www.librarything.com/bookaward/Commonwealth+Writers%27+Prize+Shortlist Commonwealth Writers' Prize Shortlist]</ref>  \n\nMaillard's novel, ''Gloria'' (1999), was well received in Canada,<ref>T. F. Rigelhof, ''Hooked on Canadian Books: The Good, the Better, and the Best Canadian Novels Since 1984'' (Cormorant Books, 2010), 258.</ref> short-listed for the [[Governor General's Literary Award]] for Fiction,<ref>Anne-Marie Tobin, \"Matt Cohen, Keith Maillard among GG literary finalists,\" ''Canadian Press Newswire'', 9 October 1999.</ref> and brought him national attention in the United States.<ref>[https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/books/00/10/08/bib/001008.rv104213.html Jesse Browner, \"Little Gloria Free at Last,\" ''The New York Times,'' 8 October 2000]</ref> <ref>[https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/keith-maillard/gloria-2/ GLORIA by Keith Maillard, starred review, ''Kirkus Reviews'', 1 July, 2000] </ref>\n\nMaillard also returned to his first love, poetry, and published ''Dementia Americana'', which won the [[Gerald Lampert Award]] for the best first book of poetry published in Canada.<ref>[http://poets.ca/lampert Gerald Lampert Memorial Award]</ref> He became interested in the re-emergence of formal poetry in North America and commented about it in his oft-cited essay, \"The New Formalism and the Return of Prosody.\"<ref>Paul Scott Derrick, ''Lines of Thought: 1983\u20132015'' (Universitat de Valencia, 2015), 143.</ref><ref>Gerry Cambridge, \"The New Formalism,\" Jay Parini, ed., ''The Oxford Encyclopedia of American Literature'' (Oxford University Press, 2004), 251, 253-54.</ref><ref>[http://www.persee.fr/doc/rfea_0397-7870_2000_num_84_1_1804 Thomas Cable, \"Connoisseurs of sound and the new formalism,\" ''Revue Francaise d'Etudes Americaines,'' No. 84 (March 2000):52-52]</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060224095203/http://www.antigonishreview.com/bi-109/109-maillard.html Keith Maillard, review of ''Rebel Angels'', ''The Antigonish Review'', 109 (1999).]</ref><ref>Keith Maillard, \"The New Formalism and the Return of Prosody,\" in R.S. Gwynn, ''New Expansive Poetry'' (1999): 52-71.</ref><ref>Catherine Addison, ''A Genealogy of the Verse Novel'' (Cambridge Scholars Publishing, 2017), 424.</ref><ref>Gregory Dowling, \"New Formalism: Dangerous Nostalgia or Angellic Rebellion?\" ''Letteratura e letterature,'' 3 (2009): 1-20.</ref>\n\n== 2000s ==\n\nThe last of the \"Raysburg Series\", ''The Clarinet Polka'' (2002), was well received in the United States, particularly by the Polish American community.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2003/05/04/books/books-in-brief-fiction-poetry-402320.html Etelka Lehoczky, \"Books in Brief: Fiction and Poetry,\" ''The New York Times,'' 4 May 2003]</ref><ref>{{cite news | first=Zofia | last=Smardz | title=Banding Together | newspaper=The Washington Post | date=4 May 2003 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/entertainment/books/2003/05/04/banding-together/130f3dba-4a65-48b5-9f71-e72b1ba1c552/ | accessdate=1 May 2018 }}</ref><ref>David James Jackson, \" 'Another Polka Rockin' Weekend': Polish American Polka Music, Identity, and Traditional Values,\" ''Polish American Studies'', Vol. 71, No. 1 (Spring 2014), 47.</ref><ref>William Hal Gorby, \"Saints,  Sinners, and Socialists on the Southside: Polish Catholic Immigrant Workers, Politics, and Culture in Wheeling, West Virginia, 1890-1930,\" PhD thesis, University of West Virginia (2014), 2, 120, 123, 124, 128, 129, 351, 355-56.</ref><ref>T. J. Napierkowski, \"''The Clarinet Polka'': Life, Literature, Music,\" ''Polish American Studies'', Vol. 61, No. 2 (Autumn 2004): 9-24.</ref> It received starred reviews from ''Library Journal'', ''Publishers Weekly'', ''Booklist'', and ''Kirkus Reviews'',<ref>Inside jacket copy, Keith Maillard, ''Looking Good'' (2006), n.p. </ref> and was included in  ''Booklist''\u2019s Editors\u2019 Choice \u201903. It won the Polish American Historical Association's Creative Arts Prize, and came to the attention of scholars in Poland.<ref>[https://www.booklistonline.com/Booklist-Editors-Choice/pid=2855242 Booklist's Editors' Choice: Adult Books, 2003]</ref><ref>[http://polishamericanstudies.org/text/26/creative-arts.html Polish American Historical Association Creative Arts Prize]</ref><ref>A. Branach-Kallas, \"Folkloristic Hybrids: Diaspora Space in ''The Clarinet Polka'' by Keith Maillard,\"  ''Przegl\u0105d Polonijny,'' Vol. 31, Issue 2 (2005):105-112.</ref>\n\nMaillard was one of 35 writers placed on the West Virginia Literary Map in 2004 and he was inducted that year into the Wheeling, West Virginia, Hall of Fame.<ref name=Maillardfame />\n\nIn 2004, Maillard returned to the raw [[Bildungsroman]]<ref>William H. New, ''A History of Canadian Literature'' (McGill-Queens, 2003), 229, 237.</ref> material first published in ''The Knife in My Hands'' and ''Cutting Through'' and rewrote and reshaped it into the ''Difficulty at the Beginning'' quartet, which appeared in four volumes between September 2005 and September 2006.<ref>Gordon Simmons, Review of ''Difficulty at the Beginning'', ''Appalachian Heritage'', Vol. 35, No. 4 (Fall 2007): 103-105.</ref> The [[Toronto]] ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' selected ''Difficulty at the Beginning'' as one of the top books of 2006, calling it \"a work of terrible beauty and grace, a masterpiece fit to contend with the best novels of the last century.\"<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/the-unbearable-lightness-of-being-american/article729950/ Tom Sandborn, \"The unbearable lightness of being American,\"''The Globe and Mail'', 10 June 2006]</ref><ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/the-60s-on-the-instalment-plan/article714388/ Tom Sandborn, \"The '60s on the installment plan,\" ''The Globe and Mail'', 21 October 2006.]</ref> Reviewer Richard Helm describes the quartet as Maillard's \"magnum opus and the keystone of a literary career that has flown largely under the Canadian radar.\" He characterizes Maillard as \"probably the most famous Canadian novelist you've never heard of.\"<ref>[https://www.pressreader.com/canada/calgary-herald/20060921/282879431237496 Richard Helm, \"Maillard Canada's best unknown writer,\" ''Calgary Herald,'' 21 September 2006].</ref>\n\nIn 2006, with eleven out of fourteen titles nominated for or winners of literary awards, Maillard won UBC's Dorothy Somerset Award for excellence in the creative arts.<ref>[https://news.ubc.ca/2007/03/01/archive-ubcreports-2007-07mar01-07mar01kudos/ \"Kudos,\" ''UBC Reports'', Vol. 53, No.3, 1 March, 2007]</ref>\n\n== 2010s ==\n\nIn its 80th anniversary edition in 2015, the ''[[Quill & Quire]]'' listed Maillard as one of Canada's \"notable Canlit talent\" along with other American-born anti-Vietnam-War authors, Philip Marchand, Jack Todd, [[Judith Merrill]], [[Mark Frutkin]], and [[William Gibson]].<ref>[https://quillandquire.com/book-culture/2015/04/15/80-years-of-qq-canlit-personalities-3/3/ \"80 years of Q&Q: getting personal with Canlit personalities,\" ''Quill & Quire'', 15 April 2015]</ref>\n\nIn his most recent novel ''Twin Studies'' (2018) -- set in Vancouver, Medicine Hat, and Los Angeles -- Maillard returns to the topic of gender fluidity that he first explored in ''Two Strand River'' in 1976.<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/books/article-the-globe-100-our-favourite-books-of-2018/\"The Globe 100: Our favourite books of 2018,\" ''The Globe and Mail'', 30 November 2018.]</ref><ref>[https://bcbooklook.com/2019/01/22/471-gender-manga-and-teen-idiom/ Theo Dombrowski, \"Gender, manga, and teen idiom,\" ''BC BookLook'', 22 January 2019.]</ref> Apple's iBooks reviewed the novel and  described it as \" a fascinating exploration of wealth, class, and gender fluidity [that] reads like a 21st-century Canadian version of Dickens' London novels.\"<ref>[https://books.apple.com/ca/book/twin-studies/id1370910770 Apple Books review of Keith Maillard's Twin Studies, 2018.]</ref> Steven Beattie, in the September 2018 issue of ''Quill & Quire'', notes that Maillard's subject matter arises out of lived experience. \"When the author began publishing, the language for describing gender-fluid approaches did not exist.\" As Maillard himself put it in his interview with Beattie, \"You can't apply a term to yourself unless it is culturally available. I would now call myself non-binary.\" <ref>[https://quillandquire.com/authors/keith-maillard-prizes-a-multiplicity-of-approaches-to-literary-craft-as-a-writer-and-teacher/ Steven W. Beattie, \"Doubling down: As a writer and teacher, Keith Maillard prizes a multiplicity of approaches to literary craft,\" ''Quill & Quire'', September 2018, 6-7.]</ref>  \n\nThe  ''Vancouver Sun'' summarized ''Twin Studies'' as \"that rare work: a story that grapples with difficult intellectual issues without ever abandoning the novelist's primary duty -- compelling narrative.\"<ref> [https://vancouversun.com/entertainment/books/book-review-keith-malliards-twin-studies-displays-a-lyrical-beauty/ Tom Sandborn, \"Keith Maillard's ''Twin Studies'' displays a lyrical beauty,\" ''Vancouver Sun'', 5 October 2018.]</ref> Maillard\u2019s novel challenges the idea of isolated nuclear families and envisions what he says is \u201c a fluid larger family, in which people come together for other reasons. I think it's essential that we start rethinking family, that we start rethinking our connections to each other.\u201d<ref> [https://www.cbc.ca/radio/thenextchapter/why-keith-maillard-s-novel-twin-studies-dissects-the-nature-of-love-and-family-1.5056760 \"Why Keith Maillard's novel ''Twin Studies'' dissects the nature of love and family,\" CBC Radio, 16 March 2019.]</ref> \n\n''Twin Studies'' won the Alberta Book of the Year Award from the Book Publishers Association of Alberta.<ref>[https://freehand-books.com/three-freehand-books-win-at-alberta-book-publishing-awards/ \"Three Freehand books win at Alberta Book Publishing Awards,\" Freehand Books, September 2019]</ref> In an interview with Quentin Mills-Fenn of ''Prairie books Now'', Maillard explained that his book explores \u201dthe impact of traumatic experiences,\u201d and that he firmly believes that \u201c[p]hysicians and therapists who work with children and adolescents are telling us that a gender-affirming point of view from parents and, if possible, from the surrounding culture, makes for healthy and happy kids.\"<ref>[https://prairiebooksnow.ca/articles/view/a-complex-pairing-delves-into-genetics-and-identity Quentin Miles-Fenn, \"A complex pairing delves into genetics and identity,\" ''Prairie books NOW'', Fall/Winter 2018/2019.]</ref>\n\nMaillard's first non-fiction book, ''Fatherless: A Memoir'' (2019), traces the life of the mysterious father he never knew, and was well received in Canada. <ref>[https://vancouversun.com/entertainment/books/book-review-b-c-novelist-keith-maillard-writes-about-his-search-for-the-father-who-abandoned-him Tom Sandborn, \"B.C. novelist Keith Maillard writes about his search for the father who abandoned him,\" ''Vancouver Sun'', 8 November 2019.] </ref> <ref>[https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/books/2019/11/21/keith-maillard-talks-about-his-absentee-fathers-one-last-gut-punch-from-beyond-the-grave.html Sue Carter, \"Keith Maillard talks about his absentee father's 'one last gut punch from the grave,' \" ''Toronto Star'', 21 November 2019.] </ref> <ref>[https://quillandquire.com/review/fatherless-a-memoir/ Robert J. Wiersema, Book Review, ''Fatherless: A Memoir'', ''Quill & Quire'', December 2019, 21.]</ref> CBC Arts columnist and creative nonfiction author/editor [[Alicia Elliott]] writes that Maillard's memoir \"gives us a model of not only self awareness and honesty but also, more importantly, healing.\"<ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/arts/new-year-new-me-how-memoirs-can-help-us-shape-our-futures-by-examining-other-people-s-pasts-1.5435211 Alicia Elliott, \"New year, new me? How memoirs can help us shape our futures by examining other people's pasts,\" ''CBC Arts'', 22 January 2020.]</ref>\n\n== 2020s ==\n\nMaillard's papers are currently held by the University of British Columbia's Rare Books and Special Collections.<ref name=Maillardfonds /> A complete list of Maillard's publications can be found on his website.<ref>[https://keithmaillard.com/writing/publications-list Keith Maillard Publications List]</ref>\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\n* 1986: winner Praxis Competition, ''Two Strand River''\n* 1990: winner [[Ethel Wilson Fiction Prize]], ''Motet''\n* 1994: runner-up [[Ethel Wilson Fiction Prize]], ''Light in the Company of Women''\n* 1995: winner [[Gerald Lampert Award]], ''Dementia Americana''\n* 1996: shortlisted [[Commonwealth Writers' Prize]], ''Hazard Zones''\n* [[1999 Governor General's Awards|1999: fiction finalist, Governor General's Awards]], ''Gloria''\n* 2004: winner West Virginia Literary Merit Award\n* 2005: winner [[Polish American Historical Association]] Creative Arts Prize, ''The Clarinet Polka''\n* 2005: shortlisted Weatherford Award, ''Running''\n* 2006: longlisted [[ReLit Awards]], ''Looking Good''\n* 2006: shortlisted Weatherford Award ''Morgantown''\n* 2006: shortlisted Weatherford Award, ''Lyndon Johnston and the Majorettes''\n* 2006: winner Dorothy Somerset Award for Excellence in the Creative Arts\n* 2018: The ''Globe'' 100, ''Twin Studies''\n* 2019: winner Alberta Book of the Year Award: Trade Fiction, ''Twin Studies''\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* 1976: ''Two Strand River'' (Press Porcepic) {{ISBN|0-88878-088-5}}\n** 1982 reissue: ''Two Strand River'' (General Publishing) {{ISBN|0-7736-7031-9}}\n** 1996 reissue: ''Two Strand River'' (HarperCollins) {{ISBN|0-00-648143-4}}\n** 2013 reissue: ''Two Strand River'' (Keith Maillard) ebook {{ASIN|BOOCOKVS4A}} \n* 1980: ''Alex Driving South'' (Dial Press) {{ISBN|0-8037-0196-9}}\n** 1983 reissue: ''Alex Driving South'' (General Publishing) {{ISBN|0-7736-7045-9}}\n** 2013 reissue: ''Alex Driving South'' (Keith Maillard) ebook {{ASIN|BOOB7ABDL2}}\n* 1981: ''The Knife in my Hands'' (General) {{ISBN|0-7737-0057-9}}\n** 1982 reissue: ''The Knife in my Hands'' (Beaufort) {{ISBN|978-0-825-30082-0}}\n* 1982: ''Cutting Through'' (Stoddart) {{ISBN|0-7737-2003-0}}\n** 1983 reissue: Cutting Through (Beaufort) {{ISBN|0-8253-0120-3}}\n* 1989: ''Motet'' (Random House) {{ISBN|0-394-22028-5}}\n** 1997 reissue: ''Motet'' (HarperCollins) {{ISBN|0-00-648163-9}}\n** 1998 reissue: ''Motet'' (Harvill Press) {{ISBN|978-0-00-648163-8}}\n** 2013 reissue: ''Motet'' (Keith Maillard) ebook {{ASIN|BOOAYB4N5S}}\n* 1993: ''Light in the Company of Women'' (HarperCollins) {{ISBN|0-00-223894-2}}\n* 1994: ''Dementia Americana'', poems (Ronsdale/Cacanadadada) {{ISBN|0-921870-28-0}}\n* 1995: ''Hazard Zones'' (Harper Perennial) {{ISBN|0-00-224397-0}}\n* 1999: ''Gloria'' (Harper Flamingo) {{ISBN|0-00-648175-2}}\n** 2000: reissue: ''Gloria'' (Soho Press) {{ISBN|978-1-56947-206-4}}\n** 2001: reissue: ''Gloria'' (HarperFlamingo) {{ISBN|978-0-00-648175-1}}\n* 2002: ''The Clarinet Polka'' (Thomas Allen) {{ISBN|0-88762-100-7}}\n** 2003: reissue: ''The Clarinet Polka'' (St.Martin's Press) {{ISBN|0-312-30889-2}}\n** 2004: reissue: ''The Clarinet Polka'' (St.Martin's Griffin) {{ISBN|978-0-312-30890-2}}\n* 2005: ''Running'' (Brindle & Glass) {{ISBN|1-897142-06-4}}\n** 2011: ''Running'' (Brindle & Glass) ebook {{ASIN|BOOSVSX3LG}}\n* 2006: ''Morgantown'' (Brindle & Glass) {{ISBN|1-897142-07-2}}\n** 2011: ''Morgantown'' (Brindle & Glass) ebook {{ASIN|BOOSVXS1J0}}\n* 2006: ''Lyndon Johnson and the Majorettes'' (Brindle & Glass) {{ISBN|1-897142-08-0}}\n** 2011: ''Lyndon Johnson and the Majorettes'' (Brindle & Glass) ebook  {{ASIN|BOOSVXS3DY}}\n* 2006: ''Looking Good'' (Brindle & Glass) {{ISBN|1-897142-09-9}}\n** 2011: ''Looking Good'' (Brindle & Glass) ebook {{ASIN|BOOSVXS1K4}}\n* 2018: ''Twin Studies'' (Freehand Press) {{ISBN|1-988298-31-8}}\n** 2018: ''Twin Studies'' (Audible) audiobook {{ASIN|BO7JPJKDFY}}\n* 2019: ''Fatherless'' (University of West Virginia Press) {{ISBN|978-1-949199-13-0}}\n\n== Anthologized ==\n\n* 1985: ''Vancouver Fiction''. David Watmough, ed., Winlaw, B.C., (Polestar Press) {{ISBN|978-0-919591-05-9}}\n* 1986: ''Magic Realism and Canadian Literature: Essays and Stories, Proceedings of the Conference on Magic Realist Writing in Canada''. University of Waterloo/Wilfrid Laurier University, May 1985; Peter and Ed Jewinski, eds. (University of Waterloo Press) {{ISBN|978-0-88898-065-6}}\n* 1999: ''New Expansive Poetry''. R.S. Gwynn, ed., Ashland, Oregon, (Story Line Press) {{ISBN|978-1-885266-69-9}}\n* 2005: ''Wild Sweet Notes II: More Great Poetry From West Virginia''. (Publishers Place) {{ISBN|978-0-9744785-2-4}}\n* 2008: ''The Best of Canadian Poetry in English, 2008''. Stephanie Bolster and Molly Peacock, eds., (Tightrope Books) {{ISBN|978-0-9783351-7-5}}\n* 2008: ''Crossing Lines: Poets Who Came to Canada in the Vietnam War''. Allan Briesmaster and Steven Michael Berzensky, eds., (Seraphim Editions) {{ISBN|978-0-9808879-1-4}}\n* 2014: ''Naked in Academe: Celebrating Fifty Years of Creative Writing at UBC.'' Rhea Tregebov, ed., (McClelland & Stewart) {{ISBN|978-0-7710-8926-8}}\n* 2018: ''Refuse: Canlit in Ruins''. Hannah McGregor, Julie Rak & Erin Wunker, eds., (Book*hug) {{ISBN|978-1-7716643-1-8}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://keithmaillard.com/ Official website]\n* [https://abcbookworld.com/scripter/scripter-7050/ BC Bookworld profile]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110927162419/http://www.wvwc.edu/library/wv_authors/authors/a_maillard.htm West Virginia Wesleyan College / Annie Merner Pfeiffer Library: Keith Maillard profile]\n* [http://go.galegroup.com/ps/i.do?p=LitRC&u=ubcolumbia&id=GALE%7CH1000063179&v=2.1&it=r&sid=LitRC&asid=de1c0d0d \"Keith Maillard,\" Contemporary Authors Online: Keith Maillard profile]\n* [http://www.ohiocountylibrary.org/wheeling-history/wheeling-hall-of-fame-keith-lee-maillard--/4194 Ohio County Public Library, \"Wheeling Hall of Fame: Keith Maillard\"]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maillard, Keith}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian male novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian novelists]]\n[[Category:Canadian male poets]]\n[[Category:Writers from Wheeling, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Writers from British Columbia]]\n[[Category:University of British Columbia faculty]]\n[[Category:West Virginia University]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian writer}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n[[File:Keith Maillard, Salt Spring Island, BC, 2015.jpg|thumb|Keith Maillard, Salt Spring Island, 2015]]\n'''Keith Maillard''' (born 28 February 1942 in [[Wheeling, West Virginia|Wheeling]], [[West Virginia]]) is a Canadian-American novelist, poet, and professor of creative writing at the [[University of British Columbia]].<ref>[https://creativewriting.ubc.ca/program-information/people/keith-maillard/ Keith Maillard, UBC Creative Writing]</ref> He moved to Canada in 1970 (due to his opposition to the Vietnam War)<ref>Marilyn B. Young and Robert Buzzanco, eds., ''A Companion to the Vietnam War'' (John Wiley & Sons, 2002), 431.</ref><ref>Robert McGill, ''War is Here: The Vietnam War and Canadian Literature'' (McGill Queens, 2017), 198, 277.</ref> and became a Canadian citizen in 1976.<ref name=Maillardfame>[http://www.ohiocountylibrary.org/wheeling-history/wheeling-hall-of-fame-keith-lee-maillard--/4194 Ohio County Public Library, \"Wheeling Hall of Fame: Keith Maillard,\"]</ref><ref name=New>William H. New, \"Keith Maillard,\" ''Encyclopedia of Literature in Canada'' (University of Toronto Press, 2002), 700.</ref>\n\n== Family background ==\n\nMaillard has French, Canadian, and American roots. His [[Huguenots]] great grandparents immigrated to Montreal from Lyon, France, in the early 1880s. His Maillard grandfather and two Montreal-born uncles continued the family tradition of glass-blowing, working for Dominion Glass in Montreal and in [[Redcliff, Alberta]].<ref>Keith Maillard, ''Fatherless: A Memoir'' (West Virginia University Press, 2019).</ref>\n\nMaillard's parents divorced when he was a baby and he never knew his father.<ref name=New /><ref>[http://www.southerncultures.org/article/hot-springs-arkansas/ Keith Maillard, \"Hot Springs, Arkansas,\" ''Southern Cultures'', Volume 17, Number 3, Fall 2011.]</ref> His father, Eugene C. Maillard, avoided glassblowing work, trained as a draughtsman, and worked for twenty-five years at the [[Hanford Site]] nuclear plant in Richland, Washington.<ref>[http://numerocinqmagazine.com/2011/03/29/from-fatherless-nonfiction-by-keith-maillard/ Keith Maillard, \"Richland,\" ''Numero Cinq Magazine'', Vol.II No.3, March 2011.]</ref> Maillard's mother's family settled in the [[Ohio River]] Valley in the late 18th century and it is from her family stories that Maillard draws inspiration for much of his [[historical fiction]]. He describes the process of his earliest childhood fiction in his 2011 essay, \"Kilroy: A Writer's Childhood.\"<ref>[http://numerocinqmagazine.com/2011/05/13/kilroy-a-writers-childhood-by-keith-maillard/ Keith Maillard, \"Kilroy: A Writer's Childhood,\" ''Numero Cinq Magazine'', Vol. II No. 5, May 2011.]</ref>\n\nKeith Maillard is married with two daughters<ref name=Gale>[http://go.galegroup.com/ps/i.do?p=LitRC&u=ubcolumbia&id=GALE%7CH1000063179&v=2.1&it=r&sid=LitRC&asid=de1c0d0d \"Keith Maillard,\" Contemporary Authors Online, Detroit: Gale, 2012]</ref> and lives in West Vancouver. His mother-in-law is Canadian novelist [[Rohan O'Grady]].<ref>[http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/vancouversun/obituary.aspx?pid=170294990 \"June Margaret nee O'Grady Skinner,\" ''The Vancouver Sun,'' 22 March 2014]</ref>\n\n== 1960s ==\n\nMaillard left his native West Virginia in 1965 and moved to Boston where he lived for five years. He worked in the anti-Vietnam-war movement from 1968-1970 and contributed numerous articles to Boston underground newspapers and radio.<ref name=Maillardfonds>[https://www.library.ubc.ca/archives/u_arch/maillard.pdf Keith Maillard fonds, University of British Columbia]</ref> In 1970, disillusioned after the [[Kent State shootings]], he emigrated to Canada.<ref>Keith Maillard, ''Dementia Americana'' (Ronsdale Press, 1994), 12.</ref> He was not eligible for the draft and was a war resister rather than a draft dodger.\n\n== 1970s ==\n\nIn the early 1970s, Maillard worked as a freelancer for [[CBC radio]], contributing pieces to ''This Country in the Morning'', ''Five Nights'', and ''Our Native Land.''<ref name=Maillardfonds>[https://www.library.ubc.ca/archives/u_arch/maillard.pdf Keith Maillard fonds, University of British Columbia]</ref><ref name=Gale />  He also contributed to periodicals, including ''Fusion'', ''Body Politic'', ''Malahat Review'', ''Books in Canada'', ''Canadian Literature'', and newspapers.<ref name=Gale />  He was in the [[Writers' Union of Canada]], served on the National Council for two years,<ref>Anne Innis Dagg, ''Smitten by a Giraffe: My Life as a Citizen Scientist'' (McGill-Queens, 2016), 131.</ref> and co-founded the [[Federation of BC Writers]].<ref>[https://bcbooklook.com/2007/12/12/25-years-of-the-federation-of-bc-writers-by-carolan-trevor/ Trevor Carolan, \"25 Years of the Federation of BC Writers,\" ''BC Booklook'', 12 December 2007]</ref><ref>[https://www.bcwriters.ca/history-of-the-fbcw/ Ben Nuttall-Smith, \"The History of the Federation of BC Writers Extended,\" 7 July 2016]</ref> Maillard studied music at [[Vancouver Community College]], played the Irish pipes, taught recorder and the rudiments of music for the [[Vancouver School Board]] and Vancouver Community College,<ref name=New /><ref name=Gale /> and played bass in the first band formed by Vancouver singer-songwriter, [[Ferron]]. In the late 1970s Maillard taught writing workshops in Vancouver's literary centre, The Literary Storefront, and participated in a number of readings and other events there.<ref>Trevor Carolan, ''The Literary Storefront: The Glory Years 1978\u20131985'' (Mother Tongue Publishing, 2015), 61, 101, 117, 121, 122, 126, 135-36, 227. {{ISBN|978-1-896949-52-9}}.</ref><ref>Nicholas Bradley, review of ''The Literary Storefront: The Glory Years 1878\u20131985'', ''BC Studies'', No. 191, Autumn 2016.</ref> In 1979 Maillard interviewed Canadian novelist Howard O\u2019Hagan who explained to him his writing process; the interview appeared as a chapter in [[Margery Fee]]'s ''Silence Made Visible: Howard O\u2019Hagan and Tay John'' (1992).<ref>Margery Fee, ed. ''Silence Made Visible: Howard O\u2019Hagan and Tay John'' (ECW Press, 1992), 21-38.</ref>\n\nMaillard's first published novel, ''Two Strand River,'' appeared in 1976, published by [[Dave Godfrey]]'s Press Porc\u00e9pic. Most reviewers were confounded by this strange book with its cross-gendered protagonists and weird events, but ''Two Strand River'' soon acquired a cult following, came to be labeled a classic of Canadian [[magic realism]],<ref name=Hancock>Geoff Hancock, \"Keith Maillard,\" ''The Oxford Companion to Canadian Literature,'' eds., William Toy and Eugene Benson (Oxford University Press, 1997, online 2006), 717-718.</ref><ref>Peter Hinchcliffe and Ed Jewinski, ''Magic Realism and Canadian Literature'' (Wilfrid Laurier University, 1985), 82.</ref><ref>Stephen Slemon, \"Magic Realism as Post Colonial Discourse,\" chapter in Lois Parkinson Zamora and Wendy B. Faris, eds., ''Magic Realism: Theory, History, Community'' (Duke University Press, 1995), 409.</ref> and has been republished twice.\n\n== 1980s ==\n\nMaillard's second published novel was actually the first one he had begun; the book rejected by 26 publishers finally&nbsp;\u2013 after having passed through eight major rewrites&nbsp;\u2013 appeared in 1980 as ''Alex Driving South''.<ref>Clark Blaise, \"Relearning Freedom,\" review of ''Alex Driving South'', ''Canadian Literature'' 89 (Summer 1981): 131-133.</ref><ref>[https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/keith-maillard-2/alex-driving-south/ Kirkus Reviews ''Alex Driving South'']</ref> In this gritty, naturalistic tale, Maillard first introduced the fictional town of Raysburg, West Virginia, where most of his novels have been set. ''The Knife in My Hands,'' influenced by American writer [[Jack Kerouac]],<ref name=New /><ref name=Hancock /> followed in 1981, and its sequel, ''Cutting Through,'' in 1982. Then, with a fifth book half-completed, Maillard was afflicted with writer's block.\n\nFrom 1985 through 1988 Maillard applied his writing skills to designing university and adult education courses for the [[Open Learning Agency]] and, from 1986\u20131989, he workshopped his screenplay, ''Two Strand River'', with [[Patricia Gruben]]'s Praxis Film Development Workshop (Simon Fraser University).<ref name=Gale /><ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/british-columbia/celebrated-bc-screenwriting-program-praxis-to-fold/article15508306/ Marsha Lederman, \"Celebrated B.C. screenwriting program Praxis to fold,\" ''The Globe and Mail'', 19 November 2013.]</ref>\n\nMaillard's fifth novel, ''Motet,'' published in 1989, won the [[Ethel Wilson Fiction Prize]].<ref>[http://www.canadianauthors.net/awards/bc_book_prizes/ethel_wilson_fiction_prize/ Ethel Wilson Fiction Prize]</ref> Reviewer David Homel assured readers that despite the novel's sixteenth-century Dutch choral mystery and Vancouver setting, \"power and madness made in the USA is still at the heart of Maillard's creativity.\"<ref>[http://www.booksincanada.com/article_view.asp?id=2291 David Homel, \"Harmonics,\" ''Books in Canada'', 1989]</ref>\n\nHaving taught as a sessional lecturer at both the [[University of British Columbia]] (UBC) and [[Simon Fraser University]], Maillard was appointed in 1989 to a regular teaching position in UBC's Creative Writing Department, where he has taught every genre except stage writing.<ref name=New>William H. New, \"Keith Maillard,\" ''Encyclopedia of Literature in Canada'' (University of Toronto Press, 2002), 700.</ref> He served as Advisory Editor of ''[[PRISM international]]'' for 10 years.\n\n== 1990s ==\n\nWhile at UBC, Maillard began what he considers his mature work \u2013 what has come to be known as the \"Raysburg Series.\"<ref name=Hancock /><ref>Meredith Sue Willis, \"Keith Maillard: Five Novels of Raysburg,  West Virginia,\" ''Appalachian Journal'', Vol. 31, No. 3/4 (2004): 358-366.</ref><ref>[http://www.wvencyclopedia.org/articles/1417 Gordon Simmons, \"Literature,\" e-WV: The West Virginia Encyclopedia, 4 February 2014. Web. 1 May 2018]</ref><ref>Gordon K. Neufeld, \"Laugh, cry, and laugh again,\" ''Books in Canada'', Vol. 31, Issue 9, December 2002.</ref><ref name=New /> Called \"a small masterpiece\" by the ''Georgia Straight'', ''Light in the Company of Women'' was published in 1993<ref>Lorraine York, \"Photographic Mixtures,\" ''Canadian Literature'' 141 (Summer 1994): 115-116.</ref> and was runner-up for the [[Ethel Wilson Fiction Prize]].<ref>[http://www.canadianauthors.net/awards/bc_book_prizes/ethel_wilson_fiction_prize/ Ethel Wilson Fiction Prize]</ref> It was followed in 1995 by ''Hazard Zones'', which was included on the ''[[Toronto Star]]'''s list of the best Canadian books for that year and was short-listed for the [[Commonwealth Writers' Prize]].<ref>[https://www.librarything.com/bookaward/Commonwealth+Writers%27+Prize+Shortlist Commonwealth Writers' Prize Shortlist]</ref>  \n\nMaillard's novel, ''Gloria'' (1999), was well received in Canada,<ref>T. F. Rigelhof, ''Hooked on Canadian Books: The Good, the Better, and the Best Canadian Novels Since 1984'' (Cormorant Books, 2010), 258.</ref> short-listed for the [[Governor General's Literary Award]] for Fiction,<ref>Anne-Marie Tobin, \"Matt Cohen, Keith Maillard among GG literary finalists,\" ''Canadian Press Newswire'', 9 October 1999.</ref> and brought him national attention in the United States.<ref>[https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/books/00/10/08/bib/001008.rv104213.html Jesse Browner, \"Little Gloria Free at Last,\" ''The New York Times,'' 8 October 2000]</ref> <ref>[https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/keith-maillard/gloria-2/ GLORIA by Keith Maillard, starred review, ''Kirkus Reviews'', 1 July, 2000] </ref>\n\nMaillard also returned to his first love, poetry, and published ''Dementia Americana'', which won the [[Gerald Lampert Award]] for the best first book of poetry published in Canada.<ref>[http://poets.ca/lampert Gerald Lampert Memorial Award]</ref> He became interested in the re-emergence of formal poetry in North America and commented about it in his oft-cited essay, \"The New Formalism and the Return of Prosody.\"<ref>Paul Scott Derrick, ''Lines of Thought: 1983\u20132015'' (Universitat de Valencia, 2015), 143.</ref><ref>Gerry Cambridge, \"The New Formalism,\" Jay Parini, ed., ''The Oxford Encyclopedia of American Literature'' (Oxford University Press, 2004), 251, 253-54.</ref><ref>[http://www.persee.fr/doc/rfea_0397-7870_2000_num_84_1_1804 Thomas Cable, \"Connoisseurs of sound and the new formalism,\" ''Revue Francaise d'Etudes Americaines,'' No. 84 (March 2000):52-52]</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060224095203/http://www.antigonishreview.com/bi-109/109-maillard.html Keith Maillard, review of ''Rebel Angels'', ''The Antigonish Review'', 109 (1999).]</ref><ref>Keith Maillard, \"The New Formalism and the Return of Prosody,\" in R.S. Gwynn, ''New Expansive Poetry'' (1999): 52-71.</ref><ref>Catherine Addison, ''A Genealogy of the Verse Novel'' (Cambridge Scholars Publishing, 2017), 424.</ref><ref>Gregory Dowling, \"New Formalism: Dangerous Nostalgia or Angellic Rebellion?\" ''Letteratura e letterature,'' 3 (2009): 1-20.</ref>\n\n== 2000s ==\n\nThe last of the \"Raysburg Series\", ''The Clarinet Polka'' (2002), was well received in the United States, particularly by the Polish American community.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2003/05/04/books/books-in-brief-fiction-poetry-402320.html Etelka Lehoczky, \"Books in Brief: Fiction and Poetry,\" ''The New York Times,'' 4 May 2003]</ref><ref>{{cite news | first=Zofia | last=Smardz | title=Banding Together | newspaper=The Washington Post | date=4 May 2003 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/entertainment/books/2003/05/04/banding-together/130f3dba-4a65-48b5-9f71-e72b1ba1c552/ | accessdate=1 May 2018 }}</ref><ref>David James Jackson, \" 'Another Polka Rockin' Weekend': Polish American Polka Music, Identity, and Traditional Values,\" ''Polish American Studies'', Vol. 71, No. 1 (Spring 2014), 47.</ref><ref>William Hal Gorby, \"Saints,  Sinners, and Socialists on the Southside: Polish Catholic Immigrant Workers, Politics, and Culture in Wheeling, West Virginia, 1890-1930,\" PhD thesis, University of West Virginia (2014), 2, 120, 123, 124, 128, 129, 351, 355-56.</ref><ref>T. J. Napierkowski, \"''The Clarinet Polka'': Life, Literature, Music,\" ''Polish American Studies'', Vol. 61, No. 2 (Autumn 2004): 9-24.</ref> It received starred reviews from ''Library Journal'', ''Publishers Weekly'', ''Booklist'', and ''Kirkus Reviews'',<ref>Inside jacket copy, Keith Maillard, ''Looking Good'' (2006), n.p. </ref> and was included in  ''Booklist''\u2019s Editors\u2019 Choice \u201903. It won the Polish American Historical Association's Creative Arts Prize, and came to the attention of scholars in Poland.<ref>[https://www.booklistonline.com/Booklist-Editors-Choice/pid=2855242 Booklist's Editors' Choice: Adult Books, 2003]</ref><ref>[http://polishamericanstudies.org/text/26/creative-arts.html Polish American Historical Association Creative Arts Prize]</ref><ref>A. Branach-Kallas, \"Folkloristic Hybrids: Diaspora Space in ''The Clarinet Polka'' by Keith Maillard,\"  ''Przegl\u0105d Polonijny,'' Vol. 31, Issue 2 (2005):105-112.</ref>\n\nMaillard was one of 35 writers placed on the West Virginia Literary Map in 2004 and he was inducted that year into the Wheeling, West Virginia, Hall of Fame.<ref name=Maillardfame />\n\nIn 2004, Maillard returned to the raw [[Bildungsroman]]<ref>William H. New, ''A History of Canadian Literature'' (McGill-Queens, 2003), 229, 237.</ref> material first published in ''The Knife in My Hands'' and ''Cutting Through'' and rewrote and reshaped it into the ''Difficulty at the Beginning'' quartet, which appeared in four volumes between September 2005 and September 2006.<ref>Gordon Simmons, Review of ''Difficulty at the Beginning'', ''Appalachian Heritage'', Vol. 35, No. 4 (Fall 2007): 103-105.</ref> The [[Toronto]] ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' selected ''Difficulty at the Beginning'' as one of the top books of 2006, calling it \"a work of terrible beauty and grace, a masterpiece fit to contend with the best novels of the last century.\"<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/the-unbearable-lightness-of-being-american/article729950/ Tom Sandborn, \"The unbearable lightness of being American,\"''The Globe and Mail'', 10 June 2006]</ref><ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/the-60s-on-the-instalment-plan/article714388/ Tom Sandborn, \"The '60s on the installment plan,\" ''The Globe and Mail'', 21 October 2006.]</ref> Reviewer Richard Helm describes the quartet as Maillard's \"magnum opus and the keystone of a literary career that has flown largely under the Canadian radar.\" He characterizes Maillard as \"probably the most famous Canadian novelist you've never heard of.\"<ref>[https://www.pressreader.com/canada/calgary-herald/20060921/282879431237496 Richard Helm, \"Maillard Canada's best unknown writer,\" ''Calgary Herald,'' 21 September 2006].</ref>\n\nIn 2006, with eleven out of fourteen titles nominated for or winners of literary awards, Maillard won UBC's Dorothy Somerset Award for excellence in the creative arts.<ref>[https://news.ubc.ca/2007/03/01/archive-ubcreports-2007-07mar01-07mar01kudos/ \"Kudos,\" ''UBC Reports'', Vol. 53, No.3, 1 March, 2007]</ref>\n\n== 2010s ==\n\nIn its 80th anniversary edition in 2015, the ''[[Quill & Quire]]'' listed Maillard as one of Canada's \"notable Canlit talent\" along with other American-born anti-Vietnam-War authors, Philip Marchand, Jack Todd, [[Judith Merrill]], [[Mark Frutkin]], and [[William Gibson]].<ref>[https://quillandquire.com/book-culture/2015/04/15/80-years-of-qq-canlit-personalities-3/3/ \"80 years of Q&Q: getting personal with Canlit personalities,\" ''Quill & Quire'', 15 April 2015]</ref>\n\nIn his most recent novel ''Twin Studies'' (2018) -- set in Vancouver, Medicine Hat, and Los Angeles -- Maillard returns to the topic of gender fluidity that he first explored in ''Two Strand River'' in 1976.<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/books/article-the-globe-100-our-favourite-books-of-2018/\"The Globe 100: Our favourite books of 2018,\" ''The Globe and Mail'', 30 November 2018.]</ref><ref>[https://bcbooklook.com/2019/01/22/471-gender-manga-and-teen-idiom/ Theo Dombrowski, \"Gender, manga, and teen idiom,\" ''BC BookLook'', 22 January 2019.]</ref> Apple's iBooks reviewed the novel and  described it as \" a fascinating exploration of wealth, class, and gender fluidity [that] reads like a 21st-century Canadian version of Dickens' London novels.\"<ref>[https://books.apple.com/ca/book/twin-studies/id1370910770 Apple Books review of Keith Maillard's Twin Studies, 2018.]</ref> Steven Beattie, in the September 2018 issue of ''Quill & Quire'', notes that Maillard's subject matter arises out of lived experience. \"When the author began publishing, the language for describing gender-fluid approaches did not exist.\" As Maillard himself put it in his interview with Beattie, \"You can't apply a term to yourself unless it is culturally available. I would now call myself non-binary.\" <ref>[https://quillandquire.com/authors/keith-maillard-prizes-a-multiplicity-of-approaches-to-literary-craft-as-a-writer-and-teacher/ Steven W. Beattie, \"Doubling down: As a writer and teacher, Keith Maillard prizes a multiplicity of approaches to literary craft,\" ''Quill & Quire'', September 2018, 6-7.]</ref>  \n\nThe  ''Vancouver Sun'' summarized ''Twin Studies'' as \"that rare work: a story that grapples with difficult intellectual issues without ever abandoning the novelist's primary duty -- compelling narrative.\"<ref> [https://vancouversun.com/entertainment/books/book-review-keith-malliards-twin-studies-displays-a-lyrical-beauty/ Tom Sandborn, \"Keith Maillard's ''Twin Studies'' displays a lyrical beauty,\" ''Vancouver Sun'', 5 October 2018.]</ref> Maillard\u2019s novel challenges the idea of isolated nuclear families and envisions what he says is \u201c a fluid larger family, in which people come together for other reasons. I think it's essential that we start rethinking family, that we start rethinking our connections to each other.\u201d<ref> [https://www.cbc.ca/radio/thenextchapter/why-keith-maillard-s-novel-twin-studies-dissects-the-nature-of-love-and-family-1.5056760 \"Why Keith Maillard's novel ''Twin Studies'' dissects the nature of love and family,\" CBC Radio, 16 March 2019.]</ref> \n\n''Twin Studies'' won the Alberta Book of the Year Award from the Book Publishers Association of Alberta.<ref>[https://freehand-books.com/three-freehand-books-win-at-alberta-book-publishing-awards/ \"Three Freehand books win at Alberta Book Publishing Awards,\" Freehand Books, September 2019]</ref> In an interview with Quentin Mills-Fenn of ''Prairie books Now'', Maillard explained that his book explores \u201dthe impact of traumatic experiences,\u201d and that he firmly believes that \u201c[p]hysicians and therapists who work with children and adolescents are telling us that a gender-affirming point of view from parents and, if possible, from the surrounding culture, makes for healthy and happy kids.\"<ref>[https://prairiebooksnow.ca/articles/view/a-complex-pairing-delves-into-genetics-and-identity Quentin Miles-Fenn, \"A complex pairing delves into genetics and identity,\" ''Prairie books NOW'', Fall/Winter 2018/2019.]</ref>\n\nMaillard's first non-fiction book, ''Fatherless: A Memoir'' (2019), traces the life of the mysterious father he never knew, and was well received in Canada. <ref>[https://vancouversun.com/entertainment/books/book-review-b-c-novelist-keith-maillard-writes-about-his-search-for-the-father-who-abandoned-him Tom Sandborn, \"B.C. novelist Keith Maillard writes about his search for the father who abandoned him,\" ''Vancouver Sun'', 8 November 2019.] </ref> <ref>[https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/books/2019/11/21/keith-maillard-talks-about-his-absentee-fathers-one-last-gut-punch-from-beyond-the-grave.html Sue Carter, \"Keith Maillard talks about his absentee father's 'one last gut punch from the grave,' \" ''Toronto Star'', 21 November 2019.] </ref> <ref>[https://quillandquire.com/review/fatherless-a-memoir/ Robert J. Wiersema, Book Review, ''Fatherless: A Memoir'', ''Quill & Quire'', December 2019, 21.]</ref> CBC Arts columnist and creative nonfiction author/editor [[Alicia Elliott]] writes that Maillard's memoir \"gives us a model of not only self awareness and honesty but also, more importantly, healing.\"<ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/arts/new-year-new-me-how-memoirs-can-help-us-shape-our-futures-by-examining-other-people-s-pasts-1.5435211 Alicia Elliott, \"New year, new me? How memoirs can help us shape our futures by examining other people's pasts,\" ''CBC Arts'', 22 January 2020.]</ref>\n\n== 2020s ==\n\nMaillard's papers are currently held by the University of British Columbia's Rare Books and Special Collections.<ref name=Maillardfonds /> A complete list of Maillard's publications can be found on his website.<ref>[https://keithmaillard.com/writing/publications-list Keith Maillard Publications List]</ref>\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\n* 1986: winner Praxis Competition, ''Two Strand River''\n* 1990: winner [[Ethel Wilson Fiction Prize]], ''Motet''\n* 1994: runner-up [[Ethel Wilson Fiction Prize]], ''Light in the Company of Women''\n* 1995: winner [[Gerald Lampert Award]], ''Dementia Americana''\n* 1996: shortlisted [[Commonwealth Writers' Prize]], ''Hazard Zones''\n* [[1999 Governor General's Awards|1999: fiction finalist, Governor General's Awards]], ''Gloria''\n* 2004: winner West Virginia Literary Merit Award\n* 2005: winner [[Polish American Historical Association]] Creative Arts Prize, ''The Clarinet Polka''\n* 2005: shortlisted Weatherford Award, ''Running''\n* 2006: longlisted [[ReLit Awards]], ''Looking Good''\n* 2006: shortlisted Weatherford Award ''Morgantown''\n* 2006: shortlisted Weatherford Award, ''Lyndon Johnston and the Majorettes''\n* 2006: winner Dorothy Somerset Award for Excellence in the Creative Arts\n* 2018: The ''Globe'' 100, ''Twin Studies''\n* 2019: winner Alberta Book of the Year Award: Trade Fiction, ''Twin Studies''\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* 1976: ''Two Strand River'' (Press Porcepic) {{ISBN|0-88878-088-5}}\n** 1982 reissue: ''Two Strand River'' (General Publishing) {{ISBN|0-7736-7031-9}}\n** 1996 reissue: ''Two Strand River'' (HarperCollins) {{ISBN|0-00-648143-4}}\n** 2013 reissue: ''Two Strand River'' (Keith Maillard) ebook {{ASIN|BOOCOKVS4A}} \n* 1980: ''Alex Driving South'' (Dial Press) {{ISBN|0-8037-0196-9}}\n** 1983 reissue: ''Alex Driving South'' (General Publishing) {{ISBN|0-7736-7045-9}}\n** 2013 reissue: ''Alex Driving South'' (Keith Maillard) ebook {{ASIN|BOOB7ABDL2}}\n* 1981: ''The Knife in my Hands'' (General) {{ISBN|0-7737-0057-9}}\n** 1982 reissue: ''The Knife in my Hands'' (Beaufort) {{ISBN|978-0-825-30082-0}}\n* 1982: ''Cutting Through'' (Stoddart) {{ISBN|0-7737-2003-0}}\n** 1983 reissue: Cutting Through (Beaufort) {{ISBN|0-8253-0120-3}}\n* 1989: ''Motet'' (Random House) {{ISBN|0-394-22028-5}}\n** 1997 reissue: ''Motet'' (HarperCollins) {{ISBN|0-00-648163-9}}\n** 1998 reissue: ''Motet'' (Harvill Press) {{ISBN|978-0-00-648163-8}}\n** 2013 reissue: ''Motet'' (Keith Maillard) ebook {{ASIN|BOOAYB4N5S}}\n* 1993: ''Light in the Company of Women'' (HarperCollins) {{ISBN|0-00-223894-2}}\n* 1994: ''Dementia Americana'', poems (Ronsdale/Cacanadadada) {{ISBN|0-921870-28-0}}\n* 1995: ''Hazard Zones'' (Harper Perennial) {{ISBN|0-00-224397-0}}\n* 1999: ''Gloria'' (Harper Flamingo) {{ISBN|0-00-648175-2}}\n** 2000: reissue: ''Gloria'' (Soho Press) {{ISBN|978-1-56947-206-4}}\n** 2001: reissue: ''Gloria'' (HarperFlamingo) {{ISBN|978-0-00-648175-1}}\n* 2002: ''The Clarinet Polka'' (Thomas Allen) {{ISBN|0-88762-100-7}}\n** 2003: reissue: ''The Clarinet Polka'' (St.Martin's Press) {{ISBN|0-312-30889-2}}\n** 2004: reissue: ''The Clarinet Polka'' (St.Martin's Griffin) {{ISBN|978-0-312-30890-2}}\n* 2005: ''Running'' (Brindle & Glass) {{ISBN|1-897142-06-4