References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://keithmaillard.com/ Official website]\n* [https://abcbookworld.com/scripter/scripter-7050/ BC Bookworld profile]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110927162419/http://www.wvwc.edu/library/wv_authors/authors/a_maillard.htm West Virginia Wesleyan College / Annie Merner Pfeiffer Library: Keith Maillard profile]\n* [http://go.galegroup.com/ps/i.do?p=LitRC&u=ubcolumbia&id=GALE%7CH1000063179&v=2.1&it=r&sid=LitRC&asid=de1c0d0d \"Keith Maillard,\" Contemporary Authors Online: Keith Maillard profile]\n* [http://www.ohiocountylibrary.org/wheeling-history/wheeling-hall-of-fame-keith-lee-maillard--/4194 Ohio County Public Library, \"Wheeling Hall of Fame: Keith Maillard\"]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maillard, Keith}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian male novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian novelists]]\n[[Category:Canadian male poets]]\n[[Category:Writers from Wheeling, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Writers from British Columbia]]\n[[Category:University of British Columbia faculty]]\n[[Category:West Virginia University]]\n", "name_user": "Herbie 53 Ocho", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFamily background", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keith_Maillard"}
{"title_page": "George Obrenovi\u0107", "text_new": "{{short description|Pretender of the Serbian throne}}\n{{Infobox pretender\n| name         = George Obrenovic\n| image        = Prince George Obrenovic.jpg\n| birth_date   = {{Birth-date|March 1890}}\n| birth_place  = [[Belgrade]], [[Kingdom of Serbia]]\n| death_date   = {{Death-date and age|9 October 1925|March 1890}}\n| death_place  = [[Hungary]]\n| regnal       = \n| title        = Prince George Obrenovi\u0107\n| throne       = [[Serbia]]\n| pretend from = 11 June 1903\n| year         = 1903\u00b9\n| king         = [[Alexander I of Serbia]]\n| relationship = Half brother\n| house        = \n| father       = [[Milan I of Serbia]]\n| mother       = Artemisia Christich\n| spouse       = \n| children     = \n| predecessor  = \n| successor    = \n| footnotes    = \u00b9 year House of Obrenovi\u0107 deposed\n}}\n'''Milan George Obrenovic''' (1889<ref>Allstr\u00f6m, Carl Magnus (1904). Dictionary of royal lineage of Europe and other countries. Volume 2.</ref>/March 1890<ref>{{Citation | title = George Obrenovitch, The Boy Pretender to the shaky throne of Servia. | newspaper = [[Detroit Free Press]] | pages = D5 | date = 25 February 1906 }}</ref> &ndash; 9 October 1925)<ref name=last/> born '''Obren Christich''' was the [[Legitimacy (family law)|natural]] son of King [[Milan I of Serbia]] and his [[Greeks|Greek]] mistress Artemisia Hristi\u0107 (n\u00e9e Joanides). After the [[regicide]] of his half brother King [[Alexander I of Serbia|Alexander]] in 1903 George became a claimant to the Serbian throne in opposition to the new king, [[Peter I Karadordevic]] before ending his life in obscurity.\n\n==Birth and family background==\nAlthough commonly known as George Obrenovi\u0107 he was born in [[Belgrade]]<ref name=MDF1908/> as Obren Hristi\u0107. Acknowledged by King Milan as his son, he was given the name Obren at birth to underline his kinship to the ruling [[House of Obrenovi\u0107]].<ref>{{Citation | title = Ex-King Milan | volume = LV | issue = 6 | newspaper = [[The Evening Post (New Zealand)|The Evening Post]] | pages = 5 | date = 8 January 1898 }}</ref> The husband of George\u2019s mother was Milan Hristi\u0107, the king\u2019s private secretary and son of the Serbian statesman [[Filip Hristi\u0107]].\n\nThe relationship between the parents of George and the fact his mother was living in the Royal Palace, caused a great scandal and resulted in Queen [[Natalie of Serbia|Natalie]] fleeing Belgrade with her son Crown Prince [[Alexander I of Serbia|Alexander]] for [[Wiesbaden]] in the German Empire. His mother\u2019s husband was subsequently removed from his position as private secretary and sent abroad as Serbian Minister to [[Berlin]] on condition his wife stays in Belgrade. This appointment fell through however after the Berlin court made it clear he was unwelcome so he was instead sent to Rome.<ref>{{Citation | title = Servia is a hotbed of wicked plots | newspaper = The Dupuyer Acantha | pages = 18 | date = 21 September 1899 }}</ref> Although King Milan had given a written promise of marriage to Artemisia his attempts to divorce Queen Natalie were opposed by Michael, the [[Metropolitan of Belgrade]].<ref>{{Citation | title = Milan's new intrigue | newspaper = [[The Evening Telegram]] | pages = 3 | date = 10 January 1898 }}</ref>\n\nEventually both of George\u2019s parents secured divorces from their respective spouses. Five months after his divorce on 6 March 1889 King Milan abdicated from the Serbian throne angering George\u2019s mother. After eventually growing tired of ex-King Milan\u2019s demands for money from her, Artemisa took George to live in [[Constantinople]] where her father lived and had acquired substantial wealth first as a landscape gardener and architect to the [[Ottoman sultan]] and later in Banking.<ref name=MDF1908>{{Citation | title = Marquise de Fontenoy | newspaper = [[Chicago Daily Tribune]] | pages = 10 | date = 18 April 1908 }}</ref> Ex-King Milan then broke off his promise of marriage and turned instead to the Serbian government for financial assistance<ref name=MDF1908/> and was eventually even reconciled with his ex-wife Queen Natalie on 8 March 1893.<ref>{{Cite book | title = [[Almanach de Gotha]] | publisher = [[Justus Perthes]] | edition =159th | year = 1922 | pages = 100}}</ref>\n\n==Serbian pretender==\n\nWith the breakdown of the relationship of his parents George was raised in a privileged environment by his mother in Constantinople.<ref name=MDF1908/> Following the death in 1901 of his father in exile in [[Vienna]], George\u2019s life changed. Some of his late father\u2019s friends who were appalled by his half brother King Alexander\u2019s treatment of King Milan took an interest in him as a possible candidate for the Serbian throne. One friend, the Hungarian count Eugene Zichy, assumed the role of his guardian. Count Eugene generally treated him as his own son and attempted to get the agreement of Emperor [[Franz Joseph I of Austria|Franz Joseph I]] to enrol George in the [[Theresian Military Academy]].<ref name=MDF1908/> However, as his pretensions to the Serbian throne were not viewed favourably in Vienna the emperor refused to allow his enrolment.<ref name=MDF1903>{{Citation | title = Letter of Marquise de Fontenoy | newspaper = [[Chicago Daily Tribune]] | pages = 6 | date = 20 October 1903 }}</ref>\n\nAlthough the natural son of King Milan and even though his half brother and his consort [[Draga Ma\u0161in|Queen Draga]] were without an heir George was not seen by his half brother as a possible successor to the throne. Instead the queens brother Nikodije Lunjevica and [[Prince Mirko of Montenegro]], who was married to [[Natalija Konstantinovi\u0107]] (granddaughter of [[Princess Anka Obrenovi\u0107]]) were talked of as being named the heir.\n\nAfter the regicide of his half brother King Alexander and his consort Queen Draga in 1903 the throne of Serbia was offered to Prince [[Peter I of Serbia|Peter Karageorgevich]] whose family had a decades long feud with the Obrenovi\u0107\u2019s over the throne. As the sole male line descendant of the Obrenovi\u0107\u2019s, George\u2019s guardian Count Eugene claimed that his father King Milan had legally adopted him and as such this was enough to legitimise him, and his claims to the throne and make him the heir to his father and half brother.<ref name=MDF1903/> George had support within Serbia in the aftermath of the regicide with his supporters posting proclamations in Belgrade and fighting with supporters of the newly elected king, Peter Karageorgevich.<ref>{{Citation | title = Peter Accepts | newspaper = The Chenango Semi-Weekly Telegraph | pages = 4 | date = 17 June 1903 }}</ref> Although there were reports that George and his mother were to cross over into Serbia nothing came of this<ref>{{Citation | title = The Porte Notified | newspaper = The Deseret News | pages = 1 | date = 16 June 1903 }}</ref> and the Ottoman sultan advised his mother that he should be kept off the streets over fears that he would be assassinated.<ref>{{Citation | title = Fears attempt to kill young Milan | newspaper = Easton Free Press | pages = 1 | date = 17 June 1903 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1906, three years after the death of his half brother and the accession of King Peter Karageorgevich, George made an unsuccessful attempt to gain the throne of Serbia.<ref name=adg>{{Cite book | title = [[Almanach de Gotha]] | publisher = Almanach de Gotha | volume = 1 |edition=186th | year = 2003 | pages = 349}}</ref> In June while studying in [[Klausenburg]], [[Kingdom of Hungary|Hungary]] a dispute in a coffee shop led to a [[duel]] with swords being fought between George and a university student. Although he survived the duel he came off worse sustaining injuries to his head, shoulder and breast.<ref>{{Citation | title = King's son is wounded in duel with student |page=4 | newspaper = [[The Washington Times]] | date = 19 June 1906 }}</ref> He suffered a further blow at the end of that year when his guardian Count Eugene Zichy died on Boxing Day<ref>{{Citation | title = Count Eugene Zichy | newspaper = [[New York Times]] | date = 27 December 1906 }}</ref> leaving George little in his will having used his own money to support his pretensions, as King Milan had left nothing to his son.<ref name=MDF1908/> All was not lost however as he still had a large inheritance to look forward to from his grandfather in Constantinople.\n\n==Fall into obscurity==\n\nBack in the Ottoman capital in February 1907 George survived an assassination attempt when a man wielding a dagger attempted to stab him in his chest, however he escaped with just a scratch after the dagger hit a thick pocket book he was carrying.<ref>{{Citation | title = Tries to kill Milan's son | newspaper = [[New York Times]] | date = 7 February 1907 }}</ref> Five months later in July 1907 a bomb went off outside the US Embassy in Constantinople. As George lived in a house adjoining the embassy word spread that it was an assassination attempt by agents of King Peter Karageorgevich. This explanation for the bombing was met with some scepticism and viewed by some as an attempt to use the explosion to keep George in the public eye.<ref>{{Citation | title = Bomb not for Leishman | newspaper = [[The Baltimore Sun]] | pages = 7 | date = 17 July 1908 }}</ref> The following month it was reported that he had attempted to take his own life after the Ottoman authorities had refused to allow him to assume the surname Obrenovi\u0107.<ref>{{Citation | title = Cable News | volume = XXIX | issue = 7268 | newspaper = [[Ashburton Guardian]] | pages = 2 | date = 8 January 1898 }}</ref> There may however have been other issues on his mind as an investigation into the bombing concluded that George had set it up himself to make it look like an attempt on his life. As a result, he was expelled from Turkey by the Sultan. The discovery also cost George his inheritance from his grandfather who was furious at his grandson's actions and wrote him out of his will. His grandfather died later that year before any chance for reconciliation could ever take place.<ref name=MDF1908/>\n         \nNow banished from Turkey George made his way to Paris before heading to [[Austria-Hungary]] where he received some support from his late father\u2019s friends<ref name=MDF1908/> who saw the potential that he may one day ascend the Serbian throne.<ref name=spencer>{{Citation |last= Spencer |first=James | title = Traded claim to throne to lead life of dishonour | newspaper = [[The Atlanta Constitution]] | pages = B1 | date = 18 April 1909 }}</ref> To help boost his finances failed attempts were also made to secure a rich wife from Austria-Hungary or America for him. When the support came to an end he largely disappeared from view travelling around Europe and falling into debt.<ref name=spencer/> Eventually he fell into comparative poverty and tried his hand at a number of different jobs to survive.<ref name=miami>{{Citation | title = Son of King Milan is waiter on dining car | newspaper = [[The Miami News]] | pages = 7 | date = 19 August 1916 }}</ref> After his attempt to work in the Austro-Hungarian state ministries failed due to his lack of qualifications, he worked at various jobs such as a stable boy and professional jockey<ref name=last>{{Citation | title = Last Obronovitch Dies | newspaper = [[New York Times]] | date = 11 October 1925 }}</ref> before trying his hand at singing in caf\u00e9s<ref>{{Citation | title = King's son a cafe singer | newspaper = [[New York Times]] | date = 28 January 1909 }}</ref> and on stage, until he was forced to abandon that career by the police due to the fact he had been billing himself as a prince.<ref name=miami/> He then went on to work as a waiter, and a porter in sleeping cars on the [[Orient Express]].<ref name=last/> His name reappeared in connection to his old pretensions during [[World War I]] when it was falsely reported in January 1916 that he had been proclaimed [[King of Serbia]] by the Germans and Austro-Hungarians.<ref>{{Citation | title = Proclaim new Serb King?; Italian Story That Teutons Have Chosen Natural Son of Milan | newspaper = [[New York Times]] | date = 13 January 1916 }}</ref>\n\nGeorge later went on to become a writer, however the only book he ever wrote, which was about the life of his father King Milan, was suppressed by the Serbian government. George Obrenovi\u0107 died penniless in a Hungarian [[poorhouse]] on 9 October 1925.<ref name=last/>\n\n==Possible descendants==\n\nAccording to a 2003 article by the Serbian media company [[Novosti AD]], George had a son called Stefan who served as a cavalry captain in the [[French Army]]. Stefan in turn had a son named Panta (Panka) Obrenovi\u0107 (also known as Mark Eme) who served as chairman of the \"Fund Obrenovi\u0107\" until his death in [[Paris]] in early 2002.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nasle\u0111e umesto krune |author=Milorad BO\u0160NJAK |url=http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/naslovna/aktuelno.69.html:143406-Nasle273e-umesto-krune |newspaper=[[Novosti AD]] |date=11 January 2003 |accessdate=12 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:George Obrenovic}}\n[[Category:1890 births]]\n[[Category:1925 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Belgrade]]\n[[Category:People from the Kingdom of Serbia]]\n[[Category:Pretenders to the Serbian throne]]\n[[Category:Obrenovi\u0107 dynasty]]\n[[Category:Serbian writers]]\n[[Category:Illegitimate children of monarchs]]\n[[Category:Duellists]]\n[[Category:Serbian people of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:Writers from Belgrade]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Pretender of the Serbian throne}}\n{{Infobox pretender\n| name         = George Obrenovic\n| image        = Prince George Obrenovic.jpg\n| birth_date   = {{Birth-date|March 1890}}\n| birth_place  = [[Belgrade]], [[Kingdom of Serbia]]\n| death_date   = {{Death-date and age|9 October 1925|March 1890}}\n| death_place  = [[Hungary]]\n| regnal       = \n| title        = Prince George Obrenovi\u0107\n| throne       = [[Serbia]]\n| pretend from = 11 June 1903\n| year         = 1903\u00b9\n| king         = [[Alexander I of Serbia]]\n| relationship = Half brother\n| house        = \n| father       = [[Milan I of Serbia]]\n| mother       = Artemisia Christich\n| spouse       = \n| children     = \n| predecessor  = \n| successor    = \n| footnotes    = \u00b9 year House of Obrenovi\u0107 deposed\n}}\n'''Milan George Obrenovic''' (1889<ref>Allstr\u00f6m, Carl Magnus (1904). Dictionary of royal lineage of Europe and other countries. Volume 2.</ref>/March 1890<ref>{{Citation | title = George Obrenovitch, The Boy Pretender to the shaky throne of Servia. | newspaper = [[Detroit Free Press]] | pages = D5 | date = 25 February 1906 }}</ref> &ndash; 9 October 1925)<ref name=last/> born '''Obren Christich''' was the [[Legitimacy (family law)|natural]] son of King [[Milan I of Serbia]] and his [[Greeks|Greek]] mistress Artemisia Hristi\u0107 (n\u00e9e Joanides). After the [[regicide]] of his half brother King [[Alexander I of Serbia|Alexander]] in 1903 George became a claimant to the Serbian throne in opposition to the new king, [[Peter I Karadordevic]] before ending his life in obscurity.\n\n==Birth and family background==\nAlthough commonly known as George Obrenovi\u0107 he was born in [[Belgrade]]<ref name=MDF1908/> as Obren Hristi\u0107. Acknowledged by King Milan as his son, he was given the name Obren at birth to underline his kinship to the ruling [[House of Obrenovi\u0107]].<ref>{{Citation | title = Ex-King Milan | volume = LV | issue = 6 | newspaper = [[The Evening Post (New Zealand)|The Evening Post]] | pages = 5 | date = 8 January 1898 }}</ref> The husband of George\u2019s mother was Milan Hristi\u0107, the king\u2019s private secretary and son of the Serbian statesman [[Filip Hristi\u0107]].\n\nThe relationship between the parents of George and the fact his mother was living in the Royal Palace, caused a great scandal and resulted in Queen [[Natalie of Serbia|Natalie]] fleeing Belgrade with her son Crown Prince [[Alexander I of Serbia|Alexander]] for [[Wiesbaden]] in the German Empire. His mother\u2019s husband was subsequently removed from his position as private secretary and sent abroad as Serbian Minister to [[Berlin]] on condition his wife stays in Belgrade. This appointment fell through however after the Berlin court made it clear he was unwelcome so he was instead sent to Rome.<ref>{{Citation | title = Servia is a hotbed of wicked plots | newspaper = The Dupuyer Acantha | pages = 18 | date = 21 September 1899 }}</ref> Although King Milan had given a written promise of marriage to Artemisia his attempts to divorce Queen Natalie were opposed by Michael, the [[Metropolitan of Belgrade]].<ref>{{Citation | title = Milan's new intrigue | newspaper = [[The Evening Telegram]] | pages = 3 | date = 10 January 1898 }}</ref>\n\nEventually both of George\u2019s parents secured divorces from their respective spouses. Five months after his divorce on 6 March 1889 King Milan abdicated from the Serbian throne angering George\u2019s mother. After eventually growing tired of ex-King Milan\u2019s demands for money from her, Artemisa took George to live in [[Constantinople]] where her father lived and had acquired substantial wealth first as a landscape gardener and architect to the [[Ottoman sultan]] and later in Banking.<ref name=MDF1908>{{Citation | title = Marquise de Fontenoy | newspaper = [[Chicago Daily Tribune]] | pages = 10 | date = 18 April 1908 }}</ref> Ex-King Milan then broke off his promise of marriage and turned instead to the Serbian government for financial assistance<ref name=MDF1908/> and was eventually even reconciled with his ex-wife Queen Natalie on 8 March 1893.<ref>{{Cite book | title = [[Almanach de Gotha]] | publisher = [[Justus Perthes]] | edition =159th | year = 1922 | pages = 100}}</ref>\n\n==Serbian pretender==\n\nWith the breakdown of the relationship of his parents George was raised in a privileged environment by his mother in Constantinople.<ref name=MDF1908/> Following the death in 1901 of his father in exile in [[Vienna]], George\u2019s life changed. Some of his late father\u2019s friends who were appalled by his half brother King Alexander\u2019s treatment of King Milan took an interest in him as a possible candidate for the Serbian throne. One friend, the Hungarian count Eugene Zichy, assumed the role of his guardian. Count Eugene generally treated him as his own son and attempted to get the agreement of Emperor [[Franz Joseph I of Austria|Franz Joseph I]] to enrol George in the [[Theresian Military Academy]].<ref name=MDF1908/> However, as his pretensions to the Serbian throne were not viewed favourably in Vienna the emperor refused to allow his enrolment.<ref name=MDF1903>{{Citation | title = Letter of Marquise de Fontenoy | newspaper = [[Chicago Daily Tribune]] | pages = 6 | date = 20 October 1903 }}</ref>\n\nAlthough the natural son of King Milan and even though his half brother and his consort [[Draga Ma\u0161in|Queen Draga]] were without an heir George was not seen by his half brother as a possible successor to the throne. Instead the queens brother Nikodije Lunjevica and [[Prince Mirko of Montenegro]], who was married to [[Natalija Konstantinovi\u0107]] (granddaughter of [[Princess Anka Obrenovi\u0107]]) were talked of as being named the heir.\n\nAfter the regicide of his half brother King Alexander and his consort Queen Draga in 1903 the throne of Serbia was offered to Prince [[Peter I of Serbia|Peter Karageorgevich]] whose family had a decades long feud with the Obrenovi\u0107\u2019s over the throne. As the sole male line descendant of the Obrenovi\u0107\u2019s, George\u2019s guardian Count Eugene claimed that his father King Milan had legally adopted him and as such this was enough to legitimise him, and his claims to the throne and make him the heir to his father and half brother.<ref name=MDF1903/> George had support within Serbia in the aftermath of the regicide with his supporters posting proclamations in Belgrade and fighting with supporters of the newly elected king, Peter Karageorgevich.<ref>{{Citation | title = Peter Accepts | newspaper = The Chenango Semi-Weekly Telegraph | pages = 4 | date = 17 June 1903 }}</ref> Although there were reports that George and his mother were to cross over into Serbia nothing came of this<ref>{{Citation | title = The Porte Notified | newspaper = The Deseret News | pages = 1 | date = 16 June 1903 }}</ref> and the Ottoman sultan advised his mother that he should be kept off the streets over fears that he would be assassinated.<ref>{{Citation | title = Fears attempt to kill young Milan | newspaper = Easton Free Press | pages = 1 | date = 17 June 1903 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1906, three years after the death of his half brother and the accession of King Peter Karageorgevich, George made an unsuccessful attempt to gain the throne of Serbia.<ref name=adg>{{Cite book | title = [[Almanach de Gotha]] | publisher = Almanach de Gotha | volume = 1 |edition=186th | year = 2003 | pages = 349}}</ref> In June while studying in [[Klausenburg]], [[Kingdom of Hungary|Hungary]] a dispute in a coffee shop led to a [[duel]] with swords being fought between George and a university student. Although he survived the duel he came off worse sustaining injuries to his head, shoulder and breast.<ref>{{Citation | title = King's son is wounded in duel with student |page=4 | newspaper = [[The Washington Times]] | date = 19 June 1906 }}</ref> He suffered a further blow at the end of that year when his guardian Count Eugene Zichy died on Boxing Day<ref>{{Citation | title = Count Eugene Zichy | newspaper = [[New York Times]] | date = 27 December 1906 }}</ref> leaving George little in his will having used his own money to support his pretensions, as King Milan had left nothing to his son.<ref name=MDF1908/> All was not lost however as he still had a large inheritance to look forward to from his grandfather in Constantinople.\n\n==Fall into obscurity==\n\nBack in the Ottoman capital in February 1907 George survived an assassination attempt when a man wielding a dagger attempted to stab him in his chest, however he escaped with just a scratch after the dagger hit a thick pocket book he was carrying.<ref>{{Citation | title = Tries to kill Milan's son | newspaper = [[New York Times]] | date = 7 February 1907 }}</ref> Five months later in July 1907 a bomb went off outside the US Embassy in Constantinople. As George lived in a house adjoining the embassy word spread that it was an assassination attempt by agents of King Peter Karageorgevich. This explanation for the bombing was met with some scepticism and viewed by some as an attempt to use the explosion to keep George in the public eye.<ref>{{Citation | title = Bomb not for Leishman | newspaper = [[The Baltimore Sun]] | pages = 7 | date = 17 July 1908 }}</ref> The following month it was reported that he had attempted to take his own life after the Ottoman authorities had refused to allow him to assume the surname Obrenovi\u0107.<ref>{{Citation | title = Cable News | volume = XXIX | issue = 7268 | newspaper = [[Ashburton Guardian]] | pages = 2 | date = 8 January 1898 }}</ref> There may however have been other issues on his mind as an investigation into the bombing concluded that George had set it up himself to make it look like an attempt on his life. As a result, he was expelled from Turkey by the Sultan. The discovery also cost George his inheritance from his grandfather who was furious at his grandson's actions and wrote him out of his will. His grandfather died later that year before any chance for reconciliation could ever take place.<ref name=MDF1908/>\n         \nNow banished from Turkey George made his way to Paris before heading to [[Austria-Hungary]] where he received some support from his late father\u2019s friends<ref name=MDF1908/> who saw the potential that he may one day ascend the Serbian throne.<ref name=spencer>{{Citation |last= Spencer |first=James | title = Traded claim to throne to lead life of dishonour | newspaper = [[The Atlanta Constitution]] | pages = B1 | date = 18 April 1909 }}</ref> To help boost his finances failed attempts were also made to secure a rich wife from Austria-Hungary or America for him. When the support came to an end he largely disappeared from view travelling around Europe and falling into debt.<ref name=spencer/> Eventually he fell into comparative poverty and tried his hand at a number of different jobs to survive.<ref name=miami>{{Citation | title = Son of King Milan is waiter on dining car | newspaper = [[The Miami News]] | pages = 7 | date = 19 August 1916 }}</ref> After his attempt to work in the Austro-Hungarian state ministries failed due to his lack of qualifications, he worked at various jobs such as a stable boy and professional jockey<ref name=last>{{Citation | title = Last Obronovitch Dies | newspaper = [[New York Times]] | date = 11 October 1925 }}</ref> before trying his hand at singing in caf\u00e9s<ref>{{Citation | title = King's son a cafe singer | newspaper = [[New York Times]] | date = 28 January 1909 }}</ref> and on stage, until he was forced to abandon that career by the police due to the fact he had been billing himself as a prince.<ref name=miami/> He then went on to work as a waiter, and a porter in sleeping cars on the [[Orient Express]].<ref name=last/> His name reappeared in connection to his old pretensions during [[World War I]] when it was falsely reported in January 1916 that he had been proclaimed [[King of Serbia]] by the Germans and Austro-Hungarians.<ref>{{Citation | title = Proclaim new Serb King?; Italian Story That Teutons Have Chosen Natural Son of Milan | newspaper = [[New York Times]] | date = 13 January 1916 }}</ref>\n\nGeorge later went on to become a writer, however the only book he ever wrote, which was about the life of his father King Milan, was suppressed by the Serbian government. George Obrenovi\u0107 died penniless in a Hungarian [[poorhouse]] on 9 October 1925.<ref name=last/>\n\n==Possible descendants==\n\nAccording to a 2003 article by the Serbian media company [[Novosti AD]], George had a son called Stefan who served as a cavalry captain in the [[French Army]]. Stefan in turn had a son named Panta (Panka) Obrenovi\u0107 (also known as Mark Eme) who served as chairman of the \"Fund Obrenovi\u0107\" until his death in [[Paris]] in early 2002.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nasle\u0111e umesto krune |author=Milorad BO\u0160NJAK |url=http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/naslovna/aktuelno.69.html:143406-Nasle273e-umesto-krune |newspaper=[[Novosti AD]] |date=11 January 2003 |accessdate=12 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:George Obrenovic}}\n[[Category:1890 births]]\n[[Category:1925 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Belgrade]]\n[[Category:People from the Kingdom of Serbia]]\n[[Category:Pretenders to the Serbian throne]]\n[[Category:Obrenovi\u0107 dynasty]]\n[[Category:Serbian writers]]\n[[Category:Illegitimate children of monarchs]]\n[[Category:Duellists]]\n[[Category:Serbian people of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:Writers from Belgrade]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Obrenovi%C4%87"}
{"title_page": "Niniwa Heremaia", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=November 2016}}\n{{orphan|date=April 2011}}\n'''Niniwa Heremaia''' or '''Niniwa-i-te-rangi''' (6 Apr 1854 \u2013 23 Mar 1929) was a [[M\u0101ori people|Maori]] leader in [[New Zealand]].\n\nIn 1898 during Parliament's Native Affairs Committee inquiry into [[Maori Land Act|Maori land]] legislation, she was the only woman to give evidence.<ref name=NZ>{{cite web|last=Ministry for Culture and Heritage|title=Niniwa Heremaia|url=http://www.nzhistory.net.nz/people/niniwa-heremaia|accessdate=24 April 2011}}</ref>  She was involved with the formation of several newspapers. The ''Te Puke ki Hikurangi'' and ''Te Tiupiri'' published in Maori and the ''Maori Record'', an English-language paper for Maori advancement.<ref name=\"DNZB \">{{DNZB|title=Niniwa-i-te-rangi |first= Angela|last= Ballara|id=2n15|accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heremaia, Niniwa}}\n[[Category:1854 births]]\n[[Category:1929 deaths]]\n[[Category:M\u0101ori activists]]\n[[Category:People from Greytown, New Zealand]]\n[[Category:New Zealand women in politics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=November 2016}}\n{{orphan|date=April 2011}}\n'''Niniwa Heremaia''' or '''Niniwa-i-te-rangi''' (6 Apr 1854 \u2013 23 Mar 1929) was a [[M\u0101ori people|Maori]] leader in [[New Zealand]].\n\nIn 1898 during Parliament\u2019s Native Affairs Committee inquiry into [[Maori Land Act|Maori land]] legislation, she was the only woman to give evidence.<ref name=NZ>{{cite web|last=Ministry for Culture and Heritage|title=Niniwa Heremaia|url=http://www.nzhistory.net.nz/people/niniwa-heremaia|accessdate=24 April 2011}}</ref>  She was involved with the formation of several newspapers. The ''Te Puke ki Hikurangi'' and ''Te Tiupiri'' published in Maori and the ''Maori Record'', an English-language paper for Maori advancement.<ref name=\"DNZB \">{{DNZB|title=Niniwa-i-te-rangi |first= Angela|last= Ballara|id=2n15|accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heremaia, Niniwa}}\n[[Category:1854 births]]\n[[Category:1929 deaths]]\n[[Category:M\u0101ori activists]]\n[[Category:People from Greytown, New Zealand]]\n[[Category:New Zealand women in politics]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Niniwa_Heremaia"}
{"title_page": "SS Op Ten Noort", "text_new": "{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image=File:S.S. Op ten Noort van de KPM, Bestanddeelnr 935-3124.jpg\n| Ship caption=SS Op Ten Noort as passenger ship\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header=\n| Ship country= \n| Ship flag= {{NLD}}\n| Ship name=\n*SS ''Op Ten Noort'' \n* (after stolen: HMHS ''Tenno Maru'')\n*(Before sinking HMHS ''Hikawa Maru No.2'')\n| Ship namesake= \n*Up North \n* (Emperor Circle)\n*([[Hikawa Shrine (Saitama)|Hikawa Shrine, Saitama]])\n| Ship owner=[[Koninklijke Paketvaart-Maatschappij]]\n| Ship operator=\n*Koninklijke Paketvaart-Maatschappij\n*[[Royal Netherlands Navy]] \n*[[Imperial Japanese Navy]] \n| Ship registry=\n| Ship route=\n| Ship ordered=\n| Ship awarded=\n| Ship builder= [[Nederlandsche Scheepsbouw Maatschappij]]\n| Ship original cost=\n| Ship yard number=\n| Ship way number= \n| Ship laid down= \n| Ship launched= February 12, 1927  \n| Ship sponsor=\n| Ship christened=\n| Ship completed= 1927 \n| Ship acquired=\n| Ship commissioned= February 14 1942 as hospital ship\n| Ship decommissioned=\n| Ship in service=\n| Ship out of service=\n| Ship renamed=\n| Ship reclassified=\n| Ship refit=\n| Ship struck=\n| Ship reinstated=\n| Ship homeport=\n| Ship identification=PKEA\n| Ship motto=  \n| Ship nickname=\n| Ship honors=\n| Ship captured=\n| Ship fate=17 August 1945 Scuttled at Wakasa Bay to cover up war crimes\n| Ship notes=\n| Ship badge=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header=\n| Header caption=\n| Ship class=  \n| Ship tonnage=\n| Ship displacement={{convert|6076|LT|MT}}\n| Ship height=\n|Ship length={{Convert|129.5|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{Convert|16.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship draft= {{Convert|6.7|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship depth=\n| Ship hold depth=\n| Ship decks=\n| Ship deck clearance=\n| Ship power=5 Coal boilers \n| Ship propulsion= \n*Two [[Hugo Lentz]] [[Reciprocating engine]]s [[Steam engine|steam]]\n*{{Convert|6000|hp|abbr=on}}\n*Two screws\n| Ship speed={{Convert|15|kn|lk=in}}\n| Ship range=\n| Ship endurance=\n| Ship boats=14 Life boats\n| Ship capacity=\n| Ship troops=\n| Ship complement=\n| Ship crew=162\n| Ship time to activate=\n| Ship sensors=\n| Ship EW=\n| Ship armament=none\n| Ship armor=\n| Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n[[File:Mailboot SS Op ten Noord van de KPM in de haven van Tandjong Priok, Bestanddeelnr 934-8087.jpg|right|thumb|SS ''Op ten Noord'' in 1931 at [[Tanjung Priok]] in Indonesia, Dutch East Indies]]\n[[File:Het passagiersschip s.s. Op ten Noort van de Koninklijke Paketvaart Mij. (KPM), Bestanddeelnr 935-3116.jpg|right|thumb|SS ''Op ten Noort'' as passenger ship of [[Koninklijke Paketvaart-Maatschappij]] in the port of Surabaya Annotation in 1941]]\n[[File:StateLibQld 1 148207 Op Ten Noort (ship).jpg|right|thumb|SS ''Op ten Noort'']]\n\nThe '''SS ''Op ten Noort''''' was a luxury [[Passenger ship]] built by [[Nederlandsche Scheepsbouw Maatschappij]] in [[Amsterdam]], [[Netherlands]] and completed in 1927. The ship was built for and owned by [[Koninklijke Paketvaart-Maatschappij]] (Royal Packet Navigation Company). Op ten Noort means ''Up North''. In December of 1941 she became a [[Royal Netherlands Navy]] [[hospital ship]]. The [[Empire of Japan]] shortly after her conversion stole the ship and renamed her the '''HMHS ''Tenno Maru''''' Before sinking her, she was renamed again to the '''HMHS ''Hikawa Maru No.2''''', after the [[Hikawa Shrine (Saitama)|Hikawa Shrine, Saitama]]. To cover up the [[Japanese war crimes|war crimes]] against the ship and her medical crew, at the end of the war she was sunk on August 17, 1945.<ref>[http://ssmaritime.com/SS-Op-Ten-Noort-plan.htm SS ''Op ten Noort, plans]</ref> \n\n==Dutch East Indies==\nAs a luxury Passenger ship, the ''Op ten Noort'' was put to service in the what was called [[Dutch East Indies]], now [[Indonesia]]. Koninklijke Paketvaart Maatschappij headquarters were in [[Java]] at this time. ''Op ten Noort'' moved both passengers and [[cargo]] on the very profitable routes. On November 9, 1927 she had here [[List of maiden voyages|maid voyage]].  Her 1927 route was from [[Singapore]] to [[Bangkok]] to [[Saigon]] to [[Manila]] to [[Maluku Island]] to [[Bali]] to [[Jakarta]]. A few years the route changed to [[Java]] to [[Batavia, Dutch East Indies|Batavia]] to [[Muntok]] to [[Belawan]] to [[Deli Serdang Regency]]. ''Op ten Noort'' had a sister ship, the SS Plancius operated in the [[South Pacific Ocean|South Pacific]] also. For fourteen years she serviced these towns as luxury ship. The 130 [[First class travel|First Class]] [[Cabin (ship)|cabins]] had access to lounges, bars, smoking room and a Tropical [[Verandah]]. For the very wealthy there were two Deluxe Suites with lounge, bedroom, two bathrooms, private deck (Veranda).  She had 18 [[Travel class|Second Class]] 18 cabins. They was for day passenger a [[Tweendeck]] and a [[cafeteria]].\n\n==World war 2==\nWith the outbreak of [[World war 2]] the SS ''Op Ten Noort'' was taken over by the Royal Dutch Navy in December of 1941 as she docked in Jakarta. There she was refit into a hospital ship. She was painted all white ship, with huge red crosses. The Dutch Government officially reported the [[Japanese Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] at the [[Swedish embassy]] in [[Tokyo]] of the change to SS ''Op Ten Noort''. She was now an operational hospital ship, as thus would not be part of the war effort, that is would not transport any weapons or active troops. On February 4, 1942 The Japanese Ministry of Foreign Affairs and [[Ministry of the Navy (Japan)|Naval Ministry]] acknowledges ''Op Ten Noort'' status change though the Swedish embassy. On February 21, 1941, completed she departed on her first trip to help wounded [[Allies of World War II|allies]]. But only a few hours out of port, the ''Op Ten Noort'' was bombed by the Empire of Japan in the [[Java Sea]]. One surgeon and three nurses were killed, eleven were badly wounded. Dutch Government sent a strong note of protest of the bombing to the Japan, through the Embassy of Sweden. After repairs, on 28 February 1942 she was commandeered by the [[Japanese destroyer Amatsukaze (1939)|Japanese destroyer Amatsukaze]] near [[Bawean Island]], stopping her rescue work again. Japanese forced her crew to transport their [[POW]]s to [[List of Japanese-run internment camps during World War II|Japan POW camps]]. The first POW move was that of 59 POWs from the [[USS Perch (SS-176)|USS ''Perch'']] that were on the [[Japanese destroyer Ushio (1930)|Japanese destroyer ''Ushi'']]. By the end of March 1942 she had 970 POWs, most from the 800 survivors from [[HMS Exeter (68)|HMS ''Exeter'']] that sank on March 1, 1942. The [[Prisoner of war|prisoners of war]] were kept in very poor conditions and feed only a cup of rice a day, called [[List of Japanese hell ships|Japanese hell ships]].  <ref>[https://www.britain-at-war.org.uk/WW2/Alf_King/html/japanese_pow.htm Japanese POW by Alf King]</ref> On 20 December 1942 she became the HMHS ''Tenno Maru'' an official Japanese Hospital Ship. The Dutch ship crew was taken off the ship and became POWs at Camp Myoshi, near [[Yokohama]]. Japan had signed the [[Hague Convention of 1907|Hague Convention X of 1907]] that stated attacking a hospital ship is a war crime.<ref name=\"hague10\">{{cite web |date= October 18, 1907|url = http://avalon.law.yale.edu/20th_century/hague10.asp|title = Convention for the adaptation to maritime war of the principles of the Geneva Convention|publisher = [[Yale University]]| accessdate = August 2, 2009 | last= |quote=}}</ref><ref>[https://archive.vn/20130616131847/http://www.minbuza.nl/en/key-topics/treaties/search-the-treaty-database/1899/7/002339.html Convention for the adaptation to maritime warfare of the principles of the Geneva Convention of 22 August 1864]</ref><ref>[http://www.combinedfleet.com/Hikawa2_t.htm combinedfleet.com ''Hikawa Maru No.2''] </ref>\n\nWith the war coming to an end, the ship was changed in October of 1944. A second dummy smokestack was added to \"hide her\". She was renamed the HMHS ''Hikawa Maru No.2''. She both served as a hospital ship and transport war cargo. For the latter part of 1944 and into 1945 she traveled from Singapore and Manila with a cargo of looted gold and other valuable Japanese conquests. The weeks before Japan surrender she arrived in Japan with gold, platinum, diamonds and gems. On August 15, 1945, the Japanese officially announce surrender. To cover up the war crimes and to hide the stolen loot, the ship was sunk on August 17, 1945, at [[Wakasa Bay]] in 400 feet of water. To sink her two 328 pound explosive charges were place in the bottom of the hull. To complete the hiding of the crime and the loot the crew that placed the bombs were killed on site. <ref>[http://ssmaritime.com/SS-Op-Ten-Noort.htm ssmaritime.com, Royal Netherlands Navy hospital ship ''Op ten Nothort'']</ref><ref>[http://www.netherlandsnavy.nl/Noort.htm Netherlands Navy ''Op ten Noort'']</ref> On 17 August 1945 the ship was scuttled at Wakasa Bay by placing explosive charges in the hull, to cover up the war crimes. <ref name=\"wrecksite.Hikawa Maru No.2\">{{cite web |year= 2011 |url = http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?59646|title = SS Hikawa Maru No.2 (+1945)| format = |publisher = wrecksite| accessdate = November 9, 2011 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"combinedfleet. Hikawa Maru 2\">{{cite web |year= 2010 |url = http://www.combinedfleet.com/Hikawa2_t.htm|title = IJN Hospital Ship HIKAWA MARU NO. 2 |publisher = combinedfleet.com | accessdate = November 9, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Post war==\nThe Netherlands thought the ''Op Ten Noort'' sank as the HMHS ''Tenno Maru HMHS'' near [[Makassar]] by a [[sea mine]]. Not knowing about the ''Hikawa Maru No.2'' plot.  In 1952 the ''Op Ten Noort'' was found after port area of Chinju Prefecture had a salvage investigations done. Professional diver from Kyoto, Mr. Shinta Koyua, photographed the wreck and it was identified as the lost ''Op Ten Noort''. In the 1953, the Dutch Government filed 700 million Yen claim against the Japan for compensation. After years of talks in the end 100 million Yen ($500,000) were paid to the Dutch Government in 1978. Info about the loot in the shipwreck is not public.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{August 1945 shipwrecks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anne Hutchinson}}\n[[Category:1927 ships]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in August 1945]]\n[[Category:Hospital ships| ]]\n[[Category:Japanese war crimes]]\n", "text_old": "{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image=File:S.S. Op ten Noort van de KPM, Bestanddeelnr 935-3124.jpg\n| Ship caption=SS Op Ten Noort as passenger ship\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header=\n| Ship country= \n| Ship flag= {{NLD}}\n| Ship name=\n*SS ''Op Ten Noort'' \n* (after stolen: HMHS ''Tenno Maru'')\n*(Before sinking HMHS ''Hikawa Maru No.2'')\n| Ship namesake= \n*Up North \n* (Emperor Circle)\n*([[Hikawa Shrine (Saitama)|Hikawa Shrine, Saitama]])\n| Ship owner=[[Koninklijke Paketvaart-Maatschappij]]\n| Ship operator=\n*Koninklijke Paketvaart-Maatschappij\n*[[Royal Netherlands Navy]] \n*[[Imperial Japanese Navy]] \n| Ship registry=\n| Ship route=\n| Ship ordered=\n| Ship awarded=\n| Ship builder= [[Nederlandsche Scheepsbouw Maatschappij]]\n| Ship original cost=\n| Ship yard number=\n| Ship way number= \n| Ship laid down= \n| Ship launched= February 12, 1927  \n| Ship sponsor=\n| Ship christened=\n| Ship completed= 1927 \n| Ship acquired=\n| Ship commissioned= February 14 1942 as hospital ship\n| Ship decommissioned=\n| Ship in service=\n| Ship out of service=\n| Ship renamed=\n| Ship reclassified=\n| Ship refit=\n| Ship struck=\n| Ship reinstated=\n| Ship homeport=\n| Ship identification=PKEA\n| Ship motto=  \n| Ship nickname=\n| Ship honors=\n| Ship captured=\n| Ship fate=17 August 1945 Scuttled at Wakasa Bay to cover up war crimes\n| Ship notes=\n| Ship badge=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header=\n| Header caption=\n| Ship class=  \n| Ship tonnage=\n| Ship displacement={{convert|6076|LT|MT}}\n| Ship height=\n|Ship length={{Convert|129.5|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{Convert|16.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship draft= {{Convert|6.7|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship depth=\n| Ship hold depth=\n| Ship decks=\n| Ship deck clearance=\n| Ship power=5 Coal boilers \n| Ship propulsion= \n*Two [[Hugo Lentz]] [[Reciprocating engine]]s [[Steam engine|steam]]\n*{{Convert|6000|hp|abbr=on}}\n*Two screws\n| Ship speed={{Convert|15|kn|lk=in}}\n| Ship range=\n| Ship endurance=\n| Ship boats=14 Life boats\n| Ship capacity=\n| Ship troops=\n| Ship complement=\n| Ship crew=162\n| Ship time to activate=\n| Ship sensors=\n| Ship EW=\n| Ship armament=none\n| Ship armor=\n| Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n[[File:Mailboot SS Op ten Noord van de KPM in de haven van Tandjong Priok, Bestanddeelnr 934-8087.jpg|right|thumb|SS ''Op ten Noord'' in 1931 at [[Tanjung Priok]] in Indonesia, Dutch East Indies]]\n[[File:Het passagiersschip s.s. Op ten Noort van de Koninklijke Paketvaart Mij. (KPM), Bestanddeelnr 935-3116.jpg|right|thumb|SS ''Op ten Noort'' as passenger ship of [[Koninklijke Paketvaart-Maatschappij]] in the port of Surabaya Annotation in 1941]]\n[[File:StateLibQld 1 148207 Op Ten Noort (ship).jpg|right|thumb|SS ''Op ten Noort'']]\n\nThe '''SS ''Op ten Noort''''' was a luxury [[Passenger ship]] built by [[Nederlandsche Scheepsbouw Maatschappij]] in [[Amsterdam]], [[Netherlands]] and completed in 1927. The ship was built for and owned by [[Koninklijke Paketvaart-Maatschappij]] (Royal Packet Navigation Company). Op ten Noort means ''Up North''. In December of 1941 she became a [[Royal Netherlands Navy]] [[hospital ship]]. The [[Empire of Japan]] shortly after her conversion stole the ship and renamed her the '''HMHS ''Tenno Maru''''' Before sinking her, she was renamed again to the '''HMHS ''Hikawa Maru No.2''''', after the [[Hikawa Shrine (Saitama)|Hikawa Shrine, Saitama]]. To cover up the [[Japanese war crimes|war crimes]] against the ship and her medical crew, at the end of the war she was sunk on August 17, 1945.<ref>[http://ssmaritime.com/SS-Op-Ten-Noort-plan.htm SS ''Op ten Noort, plans]</ref> \n\n==Dutch East Indies==\nAs a luxury Passenger ship, the ''Op ten Noort'' was put to service in the what was called [[Dutch East Indies]], now [[Indonesia]]. Koninklijke Paketvaart Maatschappij headquarters were in [[Java]] at this time. ''Op ten Noort'' moved both passengers and [[cargo]] on the very profitable routes. On November 9, 1927 she had here [[List of maiden voyages|maid voyage]].  Her 1927 route was from [[Singapore]] to [[Bangkok]] to [[Saigon]] to [[Manila]] to [[Maluku Island]] to [[Bali]] to [[Jakarta]]. A few years the route changed to [[Java]] to [[Batavia, Dutch East Indies|Batavia]] to [[Muntok]] to [[Belawan]] to [[Deli Serdang Regency]]. ''Op ten Noort'' had a sister ship, the SS Plancius operated in the [[South Pacific Ocean|South Pacific]] also. For fourteen years she serviced these towns as luxury ship. The 130 [[First class travel|First Class]] [[Cabin (ship)|cabins]] had access to lounges, bars, smoking room and a Tropical [[Verandah]]. For the very wealthy there were two Deluxe Suites with lounge, bedroom, two bathrooms, private deck (Veranda).  She had 18 [[Travel class|Second Class]] 18 cabins. They was for day passenger a [[Tweendeck]] and a [[cafeteria]].\n\n==World war 2==\nWith the outbreak of [[World war 2]] the SS ''Op Ten Noort'' was taken over by the Royal Dutch Navy in December of 1941 as she docked in Jakarta. There she was refit into a hospital ship. She was painted all white ship, with huge red crosses. The Dutch Government officially reported the [[Japanese Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] at the [[Swedish embassy]] in [[Tokyo]] of the change to SS ''Op Ten Noort''. She was now an operational hospital ship, as thus would not be part of the war effort, that is would not transport any weapons or active troops. On February 4, 1942 The Japanese Ministry of Foreign Affairs and [[Ministry of the Navy (Japan)|Naval Ministry]] acknowledges ''Op Ten Noort'' status change though the Swedish embassy. On February 21, 1941, completed she departed on her first trip to help wounded [[Allies of World War II|allies]]. But only a few hours out of port, the ''Op Ten Noort'' was bombed by the Empire of Japan in the [[Java Sea]]. One surgeon and three nurses were killed, eleven were badly wounded. Dutch Government sent a strong note of protest of the bombing to the Japan, through the Embassy of Sweden. After repairs, on 28 February 1942 she was commandeered by the [[Japanese destroyer Amatsukaze (1939)|Japanese destroyer Amatsukaze]] near [[Bawean Island]], stopping her rescue work again. Japanese forced her crew to transport their [[POW]]s to [[List of Japanese-run internment camps during World War II|Japan POW camps]]. The first POW move was that of 59 POWs from the [[USS Perch (SS-176)|USS ''Perch'']] that were on the [[Japanese destroyer Ushio (1930)|Japanese destroyer ''Ushi'']]. By the end of March 1942 she had 970 POWs, most from the 800 survivors from [[HMS Exeter (68)|HMS ''Exeter'']] that sank on March 1, 1942. The [[Prisoner of war|prisoners of war]] were kept in very poor conditions and feed only a cup of rice a day.  <ref>[https://www.britain-at-war.org.uk/WW2/Alf_King/html/japanese_pow.htm Japanese POW by Alf King]</ref> On 20 December 1942 she became the HMHS ''Tenno Maru'' an official Japanese Hospital Ship. The Dutch ship crew was taken off the ship and became POWs at Camp Myoshi, near [[Yokohama]]. Japan had signed the [[Hague Convention of 1907|Hague Convention X of 1907]] that stated attacking a hospital ship is a war crime.<ref name=\"hague10\">{{cite web |date= October 18, 1907|url = http://avalon.law.yale.edu/20th_century/hague10.asp|title = Convention for the adaptation to maritime war of the principles of the Geneva Convention|publisher = [[Yale University]]| accessdate = August 2, 2009 | last= |quote=}}</ref><ref>[https://archive.vn/20130616131847/http://www.minbuza.nl/en/key-topics/treaties/search-the-treaty-database/1899/7/002339.html Convention for the adaptation to maritime warfare of the principles of the Geneva Convention of 22 August 1864]</ref><ref>[http://www.combinedfleet.com/Hikawa2_t.htm combinedfleet.com ''Hikawa Maru No.2''] </ref>\n\nWith the war coming to an end, the ship was changed in October of 1944. A second dummy smokestack was added to \"hide her\". She was renamed the HMHS ''Hikawa Maru No.2''. She both served as a hospital ship and transport war cargo. For the latter part of 1944 and into 1945 she traveled from Singapore and Manila with a cargo of looted gold and other valuable Japanese conquests. The weeks before Japan surrender she arrived in Japan with gold, platinum, diamonds and gems. On August 15, 1945, the Japanese officially announce surrender. To cover up the war crimes and to hide the stolen loot, the ship was sunk on August 17, 1945, at [[Wakasa Bay]] in 400 feet of water. To sink her two 328 pound explosive charges were place in the bottom of the hull. To complete the hiding of the crime and the loot the crew that placed the bombs were killed on site. <ref>[http://ssmaritime.com/SS-Op-Ten-Noort.htm ssmaritime.com, Royal Netherlands Navy hospital ship ''Op ten Nothort'']</ref><ref>[http://www.netherlandsnavy.nl/Noort.htm Netherlands Navy ''Op ten Noort'']</ref> On 17 August 1945 the ship was scuttled at Wakasa Bay by placing explosive charges in the hull, to cover up the war crimes. <ref name=\"wrecksite.Hikawa Maru No.2\">{{cite web |year= 2011 |url = http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?59646|title = SS Hikawa Maru No.2 (+1945)| format = |publisher = wrecksite| accessdate = November 9, 2011 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"combinedfleet. Hikawa Maru 2\">{{cite web |year= 2010 |url = http://www.combinedfleet.com/Hikawa2_t.htm|title = IJN Hospital Ship HIKAWA MARU NO. 2 |publisher = combinedfleet.com | accessdate = November 9, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Post war==\nThe Netherlands thought the ''Op Ten Noort'' sank as the HMHS ''Tenno Maru HMHS'' near [[Makassar]] by a [[sea mine]]. Not knowing about the ''Hikawa Maru No.2'' plot.  In 1952 the ''Op Ten Noort'' was found after port area of Chinju Prefecture had a salvage investigations done. Professional diver from Kyoto, Mr. Shinta Koyua, photographed the wreck and it was identified as the lost ''Op Ten Noort''. In the 1953, the Dutch Government filed 700 million Yen claim against the Japan for compensation. After years of talks in the end 100 million Yen ($500,000) were paid to the Dutch Government in 1978. Info about the loot in the shipwreck is not public.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{August 1945 shipwrecks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anne Hutchinson}}\n[[Category:1927 ships]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in August 1945]]\n[[Category:Hospital ships| ]]\n[[Category:Japanese war crimes]]\n", "name_user": "Telecineguy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWorld war 2:Japanese hell ships", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SS_Op_Ten_Noort"}
